00:07:56.370 --> 00:07:58.260
So let's talk about ADHD,

00:07:58.260 --> 00:08:00.960
Attention Deficit Hyperactivity Disorder.

00:08:00.960 --> 00:08:03.280
Let's also talk about focus and attention

00:08:03.280 --> 00:08:06.120
and everybody's ability
to focus and attend

00:08:06.120 --> 00:08:08.570
not just people with ADHD.

00:08:08.570 --> 00:08:10.150
We are also going to talk about tools

00:08:10.150 --> 00:08:11.820
that would allow anyone,

00:08:11.820 --> 00:08:13.950
whether or not they have ADHD or not

00:08:13.950 --> 00:08:16.943
to enhance their level of
concentration and focus.

00:08:18.030 --> 00:08:23.030
Now, ADHD used to be called
ADD Attention Deficit Disorder.

00:08:24.119 --> 00:08:27.910
We have record of ADD in
the medical literature

00:08:27.910 --> 00:08:30.640
dating back to as early as 1904.

00:08:30.640 --> 00:08:32.670
Now there's nothing special about 1904.

00:08:32.670 --> 00:08:34.110
That's just the first
time that it showed up

00:08:34.110 --> 00:08:36.760
in the standard medical literature.

00:08:36.760 --> 00:08:39.240
We have to believe that ADD,

00:08:39.240 --> 00:08:43.350
which we now call ADHD existed before 1904

00:08:43.350 --> 00:08:47.170
and probably long before 1904, why?

00:08:47.170 --> 00:08:50.260
Well, because it has a
strong genetic component.

00:08:50.260 --> 00:08:53.840
If you have a close
relative that has ADHD,

00:08:53.840 --> 00:08:57.280
there's a much higher probability
that you will have ADHD

00:08:57.280 --> 00:09:00.010
and that probability goes
up depending on how closely

00:09:00.010 --> 00:09:02.090
related to that person you happen to be.

00:09:02.090 --> 00:09:02.923
So for instance,

00:09:02.923 --> 00:09:06.810
if you're an identical twin
and your twin has ADHD,

00:09:06.810 --> 00:09:09.880
there's a very high concordance as we say,

00:09:09.880 --> 00:09:12.890
a very high probability
that you will have ADHD

00:09:12.890 --> 00:09:15.250
up to 75% chance.

00:09:15.250 --> 00:09:17.150
If you have a fraternal twin with ADHD,

00:09:17.150 --> 00:09:20.620
that number goes down a
bit in the 50 to 60% range

00:09:20.620 --> 00:09:21.550
and so on.

00:09:21.550 --> 00:09:23.600
If you have a parent with ADHD,

00:09:23.600 --> 00:09:26.860
that number ranges anywhere
from 10 to 25% likelihood,

00:09:26.860 --> 00:09:28.740
that you will have ADHD
if you have two parents

00:09:28.740 --> 00:09:30.260
and so on and so on, okay?

00:09:30.260 --> 00:09:31.750
So there's a genetic component

00:09:31.750 --> 00:09:33.440
that genetic component it turns out,

00:09:33.440 --> 00:09:36.330
relates directly to how
specific neural circuits

00:09:36.330 --> 00:09:37.990
in the brain wire up,

00:09:37.990 --> 00:09:41.240
the chemicals they use and the
way they use those chemicals,

00:09:41.240 --> 00:09:44.253
a topic that we are going
to discuss in depth today.

00:09:45.270 --> 00:09:48.150
Now, if you have a close
relative with ADHD,

00:09:48.150 --> 00:09:51.500
that does not mean that
you are faded to have ADHD

00:09:51.500 --> 00:09:53.860
and if you happen to have ADHD,

00:09:53.860 --> 00:09:56.670
there are ways to overcome those symptoms

00:09:56.670 --> 00:10:00.140
of lack of attention,
impulsivity and so on.

00:10:00.140 --> 00:10:03.470
Another important point about ADHD

00:10:03.470 --> 00:10:06.470
is that it has nothing
to do with intelligence,

00:10:06.470 --> 00:10:08.140
whether or not we're
talking about intelligence

00:10:08.140 --> 00:10:10.164
measured by a standard IQ test

00:10:10.164 --> 00:10:13.040
a rather controversial issue
as many of you probably know,

00:10:13.040 --> 00:10:15.390
there are lots of forms of intelligence

00:10:15.390 --> 00:10:18.430
that a standard IQ test
just wouldn't pick up

00:10:18.430 --> 00:10:20.230
emotional intelligence,
musical intelligence,

00:10:20.230 --> 00:10:23.283
spatial intelligence, all
sorts of intelligences.

00:10:24.620 --> 00:10:27.890
None of them are related to ADHD.

00:10:27.890 --> 00:10:29.980
Being very high functioning
doesn't make you

00:10:29.980 --> 00:10:33.610
more likely to have ADHD and being ADHD

00:10:33.610 --> 00:10:35.330
doesn't necessarily mean
that you have a low IQ.

00:10:35.330 --> 00:10:37.880
So there are people with
ADHD who have low IQs

00:10:37.880 --> 00:10:39.920
people with ADHD with high IQ,

00:10:39.920 --> 00:10:43.580
people with ADHD with high
emotional IQ or with low IQ

00:10:43.580 --> 00:10:46.630
in the emotional scale,
it's all over the place.

00:10:46.630 --> 00:10:50.040
The important point is that
your ability to attend and focus

00:10:50.040 --> 00:10:55.040
does not relate to how smart
you are or your IQ of any type,

00:10:55.410 --> 00:10:57.060
not just a standard IQ.

00:10:57.060 --> 00:11:00.860
The renaming of the ADD to ADHD took place

00:11:00.860 --> 00:11:03.340
in the mid to late 1980s

00:11:03.340 --> 00:11:05.070
when the psychiatric community

00:11:05.070 --> 00:11:06.920
and the psychological community

00:11:06.920 --> 00:11:10.910
started taking better
notice of the fact that

00:11:10.910 --> 00:11:14.850
so-called hyperactive kids
also had attentional issues.

00:11:14.850 --> 00:11:16.160
This might seem obvious,

00:11:16.160 --> 00:11:19.850
but there's been extensive
and ongoing revision

00:11:19.850 --> 00:11:23.610
of the criteria for designating
a psychiatric disorder

00:11:23.610 --> 00:11:26.253
and this is still an
ongoing process even today.

00:11:27.140 --> 00:11:28.380
So in the mid eighties,

00:11:28.380 --> 00:11:30.090
we started hearing about ADHD

00:11:30.090 --> 00:11:33.150
and then gradually that term
ADD has been dropped away.

00:11:33.150 --> 00:11:37.680
However, just the renaming of ADD to ADHD

00:11:38.550 --> 00:11:43.550
has led to much better
diagnosis and detection of ADHD.

00:11:44.790 --> 00:11:46.900
So right now the current
estimates are that

00:11:46.900 --> 00:11:51.810
about one in 10 children
and probably more have ADHD.

00:11:53.040 --> 00:11:56.810
The current estimates are
anywhere from 10%, one in 10

00:11:56.810 --> 00:11:58.800
to as high as 12%.

00:11:58.800 --> 00:12:00.910
Now, fortunately about half of those

00:12:00.910 --> 00:12:03.740
will resolve with proper treatment,

00:12:03.740 --> 00:12:05.960
but the other half typically don't.

00:12:05.960 --> 00:12:08.700
The other thing that we
are seeing a lot nowadays

00:12:08.700 --> 00:12:13.340
is increased levels of ADHD in adults

00:12:13.340 --> 00:12:15.450
and there's some question
as to whether or not

00:12:15.450 --> 00:12:18.410
those adults had ADHD that went undetected

00:12:18.410 --> 00:12:21.030
during their childhood or whether or not

00:12:21.030 --> 00:12:24.070
ADHD is now cropping up in adulthood

00:12:24.070 --> 00:12:26.940
due to the way that we are
interacting with the world

00:12:26.940 --> 00:12:30.562
in particular smart phone use,

00:12:30.562 --> 00:12:34.563
the combination of email,
text, real-world interactions,

00:12:35.890 --> 00:12:39.640
multiple apps and streams
of media and social media

00:12:39.640 --> 00:12:42.100
all coming in at once
trying to manage life.

00:12:42.100 --> 00:12:44.580
All of the things that are going on

00:12:44.580 --> 00:12:49.130
are creating a kind of cloud
of poles on our attention

00:12:49.130 --> 00:12:51.420
and so there is this
question to whether or not

00:12:51.420 --> 00:12:56.100
we are creating ADHD in
adults that never had ADHD

00:12:56.100 --> 00:12:58.123
prior to being an adult.

00:12:59.100 --> 00:13:00.680
So let's talk about attention

00:13:00.680 --> 00:13:03.891
and first let's just define
what we mean by attention

00:13:03.891 --> 00:13:05.667
out there in the scientific literature

00:13:05.667 --> 00:13:08.180
and in discussions about ADHD,

00:13:08.180 --> 00:13:10.810
we will hear things
like attention and focus

00:13:10.810 --> 00:13:13.570
and concentration and impulse control

00:13:13.570 --> 00:13:15.361
for sake of today's discussion,

00:13:15.361 --> 00:13:17.820
attention, focus, and concentration

00:13:17.820 --> 00:13:20.100
are essentially the same thing, okay?

00:13:20.100 --> 00:13:22.210
We could split hairs and
the scientific literature

00:13:22.210 --> 00:13:23.960
does split hairs about these.

00:13:23.960 --> 00:13:25.730
But if we want to understand the biology

00:13:25.730 --> 00:13:26.750
and we want to have

00:13:26.750 --> 00:13:29.520
a straightforward conversation about ADHD,

00:13:29.520 --> 00:13:31.470
if I say attention or focus,

00:13:31.470 --> 00:13:33.670
I'm basically referring to the same thing,

00:13:33.670 --> 00:13:36.120
unless I specify otherwise, okay?

00:13:36.120 --> 00:13:41.120
So people with ADHD have
trouble holding their attention.

00:13:41.197 --> 00:13:43.710
What is attention?

00:13:43.710 --> 00:13:46.610
Well, attention is perception.

00:13:46.610 --> 00:13:50.550
It's how we are perceiving
the sensory world.

00:13:50.550 --> 00:13:52.650
So just a little bit of neurobiology 101,

00:13:52.650 --> 00:13:54.690
we are sensing things all the time.

00:13:54.690 --> 00:13:56.410
There's information coming
into our nervous system

00:13:56.410 --> 00:13:57.243
all the time.

00:13:57.243 --> 00:13:59.720
For instance, right now
you're hearing sound waves.

00:13:59.720 --> 00:14:00.740
You are seeing things,

00:14:00.740 --> 00:14:02.760
you are sensing things against your skin,

00:14:02.760 --> 00:14:05.765
but you're only paying
attention to some of those

00:14:05.765 --> 00:14:08.690
and the ones that you're
paying attention to

00:14:08.690 --> 00:14:09.830
are your perceptions.

00:14:09.830 --> 00:14:12.880
So if you hear my voice,
you are perceiving my voice.

00:14:12.880 --> 00:14:15.850
You are not paying attention
to your other senses

00:14:15.850 --> 00:14:17.070
at the moment, okay?

00:14:17.070 --> 00:14:18.860
You might even be outside in a breeze

00:14:18.860 --> 00:14:19.890
and until I said that,

00:14:19.890 --> 00:14:21.970
you might not be perceiving that breeze,

00:14:21.970 --> 00:14:23.920
but your body was sensing it all along.

00:14:25.370 --> 00:14:28.360
So attention and focus are
more or less the same thing,

00:14:28.360 --> 00:14:31.310
but impulse control is something
separate because impulse

00:14:31.310 --> 00:14:35.900
control requires pushing out
or putting the blinders on

00:14:35.900 --> 00:14:38.380
to sensory events in our environment.

00:14:38.380 --> 00:14:40.160
It means lack of perception,

00:14:40.160 --> 00:14:43.073
impulse control is about
limiting our perception.

00:14:44.220 --> 00:14:47.630
People with ADHD have poor attention

00:14:47.630 --> 00:14:50.478
and they have high levels of impulsivity

00:14:50.478 --> 00:14:52.550
they're easily distractable.

00:14:52.550 --> 00:14:55.740
But the way that shows
up is very surprising.

00:14:55.740 --> 00:14:58.310
You might think that people with ADHD

00:14:58.310 --> 00:15:00.330
just simply can't attend anything.

00:15:00.330 --> 00:15:01.790
They really can't focus,

00:15:01.790 --> 00:15:05.480
even if they really want to,
but that's simply not the case.

00:15:05.480 --> 00:15:09.650
People with ADHD yes,
they are distractable.

00:15:09.650 --> 00:15:12.050
Yes, they are impulsive.

00:15:12.050 --> 00:15:13.890
Yes, they are easily annoyed

00:15:13.890 --> 00:15:15.490
by things happening in the room.

00:15:15.490 --> 00:15:18.290
They sometimes have a high
level of emotionality as well.

00:15:18.290 --> 00:15:20.010
Not always, but often

00:15:20.010 --> 00:15:24.320
however people with ADHD
can have a hyper focus

00:15:24.320 --> 00:15:27.090
and incredible ability to focus

00:15:27.090 --> 00:15:29.480
on things that they really enjoy

00:15:29.480 --> 00:15:31.820
or and are intrigued by.

00:15:31.820 --> 00:15:33.600
Now, this is a very important point

00:15:33.600 --> 00:15:37.360
because typically we think
of somebody with ADHD

00:15:37.360 --> 00:15:40.100
as being really wild and hyperactive,

00:15:40.100 --> 00:15:43.986
or having no ability whatsoever
to sit still and attend

00:15:43.986 --> 00:15:46.800
and while that phenotype as we call it

00:15:46.800 --> 00:15:51.563
that contour of behavior
and cognition can exist,

00:15:52.500 --> 00:15:55.370
many people, if not all people with ADHD,

00:15:55.370 --> 00:15:57.710
if you give them something
they really love,

00:15:57.710 --> 00:15:59.530
like if the child loves video games

00:15:59.530 --> 00:16:01.340
or if a child loves to draw,

00:16:01.340 --> 00:16:05.480
or if an adult loves a
particular type of movie

00:16:05.480 --> 00:16:10.000
or a person very much, they
will obtain laser-focus

00:16:10.000 --> 00:16:11.680
without any effort.

00:16:11.680 --> 00:16:14.090
So that tells us that people with ADHD

00:16:14.090 --> 00:16:16.280
have the capacity to attend,

00:16:16.280 --> 00:16:19.210
but they can't engage that attention

00:16:19.210 --> 00:16:22.580
for things that they don't
really, really want to do

00:16:22.580 --> 00:16:24.730
and as we all know much of life,

00:16:24.730 --> 00:16:26.610
whether or not you're a child or an adult

00:16:26.610 --> 00:16:28.730
involves doing a lot of things
that we don't want to do,

00:16:28.730 --> 00:16:30.035
much of our schooling
involves doing things

00:16:30.035 --> 00:16:32.440
that we would prefer not to do

00:16:32.440 --> 00:16:35.550
and sort of forcing ourselves
to do it, to attend,

00:16:35.550 --> 00:16:37.420
even though we are not super interested

00:16:37.420 --> 00:16:39.310
in what we are attending to.

00:16:39.310 --> 00:16:40.143
There are a couple other things

00:16:40.143 --> 00:16:43.760
that people with ADHD display quite often.

00:16:43.760 --> 00:16:47.620
One is challenges with time perception.

00:16:47.620 --> 00:16:50.100
Now time perception is
a fascinating aspect

00:16:50.100 --> 00:16:51.080
of how our brain works

00:16:51.080 --> 00:16:53.050
and later we're going to
talk about time perception

00:16:53.050 --> 00:16:56.250
and how you can actually get
better at time perception.

00:16:56.250 --> 00:16:58.960
It's very likely that right
now you are doing things

00:16:58.960 --> 00:17:02.000
that get in the way of
optimal time perception

00:17:02.000 --> 00:17:05.030
and I will tell you how
to adjust your ability

00:17:05.030 --> 00:17:07.863
to measure time with your brain.

00:17:09.000 --> 00:17:12.090
People with ADHD often run late.

00:17:12.090 --> 00:17:14.010
They often procrastinate,

00:17:14.010 --> 00:17:15.700
but what's interesting and surprising

00:17:15.700 --> 00:17:17.950
is that if they are given a deadline,

00:17:17.950 --> 00:17:20.940
they actually can perceive time very well

00:17:20.940 --> 00:17:23.440
and they often can focus very well

00:17:23.440 --> 00:17:26.220
if the consequences of
not completing a task

00:17:26.220 --> 00:17:28.520
or not attending are severe enough.

00:17:28.520 --> 00:17:31.584
It's a little bit like the
way that people with ADHD

00:17:31.584 --> 00:17:34.310
can really focus if they like something.

00:17:34.310 --> 00:17:36.820
Well, if they're scared
enough about the consequences

00:17:36.820 --> 00:17:39.490
of not attending, oftentimes not always,

00:17:39.490 --> 00:17:41.063
but oftentimes they can attend.

00:17:42.680 --> 00:17:44.950
If they're not really
concerned about a deadline

00:17:44.950 --> 00:17:46.361
or a consequence,

00:17:46.361 --> 00:17:48.770
well, then they tend to lose track of time

00:17:48.770 --> 00:17:52.250
and they tend to underestimate
how long things will take.

00:17:52.250 --> 00:17:55.180
Now many people do that,
not just people with ADHD,

00:17:55.180 --> 00:17:58.840
but people with ADHD have challenges,

00:17:58.840 --> 00:18:02.560
understanding how to line up
the activities of their day

00:18:02.560 --> 00:18:04.680
in order to meet particular deadlines

00:18:04.680 --> 00:18:06.150
even if it's just a simple thing,

00:18:06.150 --> 00:18:10.290
like finishing one set
of tasks before lunch,

00:18:10.290 --> 00:18:13.830
oftentimes they will remember
that lunch starts at noon,

00:18:13.830 --> 00:18:16.980
but somehow they aren't able
to fill the intervening time

00:18:16.980 --> 00:18:19.170
in a way that's productive

00:18:19.170 --> 00:18:20.510
and they can obsess about

00:18:20.510 --> 00:18:22.770
the upcoming deadline for instance,

00:18:22.770 --> 00:18:25.080
we will talk about how to remedy this.

00:18:25.080 --> 00:18:25.990
In addition,

00:18:25.990 --> 00:18:30.360
their spatial organization
skills are often subpar,

00:18:30.360 --> 00:18:34.850
not always, but often you will
find that somebody with ADHD

00:18:34.850 --> 00:18:37.170
uses what's called the pile system

00:18:37.170 --> 00:18:39.260
in order to organize things,

00:18:39.260 --> 00:18:41.250
they will take many belongings

00:18:41.250 --> 00:18:43.440
and this could be in the
kitchen or in their bedroom

00:18:43.440 --> 00:18:46.600
or in their office or in any space

00:18:46.600 --> 00:18:48.190
and they will start piling things up

00:18:48.190 --> 00:18:50.060
according to a categorization system

00:18:50.060 --> 00:18:52.410
that makes sense to them and only them.

00:18:52.410 --> 00:18:55.660
It doesn't really have
any logical framework.

00:18:55.660 --> 00:18:57.340
Now, many people use the pile system

00:18:57.340 --> 00:18:58.420
and if you use the pile system,

00:18:58.420 --> 00:18:59.940
that doesn't mean that you have ADHD

00:18:59.940 --> 00:19:01.580
in fact, if you're unpacking a house

00:19:01.580 --> 00:19:03.230
or you've moved recently,

00:19:03.230 --> 00:19:05.750
or you've received a lot
of presence recently,

00:19:05.750 --> 00:19:09.480
the pile system makes perfect
sense to organize your space.

00:19:09.480 --> 00:19:12.230
But people with ADHD
tend to organize things

00:19:12.230 --> 00:19:14.700
according to the pile system all the time

00:19:14.700 --> 00:19:17.700
and that pile system
doesn't work for them.

00:19:17.700 --> 00:19:18.980
Okay, so that's the key distinction

00:19:18.980 --> 00:19:21.440
that they use a filing system,
and it's not really files,

00:19:21.440 --> 00:19:24.250
they're piling things up in a
way that makes sense to them,

00:19:24.250 --> 00:19:27.270
but then it doesn't work for
them in terms of what tasks

00:19:27.270 --> 00:19:29.080
they actually need to perform.

00:19:29.080 --> 00:19:30.560
They can't find things

00:19:30.560 --> 00:19:33.730
or if anyone moves one thing
then it's very disruptive

00:19:33.730 --> 00:19:35.730
to their overall plan
because their overall plan

00:19:35.730 --> 00:19:38.140
doesn't really work in the first place.

00:19:38.140 --> 00:19:41.890
So that's a common
phenotype as we call it.

00:19:41.890 --> 00:19:42.730
A phenotype by the way,

00:19:42.730 --> 00:19:47.670
is just an expression of a
particular set of underlying

00:19:47.670 --> 00:19:51.420
genetic or psychological components, okay?

00:19:51.420 --> 00:19:52.560
So we say the phenotype.

00:19:52.560 --> 00:19:55.460
So a phenotype can brown
hair and green eyes,

00:19:55.460 --> 00:19:56.320
like for me,

00:19:56.320 --> 00:19:57.460
a phenotype could also be

00:19:57.460 --> 00:19:59.610
that somebody uses the
piling system, okay?

00:20:00.900 --> 00:20:04.780
The other thing that people
with ADHD have real trouble with

00:20:04.780 --> 00:20:06.950
is so-called working memory.

00:20:06.950 --> 00:20:08.480
Now you might think that people with ADHD

00:20:08.480 --> 00:20:09.900
would have really poor memories,

00:20:09.900 --> 00:20:11.420
but in fact, that's not the case.

00:20:11.420 --> 00:20:14.890
People with ADHD often
can have a terrific memory

00:20:14.890 --> 00:20:16.180
for past events,

00:20:16.180 --> 00:20:19.160
they can remember upcoming
events quite well.

00:20:19.160 --> 00:20:21.170
Their memory is clearly working.

00:20:21.170 --> 00:20:23.270
However, one aspect of
memory in particular

00:20:23.270 --> 00:20:26.770
that we call working
memory is often disrupted.

00:20:26.770 --> 00:20:28.920
Working memory is the ability to keep

00:20:28.920 --> 00:20:30.950
specific information online,

00:20:30.950 --> 00:20:33.220
to recycle it in your
brain over and over again,

00:20:33.220 --> 00:20:36.620
so that you can use it in
the immediate or short term.

00:20:36.620 --> 00:20:39.070
A good example of this
would be you meet somebody,

00:20:39.070 --> 00:20:40.440
they tell you their name,

00:20:40.440 --> 00:20:42.240
they give you their phone number verbally,

00:20:42.240 --> 00:20:43.910
and you have to walk back to your phone

00:20:43.910 --> 00:20:46.070
and enter it into your phone.

00:20:46.070 --> 00:20:49.440
People without ADHD might have
to put some effort into it,

00:20:49.440 --> 00:20:50.770
it might feel like a bit of a struggle,

00:20:50.770 --> 00:20:53.100
but typically they will be able
to recite that phone number

00:20:53.100 --> 00:20:55.790
in their mind over and over,
and then put into their phone.

00:20:55.790 --> 00:20:56.940
People with ADHD,

00:20:56.940 --> 00:21:00.550
tend to lose the ability
or lack the ability

00:21:00.550 --> 00:21:03.830
to remember things that they
just need to keep online for

00:21:03.830 --> 00:21:07.170
anywhere from 10 seconds
to a minute or two, okay?

00:21:07.170 --> 00:21:11.010
So a string of numbers like 6,
4, 3, 7, 8, 1 for most people

00:21:11.010 --> 00:21:12.560
would be pretty easy.

00:21:12.560 --> 00:21:14.840
6, 4, 3, 7, 8, 1, 6, 4, 3, 7, 8, 1,

00:21:14.840 --> 00:21:17.170
you could probably remember
that a minute from now

00:21:17.170 --> 00:21:18.810
without writing it down.

00:21:18.810 --> 00:21:23.250
But if you add one more number
to that 6, 4, 3, 7, 8, 1, 3,

00:21:23.250 --> 00:21:25.070
it gets tougher, okay?

00:21:25.070 --> 00:21:28.370
So there's a reason why
phone numbers typically have

00:21:28.370 --> 00:21:31.030
seven digits in them, of
course, there's an area code,

00:21:31.030 --> 00:21:35.530
but remembering information
that strings out longer

00:21:35.530 --> 00:21:39.490
than seven numbers or a sentence or two

00:21:39.490 --> 00:21:41.100
that's challenging for most people,

00:21:41.100 --> 00:21:43.210
people with ADHD have severe challenges,

00:21:43.210 --> 00:21:46.100
even with much smaller
batches of information

00:21:46.100 --> 00:21:49.460
over even much smaller batches of time.

00:21:49.460 --> 00:21:51.130
Deficits in working memory are also

00:21:51.130 --> 00:21:52.910
something that we see in people who have

00:21:52.910 --> 00:21:54.460
frontotemporal dementia,

00:21:54.460 --> 00:21:56.110
so damage to the frontal lobes

00:21:56.110 --> 00:21:59.410
or age-related cognitive decline

00:21:59.410 --> 00:22:01.630
and so it will come as
no surprise that later

00:22:01.630 --> 00:22:04.890
when we discuss treatments, supplements,

00:22:04.890 --> 00:22:07.190
and other tools for ADHD,

00:22:07.190 --> 00:22:08.530
that many of those treatments,

00:22:08.530 --> 00:22:11.970
supplements and tools for
ADHD are similar to the ones

00:22:11.970 --> 00:22:14.793
that work for age-related
cognitive decline.

00:22:15.920 --> 00:22:19.350
Okay, so we've more or less established

00:22:19.350 --> 00:22:23.160
the kind of menu of items that
people with ADHD tend to have

00:22:23.160 --> 00:22:24.210
some have all of them.

00:22:24.210 --> 00:22:26.220
Some have just a subset of them.

00:22:26.220 --> 00:22:31.120
Their severity can range
from very intense to mild,

00:22:31.120 --> 00:22:32.100
but in general,

00:22:32.100 --> 00:22:35.230
it's challenges with attention and focus,

00:22:35.230 --> 00:22:38.410
challenges with impulse control,
they get annoyed easily.

00:22:38.410 --> 00:22:39.810
They have kind of an impulsivity,

00:22:39.810 --> 00:22:41.678
they can't stay on task.

00:22:41.678 --> 00:22:43.703
Time perception can be off,

00:22:44.590 --> 00:22:45.980
they use the piling system

00:22:45.980 --> 00:22:48.770
or a system that doesn't
work well for them

00:22:48.770 --> 00:22:52.190
in order to organize their
things in physical space

00:22:52.190 --> 00:22:54.630
and they have a hard time
with anything that's mundane

00:22:54.630 --> 00:22:56.900
that they're not really interested in.

00:22:56.900 --> 00:22:59.650
But again, I just want to
highlight that people with ADHD

00:22:59.650 --> 00:23:02.420
are able to obtain
heightened levels of focus,

00:23:02.420 --> 00:23:05.520
even hyper-focus for things
that are exciting to them

00:23:05.520 --> 00:23:07.690
and that they really want to engage in.

00:23:07.690 --> 00:23:10.380
So now you have the
contour of what ADHD is,

00:23:10.380 --> 00:23:12.760
and if you're somebody
who doesn't have ADHD,

00:23:12.760 --> 00:23:16.919
you should also be asking
yourself which aspects of ADHD

00:23:16.919 --> 00:23:20.640
are similar to things
I've experienced before.

00:23:20.640 --> 00:23:24.120
Because what we know
about the healthy brain

00:23:24.120 --> 00:23:27.136
is that there's also a
range of abilities to focus.

00:23:27.136 --> 00:23:29.927
Some people focus very well on any task.

00:23:29.927 --> 00:23:33.760
You give them a task, they can
just laser in on that task.

00:23:33.760 --> 00:23:36.690
Other people that have to kind
of fight an internal battle,

00:23:36.690 --> 00:23:37.900
they have to convince themselves

00:23:37.900 --> 00:23:39.210
that it's important or interesting.

00:23:39.210 --> 00:23:42.900
They have to kind of incentivize
themselves internally.

00:23:42.900 --> 00:23:45.670
Other people doesn't matter,

00:23:45.670 --> 00:23:47.940
they could be bored to
tears with the information,

00:23:47.940 --> 00:23:50.017
but they can do it just because they are,

00:23:50.017 --> 00:23:51.610
"Very disciplined people."

00:23:51.610 --> 00:23:53.040
We tend to admire those people

00:23:53.040 --> 00:23:54.690
but as you'll see a little bit later,

00:23:54.690 --> 00:23:56.040
it's not clear that that's the best way

00:23:56.040 --> 00:23:57.750
to run your attentional system.

00:23:57.750 --> 00:23:59.940
There might be something to this business

00:23:59.940 --> 00:24:02.050
of having heightened levels of attention

00:24:02.050 --> 00:24:03.220
for the things that you are

00:24:03.220 --> 00:24:05.323
most interested or excited by.

00:24:07.130 --> 00:24:10.750
So let's drill into this
issue of why people with ADHD

00:24:10.750 --> 00:24:14.600
actually can focus very intensely
on things that they enjoy

00:24:14.600 --> 00:24:15.863
and are curious about.

00:24:16.700 --> 00:24:21.350
Now, enjoyment and curiosity
are psychological terms,

00:24:21.350 --> 00:24:22.950
they're not even really
psychological terms.

00:24:22.950 --> 00:24:25.570
They're just the way that we
describe our human experience

00:24:25.570 --> 00:24:28.810
of liking things, wanting
to know more about them.

00:24:28.810 --> 00:24:31.540
But from a neuro-biological perspective,

00:24:31.540 --> 00:24:34.800
they have a very clear
identity and signature

00:24:34.800 --> 00:24:36.818
and that's dopamine.

00:24:36.818 --> 00:24:38.960
Dopamine is released from neurons,

00:24:38.960 --> 00:24:41.180
it's what we call a neuromodulator

00:24:41.180 --> 00:24:44.540
and as a neuromodulator
it changes the activity

00:24:44.540 --> 00:24:45.850
of the circuits in the brain,

00:24:45.850 --> 00:24:49.061
such that certain circuits
are more active than others

00:24:49.061 --> 00:24:50.910
and in particular,

00:24:50.910 --> 00:24:54.850
dopamine creates a
heightened state of focus.

00:24:54.850 --> 00:24:57.570
It tends to contract our visual world

00:24:57.570 --> 00:25:00.020
and it tends to make us
pay attention to things

00:25:00.020 --> 00:25:04.130
that are outside and beyond
the confines of our skin.

00:25:04.130 --> 00:25:06.430
That's what we call exteroception.

00:25:06.430 --> 00:25:10.730
Dopamine also tends to put
us in a state of motivation

00:25:10.730 --> 00:25:14.230
and wanting things outside
the confines of our skin.

00:25:14.230 --> 00:25:16.000
So whether or not we're pursuing something

00:25:16.000 --> 00:25:17.560
physical in our world,

00:25:17.560 --> 00:25:19.879
or whether or not we're
pursuing information

00:25:19.879 --> 00:25:21.750
in our outside world,

00:25:21.750 --> 00:25:24.840
dopamine is largely
responsible for our ability

00:25:24.840 --> 00:25:27.199
and our drive to do that.

00:25:27.199 --> 00:25:30.810
But dopamine as a
neuromodulator is also involved

00:25:30.810 --> 00:25:34.150
in changing the way that
we perceive the world.

00:25:34.150 --> 00:25:35.210
So, as I mentioned earlier

00:25:35.210 --> 00:25:37.200
you have all these senses coming in

00:25:37.200 --> 00:25:39.160
and you can only perceive some of them

00:25:39.160 --> 00:25:41.802
because you're only paying
attention to some of them.

00:25:41.802 --> 00:25:45.630
Dopamine when it's released in our brain

00:25:45.630 --> 00:25:47.910
tends to turn on areas of our brain

00:25:47.910 --> 00:25:50.090
that narrow our visual focus

00:25:50.090 --> 00:25:51.810
and our auditory focus,

00:25:51.810 --> 00:25:54.360
so it creates a cone
of auditory attention,

00:25:54.360 --> 00:25:55.680
that's very narrow,

00:25:55.680 --> 00:25:58.870
creates a tunnel of visual
attention that's very narrow.

00:25:58.870 --> 00:26:00.710
Whereas when we have less dopamine,

00:26:00.710 --> 00:26:02.830
we tend to view the entire world,

00:26:02.830 --> 00:26:04.940
we tend to see the whole
scene that we are in,

00:26:04.940 --> 00:26:07.470
we tend to hear everything all at once.

00:26:07.470 --> 00:26:09.062
So as I describe this,

00:26:09.062 --> 00:26:12.940
hopefully you're already
starting to see and understand

00:26:12.940 --> 00:26:17.340
how having dopamine
release can allow a person,

00:26:17.340 --> 00:26:20.050
whether or not they have ADHD or not

00:26:20.050 --> 00:26:22.850
to direct their attention
to particular things

00:26:22.850 --> 00:26:24.500
in their environment, all right?

00:26:24.500 --> 00:26:27.760
So now what we're doing is
we're moving away from attention

00:26:27.760 --> 00:26:30.410
as this kind of vague ambiguous term,

00:26:30.410 --> 00:26:33.550
and we're giving it a
neurochemical identity dopamine,

00:26:33.550 --> 00:26:36.560
and we are giving it a
neural circuit identity

00:26:36.560 --> 00:26:39.820
and just to put a little
bit of flavor and detail

00:26:39.820 --> 00:26:41.650
on which neurocircuits those are,

00:26:41.650 --> 00:26:44.590
I want to discuss two general
types of neurocircuits

00:26:44.590 --> 00:26:46.990
that dopamine tends to enhance.

00:26:46.990 --> 00:26:48.560
So let's talk neurocircuits

00:26:48.560 --> 00:26:51.280
and for those of you that
love hearing neuroscience,

00:26:51.280 --> 00:26:54.180
nomenclature, you're
going to eat this part up

00:26:54.180 --> 00:26:56.350
and for those of you that
don't like a lot of names

00:26:56.350 --> 00:26:59.240
of brain areas I invite you to tune out

00:26:59.240 --> 00:27:01.940
or just try and grab
the top contour of this.

00:27:01.940 --> 00:27:03.830
I will describe it in
pretty general terms,

00:27:03.830 --> 00:27:06.290
but I will give some detail
because I know there are

00:27:06.290 --> 00:27:08.699
some of you out there who
really want to dig deeper into

00:27:08.699 --> 00:27:12.410
what the exact structures
and connectivities are, okay?

00:27:12.410 --> 00:27:15.200
So there are two main
types of circuits that

00:27:15.200 --> 00:27:17.550
we need to think about
with respect to ADHD,

00:27:17.550 --> 00:27:19.060
attention and dopamine.

00:27:19.060 --> 00:27:22.130
The first one is called
the default mode network.

00:27:22.130 --> 00:27:25.750
The default mode network is
the network of brain areas

00:27:25.750 --> 00:27:28.550
in your brain and my brain
and in everybody's brain

00:27:28.550 --> 00:27:31.880
that is active when
we're not doing anything

00:27:31.880 --> 00:27:34.290
when we're just sitting
there idle at rest.

00:27:34.290 --> 00:27:36.560
Now it's very hard to
not think about anything,

00:27:36.560 --> 00:27:39.780
but when you're not engaged
in any type of specific task,

00:27:39.780 --> 00:27:42.180
so you're not driving, you're
not playing a video game,

00:27:42.180 --> 00:27:44.570
you're not trying to study,
you're not trying to listen,

00:27:44.570 --> 00:27:46.210
you're just sitting
there letting your brain

00:27:46.210 --> 00:27:48.740
kind of go wherever it wants to go.

00:27:48.740 --> 00:27:53.083
Your default mode network
underlies that state of mind.

00:27:54.250 --> 00:27:56.940
The other set of circuits that
we're going to think about

00:27:56.940 --> 00:28:01.630
and talk about with respect
to ADHD are the task networks,

00:28:01.630 --> 00:28:04.920
the networks of the brain
that make you goal oriented,

00:28:04.920 --> 00:28:08.410
or that are at least trying
to make you goal oriented

00:28:08.410 --> 00:28:11.330
and those are a completely
different set of brain areas.

00:28:11.330 --> 00:28:14.760
However, the default mode network

00:28:14.760 --> 00:28:18.520
and these tasks networks are
communicating with one another

00:28:18.520 --> 00:28:21.240
and they're doing that
in very interesting ways.

00:28:21.240 --> 00:28:23.820
So first I want to describe how these two

00:28:23.820 --> 00:28:25.010
sets of brain areas,

00:28:25.010 --> 00:28:26.110
the default mode network

00:28:26.110 --> 00:28:29.590
and the task networks
normally interact, okay?

00:28:29.590 --> 00:28:31.010
So little bit of naming here

00:28:31.010 --> 00:28:32.300
again feel free to ignore it

00:28:32.300 --> 00:28:34.360
if you don't want this level of detail,

00:28:34.360 --> 00:28:38.040
but the default mode network includes

00:28:38.040 --> 00:28:41.350
an area called the
dorsolateral prefrontal cortex,

00:28:41.350 --> 00:28:43.828
frontal cortex, no surprises in the front

00:28:43.828 --> 00:28:45.360
and you have a dorsal, the top

00:28:45.360 --> 00:28:49.070
and side lateral part
dorsolateral, prefrontal cortex.

00:28:49.070 --> 00:28:51.480
You got one on each side
of your brain, right?

00:28:51.480 --> 00:28:52.700
And then you have a brain area called

00:28:52.700 --> 00:28:54.830
the posterior cingulate cortex

00:28:54.830 --> 00:28:57.200
and then you have an area called
the lateral parietal lobe.

00:28:57.200 --> 00:28:58.990
Again, you don't need to
remember these names for,

00:28:58.990 --> 00:29:01.550
these are three brain areas that normally

00:29:01.550 --> 00:29:03.210
are synchronized in their activity.

00:29:03.210 --> 00:29:06.500
So when one of these areas is
active in a typical person,

00:29:06.500 --> 00:29:08.640
the other areas would be active as well.

00:29:08.640 --> 00:29:10.850
So it's a little bit
like a symphony or a band

00:29:10.850 --> 00:29:13.200
like a three-piece band
is like drums, guitar,

00:29:13.200 --> 00:29:16.160
and bass they're playing together, okay?

00:29:16.160 --> 00:29:17.890
That's how it is in a typical person

00:29:17.890 --> 00:29:19.820
and in a person with ADHD,

00:29:19.820 --> 00:29:22.550
or even a person who has subclinical ADHD

00:29:22.550 --> 00:29:26.030
or in any human being
who hasn't slept well,

00:29:26.030 --> 00:29:27.990
what you find is the default mode network

00:29:27.990 --> 00:29:29.000
is not synchronized.

00:29:29.000 --> 00:29:31.823
These brain areas are just
not playing well together.

00:29:32.870 --> 00:29:37.690
Now the task networks include
a different set of structures.

00:29:37.690 --> 00:29:39.700
It still involves the prefrontal cortex,

00:29:39.700 --> 00:29:42.980
but it's a different part of
the prefrontal cortex, okay?

00:29:42.980 --> 00:29:45.700
Tends to be the medial prefrontal cortex

00:29:45.700 --> 00:29:47.280
and there are some other brain areas

00:29:47.280 --> 00:29:49.820
that the medial prefrontal
cortex is communicating to

00:29:49.820 --> 00:29:53.260
all the time, mainly to suppress impulses.

00:29:53.260 --> 00:29:56.340
It's shutting down the desire to stand up

00:29:56.340 --> 00:29:58.610
or to scratch the side of
your cheek or your nose,

00:29:58.610 --> 00:29:59.950
if you're trying not to do that,

00:29:59.950 --> 00:30:01.900
anytime you're restricting your behavior,

00:30:01.900 --> 00:30:06.227
These task directed networks
are very active, okay?

00:30:06.227 --> 00:30:10.260
Now normally in a person without ADHD,

00:30:10.260 --> 00:30:14.050
the task networks and
the default mode networks

00:30:14.050 --> 00:30:15.980
are going in kind of Seesaw fashion,

00:30:15.980 --> 00:30:18.810
they are actually what
we call anti-correlated.

00:30:18.810 --> 00:30:20.760
So it's not just that
they are not correlated,

00:30:20.760 --> 00:30:22.850
they're actually opposing one another

00:30:22.850 --> 00:30:24.333
they are anti-correlated.

00:30:25.260 --> 00:30:26.880
In a person with ADHD,

00:30:26.880 --> 00:30:29.510
the default mode networks
and the tasks networks

00:30:29.510 --> 00:30:31.860
are actually more coordinated.

00:30:31.860 --> 00:30:33.100
That might come a surprising,

00:30:33.100 --> 00:30:35.940
I think that we all have this tendency

00:30:35.940 --> 00:30:39.000
to kind of jump to conclusion
and assume that somebody

00:30:39.000 --> 00:30:42.820
who doesn't have an easy time
paying attention or has ADHD,

00:30:42.820 --> 00:30:45.550
that their brain must
be completely incoherent

00:30:45.550 --> 00:30:46.900
that it's not working well

00:30:46.900 --> 00:30:49.000
and because everything's out of whack,

00:30:49.000 --> 00:30:51.620
but there's something interesting
about people with ADHD

00:30:51.620 --> 00:30:56.360
whereby the task networks
and the default mode networks

00:30:56.360 --> 00:30:59.410
are actually working together
in a way that's correlated

00:30:59.410 --> 00:31:01.770
and that is what's abnormal.

00:31:01.770 --> 00:31:05.120
So this would be like the
guitar bass and the drums

00:31:05.120 --> 00:31:07.610
playing together in a way where

00:31:07.610 --> 00:31:10.010
the bass isn't keeping the
backbeat and the drums,

00:31:10.010 --> 00:31:13.340
aren't keeping the backbeat
that they're playing together,

00:31:13.340 --> 00:31:14.990
they're all playing the
melodies and harmonies

00:31:14.990 --> 00:31:17.130
in a way that just doesn't sound right.

00:31:17.130 --> 00:31:21.530
That's what's going on in the
brain of somebody with ADHD

00:31:21.530 --> 00:31:23.340
and we can now confidently say

00:31:23.340 --> 00:31:24.940
based on brain imaging studies,

00:31:24.940 --> 00:31:26.870
that when somebody gets better,

00:31:26.870 --> 00:31:30.600
when they're treated for ADHD
or when they age out of ADHD,

00:31:30.600 --> 00:31:34.750
as sometimes it's the case
that the default mode networks

00:31:34.750 --> 00:31:36.580
and the task networks tend to become

00:31:36.580 --> 00:31:38.690
anti-correlated again, okay?

00:31:38.690 --> 00:31:41.450
So that's the underlying neurobiology,

00:31:41.450 --> 00:31:44.759
but you'll notice that I
didn't mention dopamine at all.

00:31:44.759 --> 00:31:47.430
What dopamine is doing in this context

00:31:47.430 --> 00:31:50.580
is dopamine is acting like a conductor.

00:31:50.580 --> 00:31:52.870
Dopamine is saying this
circuit should be active

00:31:52.870 --> 00:31:54.030
then that circuit should be active.

00:31:54.030 --> 00:31:55.520
It should be default mode network

00:31:55.520 --> 00:31:57.920
and then when the default
mode network is not active,

00:31:57.920 --> 00:31:59.350
then it should be the task network.

00:31:59.350 --> 00:32:01.550
So it's really acting as a
conductor saying, you go,

00:32:01.550 --> 00:32:03.320
now you go, now you go, now you go.

00:32:03.320 --> 00:32:04.720
And in ADHD,

00:32:04.720 --> 00:32:06.755
there's something about
the dopamine system

00:32:06.755 --> 00:32:10.760
that is not allowing it
to conduct these networks

00:32:10.760 --> 00:32:13.360
and make sure that they stay what,

00:32:13.360 --> 00:32:15.580
the engineers or physicists
or mathematicians would say

00:32:15.580 --> 00:32:18.740
out of phase to be anti-correlated, okay?

00:32:18.740 --> 00:32:21.020
Out of phase and anti correlate,
essentially the same thing,

00:32:21.020 --> 00:32:23.500
at least for purposes of this discussion.

00:32:23.500 --> 00:32:25.740
So that raises two questions,

00:32:25.740 --> 00:32:30.500
could it be that dopamine is
not at sufficiently high levels

00:32:30.500 --> 00:32:33.260
or could it be that dopamine
is just doing it all wrong?

00:32:33.260 --> 00:32:34.093
In other words,

00:32:34.093 --> 00:32:36.560
is there no conductor or is
the conductor playing with like

00:32:36.560 --> 00:32:37.580
little tiny toothpicks

00:32:37.580 --> 00:32:39.620
and so the instruments can't see

00:32:39.620 --> 00:32:41.020
what they're supposed to do.

00:32:41.020 --> 00:32:42.650
They can't get the instruction

00:32:42.650 --> 00:32:45.090
'cause it's just not
loud enough, so to speak,

00:32:45.090 --> 00:32:47.100
or could it be that the
information is getting out,

00:32:47.100 --> 00:32:49.130
but the information that's
getting out is wrong,

00:32:49.130 --> 00:32:50.010
the conductor's there,

00:32:50.010 --> 00:32:52.743
but the conductor is in
very good at conducting.

00:32:54.200 --> 00:32:57.690
Now we can gain insight
into how the system works

00:32:57.690 --> 00:33:00.310
and fails and how to treat it

00:33:00.310 --> 00:33:01.860
by looking at some of the current

00:33:01.860 --> 00:33:04.300
and previous treatments for ADHD,

00:33:04.300 --> 00:33:06.360
as well as some of the recreational drugs

00:33:06.360 --> 00:33:09.870
that people with ADHD
tend to pursue and like

00:33:09.870 --> 00:33:12.610
now I'm certainly not a
proponent of people with ADHD

00:33:12.610 --> 00:33:14.040
taking drugs recreationally,

00:33:14.040 --> 00:33:15.550
that's not what this is about,

00:33:15.550 --> 00:33:18.300
but if you look at their
drug seeking behavior

00:33:18.300 --> 00:33:21.530
and you couple that drug seeking behavior

00:33:21.530 --> 00:33:25.550
to their desire to remedy
their attention deficit,

00:33:25.550 --> 00:33:28.280
you start gaining some
really interesting insight

00:33:28.280 --> 00:33:31.660
into how dopamine is
regulating these circuits

00:33:31.660 --> 00:33:35.940
in normal circumstances
and in people with ADHD.

00:33:35.940 --> 00:33:38.450
So what exactly is going on
with the dopamine system,

00:33:38.450 --> 00:33:40.260
in people with ADHD

00:33:40.260 --> 00:33:42.030
and what's going on
with the dopamine system

00:33:42.030 --> 00:33:44.980
in people that have
terrific levels of attention

00:33:44.980 --> 00:33:46.530
for any task?

00:33:46.530 --> 00:33:51.000
Well, in the year 2015, an
important paper came out.

00:33:51.000 --> 00:33:52.820
The first author is Spencer,

00:33:52.820 --> 00:33:55.900
and it came out in a journal
called Biological Psychiatry,

00:33:55.900 --> 00:33:57.960
and it formalized the so-called

00:33:57.960 --> 00:34:01.910
low dopamine hypothesis of ADHD.

00:34:01.910 --> 00:34:04.110
The idea that dopamine
was somehow involved

00:34:04.110 --> 00:34:07.390
or not at the appropriate
levels in people with ADHD

00:34:07.390 --> 00:34:09.850
had been around for a pretty long time,

00:34:09.850 --> 00:34:14.830
but a formal proposition of
the low dopamine hypothesis

00:34:14.830 --> 00:34:17.710
led to some really important
experiments and understanding

00:34:17.710 --> 00:34:19.713
of what goes wrong in ADHD.

00:34:20.790 --> 00:34:24.380
It turns out that if
dopamine levels are too low

00:34:24.380 --> 00:34:27.150
in particular circuits in the brain,

00:34:27.150 --> 00:34:31.260
that it leads to unnecessary
firing of neurons in the brain

00:34:31.260 --> 00:34:35.370
that are unrelated to the
task that one is trying to do

00:34:35.370 --> 00:34:37.950
and that is unrelated to the information

00:34:37.950 --> 00:34:39.930
that one is trying to focus on.

00:34:39.930 --> 00:34:41.700
So if you think back
before you've got this

00:34:41.700 --> 00:34:44.260
default mode network and
a task-related network,

00:34:44.260 --> 00:34:46.960
and they need to be in
this kind of concert of

00:34:46.960 --> 00:34:50.632
anti-correlation and an ADHD
they're firing together.

00:34:50.632 --> 00:34:54.123
Well, the problem seems to
be that when dopamine is low,

00:34:55.320 --> 00:34:57.690
certain neurons are firing
when they shouldn't be,

00:34:57.690 --> 00:34:59.150
this is like a band, right?

00:34:59.150 --> 00:35:01.550
We'll go back to our band,
that's a guitar bass in it,

00:35:01.550 --> 00:35:03.350
and the person playing the drums

00:35:03.350 --> 00:35:06.660
and it's as if one of those or
several of those instruments

00:35:06.660 --> 00:35:09.500
are playing notes when they
shouldn't be playing, right?

00:35:09.500 --> 00:35:12.030
The pauses and music are just as important

00:35:12.030 --> 00:35:14.513
as the actual playing of notes.

00:35:15.680 --> 00:35:19.050
When dopamine is too low neurons fire,

00:35:19.050 --> 00:35:20.920
more than they should in these networks

00:35:20.920 --> 00:35:22.023
that govern attention.

00:35:23.090 --> 00:35:26.300
This is the so-called
low dopamine hypothesis

00:35:26.300 --> 00:35:29.530
and if you start looking anecdotally

00:35:29.530 --> 00:35:33.670
at what people with ADHD
have done for decades,

00:35:33.670 --> 00:35:36.670
not just recently since
the low dopamine hypothesis

00:35:36.670 --> 00:35:38.320
has been proposed,

00:35:38.320 --> 00:35:41.739
but what they were doing in
the 1950s and then the 1940s

00:35:41.739 --> 00:35:42.572
and the 1960s.

00:35:42.572 --> 00:35:47.572
What you find is that they
tend to use recreational drugs,

00:35:48.090 --> 00:35:53.090
or they tend to indulge
in non drug stimulants.

00:35:53.860 --> 00:35:57.180
So things like drinking,
six cups of coffee

00:35:57.180 --> 00:35:59.250
or quadruple espressos,

00:35:59.250 --> 00:36:01.140
or when it was more prominent

00:36:01.140 --> 00:36:03.020
smoking a half a pack of cigarettes

00:36:03.020 --> 00:36:05.106
and drinking four cups of coffee a day

00:36:05.106 --> 00:36:08.010
or if the person had access to it

00:36:08.010 --> 00:36:10.100
using cocaine as a recreational drug

00:36:10.100 --> 00:36:12.620
or amphetamine as a recreational drug.

00:36:12.620 --> 00:36:15.387
All of those substances
that I just described

00:36:15.387 --> 00:36:17.760
in particular cocaine and amphetamine,

00:36:17.760 --> 00:36:20.500
but also coffee and cigarettes

00:36:20.500 --> 00:36:23.620
increase levels of
multiple neurotransmitters,

00:36:23.620 --> 00:36:26.250
but all have the quality
of increasing levels

00:36:26.250 --> 00:36:29.110
of dopamine in the
brain and in particular,

00:36:29.110 --> 00:36:31.850
in the regions of the brain
that regulate attention

00:36:31.850 --> 00:36:35.800
and these task related and
default mode networks okay?

00:36:35.800 --> 00:36:36.910
Now young children,

00:36:36.910 --> 00:36:39.518
fortunately don't have access
to those kinds of stimulants

00:36:39.518 --> 00:36:41.170
most of the time

00:36:41.170 --> 00:36:44.570
and those stimulants
all have high potential

00:36:44.570 --> 00:36:46.460
for abuse in adults.

00:36:46.460 --> 00:36:48.330
So we will talk about
the potential for abuse

00:36:48.330 --> 00:36:49.390
in a few minutes.

00:36:49.390 --> 00:36:51.610
But if you look at children,

00:36:51.610 --> 00:36:54.550
even very young children with ADHD,

00:36:54.550 --> 00:36:57.650
they show things like
preference for sugary foods,

00:36:57.650 --> 00:37:01.810
which also act as dopamine
inducing stimulants.

00:37:01.810 --> 00:37:05.900
Now, of course, once they
get access to soda pop

00:37:05.900 --> 00:37:07.770
and coffee and tea,

00:37:07.770 --> 00:37:10.150
they start to indulge in
those more than other people.

00:37:10.150 --> 00:37:10.983
For a long time,

00:37:10.983 --> 00:37:12.450
it was thought that children with ADHD

00:37:12.450 --> 00:37:15.680
consumed too many sugary
foods or drank too much soda

00:37:15.680 --> 00:37:18.340
or adults with ADHD

00:37:18.340 --> 00:37:20.810
would take recreational
drugs like methamphetamine

00:37:20.810 --> 00:37:24.080
or cocaine or would drink coffee to excess

00:37:24.080 --> 00:37:25.880
or smoke cigarettes to excess

00:37:25.880 --> 00:37:28.390
because they had poor levels of attention

00:37:28.390 --> 00:37:31.210
and because they couldn't
make good decisions,

00:37:31.210 --> 00:37:33.380
they were too impulsive and so forth

00:37:33.380 --> 00:37:35.660
and while that certainly
could be the case,

00:37:35.660 --> 00:37:37.950
knowing what we now know about dopamine,

00:37:37.950 --> 00:37:41.940
and the fact that having
enough dopamine is required

00:37:41.940 --> 00:37:43.630
in order to coordinate
these neural circuits

00:37:43.630 --> 00:37:47.048
that allow for focus and
quality decision-making

00:37:47.048 --> 00:37:51.170
an equally valid idea
is that these children

00:37:51.170 --> 00:37:53.880
and these adults are actually
trying to self-medicate

00:37:53.880 --> 00:37:56.170
by pursuing these compounds, right?

00:37:56.170 --> 00:37:59.110
Things like cocaine lead to
huge increases in dopamine.

00:37:59.110 --> 00:38:01.830
Well, what happens was
when somebody with ADHD

00:38:01.830 --> 00:38:03.290
takes that drug,

00:38:03.290 --> 00:38:05.190
it turns out they actually obtain

00:38:05.190 --> 00:38:07.120
heightened levels of focus,

00:38:07.120 --> 00:38:08.710
their ability to focus on things

00:38:08.710 --> 00:38:11.000
other than things they absolutely care

00:38:11.000 --> 00:38:13.690
intensely about goes up,

00:38:13.690 --> 00:38:16.530
likewise, children who consume anything

00:38:16.530 --> 00:38:18.727
that increases their levels of dopamine,

00:38:18.727 --> 00:38:23.727
if those children have ADHD,
they tend to be calmer,

00:38:23.760 --> 00:38:25.810
they tend to be able to focus more.

00:38:25.810 --> 00:38:28.480
Now, this is very different than children

00:38:28.480 --> 00:38:29.910
who do not have ADHD.

00:38:29.910 --> 00:38:30.940
When they consume too much sugar,

00:38:30.940 --> 00:38:33.220
they tend to become super hyperactive.

00:38:33.220 --> 00:38:34.930
When they consume any kind of stimulant,

00:38:34.930 --> 00:38:37.463
they tend to go wild and
run around like crazy.

00:38:37.463 --> 00:38:38.690
Actually, I have an anecdote about this

00:38:38.690 --> 00:38:40.380
just to illustrate it.

00:38:40.380 --> 00:38:41.350
I have a friend,

00:38:41.350 --> 00:38:44.010
he has two children that
are now in their teens

00:38:44.010 --> 00:38:45.720
and twenties, but when they were little,

00:38:45.720 --> 00:38:48.260
one time, I brought them some
chocolate just as a gift,

00:38:48.260 --> 00:38:51.680
when I showed up at their
house and within 30 minutes,

00:38:51.680 --> 00:38:53.730
the kids were running around like crazy

00:38:53.730 --> 00:38:56.130
I mean they were pretty high energy kids,

00:38:56.130 --> 00:38:57.770
but they were going bonkers

00:38:57.770 --> 00:39:01.010
and that's actually when the
mother, my friend at the time,

00:39:01.010 --> 00:39:03.030
unfortunately, still now
looked at the chocolate,

00:39:03.030 --> 00:39:06.140
realized that it was chocolate
with espresso beans in it.

00:39:06.140 --> 00:39:07.530
It was like dark chocolate
with espresso beans

00:39:07.530 --> 00:39:09.170
so I was really at fault there,

00:39:09.170 --> 00:39:10.880
you don't want to give kids dark chocolate

00:39:10.880 --> 00:39:11.713
with espresso beans,

00:39:11.713 --> 00:39:13.837
but what you're really
seeing that hyperactivity

00:39:13.837 --> 00:39:15.790
that is dopamine, okay?

00:39:15.790 --> 00:39:18.720
It's the sugar combined with
the caffeine in this case,

00:39:18.720 --> 00:39:21.370
combined with a few other
compounds that exist in chocolate,

00:39:21.370 --> 00:39:23.470
that really increase
our levels of alertness

00:39:23.470 --> 00:39:27.630
and our tendency to want
to move around a lot, okay?

00:39:27.630 --> 00:39:31.240
So dopamine and low levels of dopamine

00:39:31.240 --> 00:39:34.980
apparently are what's
wrong in people with ADHD,

00:39:34.980 --> 00:39:36.700
that dopamine hypothesis

00:39:36.700 --> 00:39:39.810
is what led to the idea
that treating people,

00:39:39.810 --> 00:39:44.490
children and adults included
with dopaminergic compounds

00:39:44.490 --> 00:39:48.420
would somehow increase
their ability to focus

00:39:48.420 --> 00:39:51.410
and if you look at the major
drugs that were developed

00:39:51.410 --> 00:39:54.010
and now marketed by
pharmaceutical companies

00:39:54.010 --> 00:39:55.793
for the treatment of ADHD,

00:39:56.920 --> 00:39:59.850
those drugs have names like Ritalin.

00:39:59.850 --> 00:40:04.700
Nowadays, it's typically
things like Adderall, Modafinil

00:40:04.700 --> 00:40:06.170
and some of the other derivatives,

00:40:06.170 --> 00:40:09.240
they all serve to increase
levels of dopamine

00:40:09.240 --> 00:40:11.340
in particular dopamine in the networks

00:40:11.340 --> 00:40:13.670
that control task directed behavior,

00:40:13.670 --> 00:40:16.730
and that coordinate the
default mode network

00:40:16.730 --> 00:40:18.840
and these task-related networks.

00:40:18.840 --> 00:40:20.900
So many of you have
probably heard of Ritalin.

00:40:20.900 --> 00:40:24.810
Ritalin is a prescription
stimulant that is

00:40:24.810 --> 00:40:28.270
prescribed for ADHD as
well as for narcolepsy.

00:40:28.270 --> 00:40:30.010
Narcolepsy is a condition

00:40:30.010 --> 00:40:32.050
in which people tend to fall asleep

00:40:32.050 --> 00:40:33.570
during the day time, quite a lot,

00:40:33.570 --> 00:40:35.040
excessive daytime sleepiness,

00:40:35.040 --> 00:40:37.250
not due to lack of sleep at night,

00:40:37.250 --> 00:40:39.860
but also tend to fall asleep
when they get excited,

00:40:39.860 --> 00:40:42.900
if they're really emotionally
excited or about to eat

00:40:42.900 --> 00:40:44.830
or any other kind of activity that

00:40:44.830 --> 00:40:47.460
would normally get somebody
really aroused and alert

00:40:47.460 --> 00:40:49.390
people with narcolepsy
tend to fall asleep,

00:40:49.390 --> 00:40:51.930
or they tend to become
what's called cataplectic.

00:40:51.930 --> 00:40:54.500
They tend to just sort of
go limp in the muscles.

00:40:54.500 --> 00:40:57.170
So it's this invasion of
sleep into the daytime.

00:40:57.170 --> 00:40:59.020
It's dysregulated by emotion.

00:40:59.020 --> 00:41:00.890
You can imagine why a stimulant,

00:41:00.890 --> 00:41:03.210
something that would wake
you up, make you very alert,

00:41:03.210 --> 00:41:04.230
focused and motivated

00:41:04.230 --> 00:41:07.430
would be a good treatment for narcolepsy.

00:41:07.430 --> 00:41:12.430
Adderall also is used to treat
ADHD and to treat narcolepsy

00:41:13.770 --> 00:41:15.260
things like Modafinil

00:41:15.260 --> 00:41:18.180
also used to treat ADHD and narcolepsy.

00:41:18.180 --> 00:41:19.810
So you're sensing a theme here.

00:41:19.810 --> 00:41:22.020
So what are the differences
and similarities

00:41:22.020 --> 00:41:23.255
between these drugs

00:41:23.255 --> 00:41:25.070
and what can that tell us about ADHD?

00:41:25.070 --> 00:41:29.410
Well, Ritalin was one of
the first-generation drugs

00:41:29.410 --> 00:41:34.190
that was prescribed for ADHD
in order to deal head on

00:41:34.190 --> 00:41:36.180
with this dopamine hypothesis.

00:41:36.180 --> 00:41:40.340
This idea that in ADHD,
dopamine levels are too low.

00:41:40.340 --> 00:41:43.480
Nowadays, Adderall is the
more typically prescribed drug

00:41:43.480 --> 00:41:45.780
for ADHD that has to do

00:41:45.780 --> 00:41:47.830
with some of the so-called
pharmacokinetics,

00:41:47.830 --> 00:41:50.790
the rate at which those
drugs enter the system

00:41:50.790 --> 00:41:52.820
and how long they last in the system.

00:41:52.820 --> 00:41:53.653
So for instance,

00:41:53.653 --> 00:41:56.130
Ritalin was a drug that was packaged

00:41:56.130 --> 00:41:58.330
into various time-release formulas.

00:41:58.330 --> 00:42:02.390
Whereas initially Adderall was
only released in a form that

00:42:02.390 --> 00:42:03.630
had a very short life,

00:42:03.630 --> 00:42:07.340
So meaning that it wasn't
in the bloodstream very long

00:42:07.340 --> 00:42:08.980
and didn't affect the brain for very long

00:42:08.980 --> 00:42:13.040
and so the dosages could be
controlled in a more typical way

00:42:13.040 --> 00:42:15.930
without going into a lot
of tangential detail.

00:42:15.930 --> 00:42:18.020
As you all know, at
different times of day,

00:42:18.020 --> 00:42:19.890
you tend to be more or less alert.

00:42:19.890 --> 00:42:22.660
So a long sustained release drug

00:42:22.660 --> 00:42:24.950
while that might sound like
a really terrific thing.

00:42:24.950 --> 00:42:26.580
If that drug is having an effect

00:42:26.580 --> 00:42:27.850
of making you more alert

00:42:27.850 --> 00:42:31.190
and it's released across
very many hours of your day,

00:42:31.190 --> 00:42:32.800
there might be periods of your day

00:42:32.800 --> 00:42:34.400
when you feel too alert,

00:42:34.400 --> 00:42:35.233
periods of your day,

00:42:35.233 --> 00:42:37.010
when you feel just right
and periods of your day,

00:42:37.010 --> 00:42:39.270
when you wished that you were more alert.

00:42:39.270 --> 00:42:42.070
These are some of the
pharmacokinetics, kinetics,

00:42:42.070 --> 00:42:44.064
meaning movement of
the different compounds

00:42:44.064 --> 00:42:46.750
within the bloodstream
and brain that could,

00:42:46.750 --> 00:42:48.630
you could imagine in a very real way,

00:42:48.630 --> 00:42:50.790
would impact whether or not
someone would feel really good

00:42:50.790 --> 00:42:52.500
on one of these drugs or whether or not

00:42:52.500 --> 00:42:55.163
they would feel too anxious
or too sleepy and so on.

00:42:56.280 --> 00:42:57.970
Let's take a step back
for a second and just ask,

00:42:57.970 --> 00:42:59.390
what are these drugs?

00:42:59.390 --> 00:43:01.000
We know they increase dopamine,

00:43:01.000 --> 00:43:03.220
but what are they really?

00:43:03.220 --> 00:43:07.680
Well, Ritalin also called methylphenidate

00:43:07.680 --> 00:43:11.330
is very similar to amphetamine speed,

00:43:11.330 --> 00:43:13.090
or what's typically call speed

00:43:13.090 --> 00:43:16.390
in the street drug nomenclature.

00:43:16.390 --> 00:43:20.960
Adderall, which goes by
various other names, okay?

00:43:20.960 --> 00:43:25.960
So Adderall, Adderall XR, my
dialysis, things like that.

00:43:28.110 --> 00:43:29.980
Adderall is basically a combination of

00:43:29.980 --> 00:43:33.300
amphetamine and dextroamphetamine.

00:43:33.300 --> 00:43:35.270
Now some of you probably realize this,

00:43:35.270 --> 00:43:37.040
that Adderall is amphetamine,

00:43:37.040 --> 00:43:39.270
but I'm guessing that there a
good number of you out there,

00:43:39.270 --> 00:43:42.840
perhaps even parents and
kids that don't realize that

00:43:42.840 --> 00:43:45.750
these drugs like cocaine and
amphetamine methamphetamine,

00:43:45.750 --> 00:43:50.750
which are incredibly dangerous
and incredibly habit forming

00:43:51.340 --> 00:43:53.630
and have high potential for abuse.

00:43:53.630 --> 00:43:56.220
Well, the pharmaceutical versions of those

00:43:56.220 --> 00:43:59.580
are exactly what are used to treat ADHD

00:43:59.580 --> 00:44:01.960
and they're not exactly like
cocaine or methamphetamine,

00:44:01.960 --> 00:44:05.130
but they are structurally
and chemically very similar

00:44:05.130 --> 00:44:07.910
and their net effect in the brain and body

00:44:07.910 --> 00:44:08.910
is essentially the same,

00:44:08.910 --> 00:44:11.700
which is to increase dopamine primarily,

00:44:11.700 --> 00:44:14.160
but also to increase
levels of a neuromodulator

00:44:14.160 --> 00:44:16.420
called epinephrin or norepinephrine

00:44:16.420 --> 00:44:18.290
also called noradrenaline and adrenaline

00:44:18.290 --> 00:44:21.000
those names are the
same and to some extent

00:44:21.000 --> 00:44:23.712
to increase levels of serotonin
in the brain and blood,

00:44:23.712 --> 00:44:25.810
but not so much serotonin,

00:44:25.810 --> 00:44:28.420
that's just kind of a small
smidgen of effect, okay?

00:44:28.420 --> 00:44:32.860
So dopamine way up norepinephrine
and adrenaline way up.

00:44:32.860 --> 00:44:36.850
So that's motivation
drive, focus and energy

00:44:36.850 --> 00:44:40.050
and to some extent, a
little bit of serotonin,

00:44:40.050 --> 00:44:44.391
which is really more about
feeling calm and relaxed

00:44:44.391 --> 00:44:46.680
and you can imagine why that would be

00:44:46.680 --> 00:44:50.633
a good balancing effect for
dopamine and norepinephrine.

00:44:52.000 --> 00:44:54.010
So what I'm essentially
saying is that the drugs

00:44:54.010 --> 00:44:56.960
that are used to treat
ADHD are stimulants,

00:44:56.960 --> 00:44:58.463
and they look very much alike.

00:44:58.463 --> 00:45:00.930
In fact, nearly identical to

00:45:00.930 --> 00:45:02.410
some of the so-called street drugs,

00:45:02.410 --> 00:45:05.860
stimulants that we all
here are so terrible.

00:45:05.860 --> 00:45:07.789
However, I do want to emphasize

00:45:07.789 --> 00:45:10.180
that at the appropriate dosages

00:45:10.180 --> 00:45:13.680
and working with a quality psychiatrist

00:45:13.680 --> 00:45:16.200
or neurologist or family physician

00:45:16.200 --> 00:45:17.860
does have to be a board certified MD

00:45:17.860 --> 00:45:19.470
that prescribes these things,

00:45:19.470 --> 00:45:23.840
many people with ADHD
achieve excellent relief

00:45:23.840 --> 00:45:26.310
with these drugs, not all of
them, but many of them do,

00:45:26.310 --> 00:45:30.210
especially if these treatments
are started early in life.

00:45:30.210 --> 00:45:32.010
So now knowing what these drugs are,

00:45:32.010 --> 00:45:36.470
I want to raise the question
of why prescribe these drugs?

00:45:36.470 --> 00:45:38.550
I mean, everyone has to make
a decision for themselves

00:45:38.550 --> 00:45:39.790
or for their child as to whether or not

00:45:39.790 --> 00:45:41.743
they're going to take these things or not.

00:45:42.670 --> 00:45:46.400
I also want to acknowledge
that many people out there,

00:45:46.400 --> 00:45:49.840
many, many people out there
are taking these drugs,

00:45:49.840 --> 00:45:52.270
even though they have not
been clinically diagnosed

00:45:52.270 --> 00:45:54.020
with ADHD when I say these drugs,

00:45:54.020 --> 00:45:56.270
I'm specifically referring
to Ritalin and Adderall

00:45:56.270 --> 00:46:00.120
and Modafinil, but more
typically it's Adderall, okay?

00:46:00.120 --> 00:46:02.000
People using cocaine and amphetamine

00:46:02.000 --> 00:46:03.290
for recreational purposes,

00:46:03.290 --> 00:46:05.370
that's a completely different beast

00:46:05.370 --> 00:46:06.510
and it is indeed a beast

00:46:06.510 --> 00:46:08.823
and it's something that
I strongly discourage.

00:46:10.130 --> 00:46:15.130
However, I'm aware that up
to 25% of college students,

00:46:15.540 --> 00:46:19.410
and perhaps as many as
35% of all individuals

00:46:19.410 --> 00:46:24.410
between the ages of 17
and 30 are taking Adderall

00:46:25.080 --> 00:46:27.160
on a regular or semi-regular basis

00:46:27.160 --> 00:46:30.850
in order to work, in order to study

00:46:30.850 --> 00:46:33.720
and in order to function and
focus in their daily life.

00:46:33.720 --> 00:46:37.060
Even though they have not
been diagnosed with ADHD,

00:46:37.060 --> 00:46:38.340
there's a whole black market for this.

00:46:38.340 --> 00:46:40.110
They're getting it from
people with prescriptions.

00:46:40.110 --> 00:46:41.870
I'm not here to pass judgment.

00:46:41.870 --> 00:46:44.750
I just want to emphasize
how these drugs work.

00:46:44.750 --> 00:46:48.047
Some of the things that
they do to enhance cognition

00:46:48.047 --> 00:46:50.010
and focus that actually
serve the brain well

00:46:50.010 --> 00:46:53.310
in certain individuals and how
they can be very detrimental

00:46:54.510 --> 00:46:55.830
in other individuals.

00:46:55.830 --> 00:46:57.180
I sort of blew right past it.

00:46:57.180 --> 00:47:01.750
But the fact that in upwards
of 25% of young people

00:47:01.750 --> 00:47:03.810
are taking things like Adderall,

00:47:03.810 --> 00:47:07.950
despite not having a
clinical diagnosis of ADHD.

00:47:07.950 --> 00:47:10.823
Well, that's a ridiculously high number.

00:47:11.690 --> 00:47:12.600
A few years ago,

00:47:12.600 --> 00:47:15.980
it was estimated that
Adderall use and Ritalin use

00:47:15.980 --> 00:47:19.690
without diagnosis of ADHD
was second in incident

00:47:19.690 --> 00:47:21.590
only to cannabis,

00:47:21.590 --> 00:47:25.410
but actually now the
consumption of Adderall

00:47:25.410 --> 00:47:29.100
without prescription is higher than

00:47:29.100 --> 00:47:31.810
the consumption of
cannabis in that age group.

00:47:31.810 --> 00:47:35.140
So what that means is that
there's a lot of stimulant use

00:47:35.140 --> 00:47:36.270
in that age group

00:47:36.270 --> 00:47:39.090
and there are a lot of adults also

00:47:39.090 --> 00:47:42.180
using and abusing stimulants
in order to gain focus.

00:47:42.180 --> 00:47:43.830
Then we can have a whole
discussion about whether or not

00:47:43.830 --> 00:47:45.700
life is becoming more demanding,

00:47:45.700 --> 00:47:48.190
whether or not the need
for focus is excessive

00:47:48.190 --> 00:47:50.040
and that's why people are doing that.

00:47:50.040 --> 00:47:51.630
But frankly, it's an
interesting discussion,

00:47:51.630 --> 00:47:54.140
but it's not one that would
deliver us to any answers.

00:47:54.140 --> 00:47:57.167
Rather, I'd like to focus
on the ways that people now

00:47:57.167 --> 00:47:59.610
and people have always
been self-medicating

00:47:59.610 --> 00:48:02.050
to increase, focus, right?

00:48:02.050 --> 00:48:05.130
Caffeine, which I can indulge

00:48:05.130 --> 00:48:08.530
some, I don't think to
access has long been used

00:48:08.530 --> 00:48:10.410
as a stimulant to increase dopamine,

00:48:10.410 --> 00:48:11.390
increase norepinephrine,

00:48:11.390 --> 00:48:15.230
increased focus and energy
and in addition to that,

00:48:15.230 --> 00:48:16.800
it works through the so-called cyclic amp,

00:48:16.800 --> 00:48:20.200
phosphodiesterase pathway,
remember anytime you see,

00:48:20.200 --> 00:48:22.300
you hear an ASE, that's an enzyme.

00:48:22.300 --> 00:48:24.610
Phosphodiesterase is involved in the

00:48:24.610 --> 00:48:27.460
conversion of things like cyclic amp into

00:48:27.460 --> 00:48:28.820
energy for cells and so forth.

00:48:28.820 --> 00:48:31.210
Basically coffee gives you
energy it makes you feel good

00:48:31.210 --> 00:48:34.120
and it increases focus
because of the circuits

00:48:34.120 --> 00:48:35.663
that it engages in the brain.

00:48:37.390 --> 00:48:38.640
People have been taking caffeine

00:48:38.640 --> 00:48:42.570
and continue to take it caffeine for ages.

00:48:42.570 --> 00:48:45.390
People also used to smoke cigarettes,

00:48:45.390 --> 00:48:47.600
nicotine in order to gain focus.

00:48:47.600 --> 00:48:50.282
Nowadays, that's less common
because of the concerns,

00:48:50.282 --> 00:48:54.260
quite valid concerns about
lung cancer from smoking,

00:48:54.260 --> 00:48:57.170
but there's a lot of vaping out there.

00:48:57.170 --> 00:48:59.930
There are a lot of people
now consuming nicotine,

00:48:59.930 --> 00:49:02.510
which is the active
substance in cigarettes

00:49:02.510 --> 00:49:06.930
and in most nicotine vapes
that stimulates the brain

00:49:06.930 --> 00:49:09.290
to be more focused and more alert.

00:49:09.290 --> 00:49:12.470
So the idea of taking
stimulants of consuming things

00:49:12.470 --> 00:49:15.670
or smoking things in order
to increase alertness

00:49:15.670 --> 00:49:17.200
is not a new idea.

00:49:17.200 --> 00:49:19.003
It's just that in ADHD,

00:49:20.130 --> 00:49:22.630
it's surprising that these
things would work, right?

00:49:22.630 --> 00:49:23.770
I mean, if the problem is

00:49:23.770 --> 00:49:26.600
Attention Deficit Hyperactivity Disorder,

00:49:26.600 --> 00:49:28.320
what we're really talking about here,

00:49:28.320 --> 00:49:31.890
or children that are prescribed a drug

00:49:31.890 --> 00:49:33.000
that ought to be a stimulant,

00:49:33.000 --> 00:49:35.570
it ought to make them hyper hyperactive

00:49:35.570 --> 00:49:36.960
and rather than doing that,

00:49:36.960 --> 00:49:40.450
it actually somehow
serves to calm them a bit,

00:49:40.450 --> 00:49:42.670
or at least allow them to focus.

00:49:42.670 --> 00:49:45.870
Here's the reason, children have a brain

00:49:45.870 --> 00:49:49.770
that's a very plastic
meaning it can remodel itself

00:49:49.770 --> 00:49:52.620
and change in response to
experience very, very quickly

00:49:52.620 --> 00:49:54.490
compared to adults.

00:49:54.490 --> 00:49:56.960
Taking stimulants as a child,

00:49:56.960 --> 00:50:00.110
if you are a child diagnosed with ADHD

00:50:00.110 --> 00:50:04.560
allows that forebrain task
related network to come online,

00:50:04.560 --> 00:50:07.460
to be active at the appropriate times

00:50:07.460 --> 00:50:09.710
and because those children are young,

00:50:09.710 --> 00:50:12.720
it allows those children
to learn what focus is

00:50:12.720 --> 00:50:16.880
and to sort of follow or
enter that tunnel of focus.

00:50:16.880 --> 00:50:20.350
Now, by taking a drug, it's
creating focus artificially,

00:50:20.350 --> 00:50:23.260
it's not creating focus because
they're super interested

00:50:23.260 --> 00:50:27.240
in something it's chemically
inducing, a state of focus,

00:50:27.240 --> 00:50:30.220
and let's face it a lot
of childhood and school

00:50:30.220 --> 00:50:31.550
and becoming a functional adult

00:50:31.550 --> 00:50:32.700
is about learning how to focus

00:50:32.700 --> 00:50:34.090
even though you don't
want to do something.

00:50:34.090 --> 00:50:35.170
In fact, when I was in college,

00:50:35.170 --> 00:50:37.220
I had this little trick
that may or may not work

00:50:37.220 --> 00:50:38.330
for some of you,

00:50:38.330 --> 00:50:40.920
which is if I couldn't
focus on the material

00:50:40.920 --> 00:50:42.350
I was trying to learn,

00:50:42.350 --> 00:50:44.500
I would delude myself into thinking

00:50:44.500 --> 00:50:46.460
that it was the most
interesting thing in the world.

00:50:46.460 --> 00:50:48.490
I would just kind of lie
to myself and tell myself,

00:50:48.490 --> 00:50:50.893
okay, this, I won't mention the subjects,

00:50:52.830 --> 00:50:54.000
I absolutely love this.

00:50:54.000 --> 00:50:56.270
I would just, I would tell
myself that I loved it

00:50:56.270 --> 00:50:58.980
and I noticed that just that selective

00:50:58.980 --> 00:51:03.100
or deliberate engagement of
that desire to know circuit,

00:51:03.100 --> 00:51:06.140
whatever that is in my brain,
no doubt involves dopamine,

00:51:06.140 --> 00:51:08.370
allowed me to focus and
remember the information

00:51:08.370 --> 00:51:11.640
and somewhat surprisingly
or perhaps not surprisingly,

00:51:11.640 --> 00:51:13.470
I would often fall in
love with the information.

00:51:13.470 --> 00:51:14.990
I find that that was my favorite class.

00:51:14.990 --> 00:51:17.100
So it was what I wanted to learn the most.

00:51:17.100 --> 00:51:19.860
So that's one way you
can do it artificially,

00:51:19.860 --> 00:51:22.000
but kids with ADHD, they
can't do that, right?

00:51:22.000 --> 00:51:23.110
They're told to sit still

00:51:23.110 --> 00:51:25.310
and they end up getting up 11 times.

00:51:25.310 --> 00:51:28.460
They are told that they
can't speak out in class

00:51:28.460 --> 00:51:31.660
or that they have to remain
in their seats for 10 minutes

00:51:31.660 --> 00:51:33.800
and they just, despite their best effort,

00:51:33.800 --> 00:51:35.090
they simply cannot do it,

00:51:35.090 --> 00:51:37.190
they're highly distractable.

00:51:37.190 --> 00:51:39.380
So what are we to make
of this whole picture

00:51:39.380 --> 00:51:42.710
that we need more dopamine,
but these kids with ADHD,

00:51:42.710 --> 00:51:45.230
they're getting their
dopamine by way of a drug,

00:51:45.230 --> 00:51:47.970
which is for all the
world amphetamines, right?

00:51:47.970 --> 00:51:50.180
It's speed, that's really what it is.

00:51:50.180 --> 00:51:51.520
What are the long-term consequences,

00:51:51.520 --> 00:51:55.810
where the short-term consequences
and what should we make of

00:51:55.810 --> 00:51:58.210
people taking these drugs
without a clinical need?

00:51:58.210 --> 00:52:00.100
What are the consequences there?

00:52:00.100 --> 00:52:02.360
Well, in order to get to
some of those answers,

00:52:02.360 --> 00:52:04.290
I went to one of my colleagues,

00:52:04.290 --> 00:52:05.720
this is a colleague
that I've actually known

00:52:05.720 --> 00:52:08.300
for a very long time, I was
their teaching assistant

00:52:08.300 --> 00:52:10.150
when they were an undergraduate,

00:52:10.150 --> 00:52:12.980
they went on to get an
MD, a medical degree,

00:52:12.980 --> 00:52:17.980
as well as a PhD and become
a pediatric neurologist

00:52:18.200 --> 00:52:21.040
that specializes in the
treatment of epilepsy

00:52:21.040 --> 00:52:25.720
and ADHD in kids of all
ages, from age three to 21,

00:52:25.720 --> 00:52:26.553
that's the age range,

00:52:26.553 --> 00:52:30.210
pretty broad age range and has
extensive knowledge in this

00:52:30.210 --> 00:52:34.530
and what makes them particularly
interesting for sake of

00:52:34.530 --> 00:52:38.210
this discussion is that they
have a child, a young boy,

00:52:38.210 --> 00:52:40.800
who's now showing signs of ADHD

00:52:40.800 --> 00:52:43.970
and they are on the
threshold of trying to decide

00:52:43.970 --> 00:52:47.260
whether or not they
will prescribe Adderall

00:52:47.260 --> 00:52:48.403
or something similar.

00:52:49.240 --> 00:52:51.340
So we had a discussion about this

00:52:51.340 --> 00:52:56.220
and prior to learning that
their child may have ADHD.

00:52:56.220 --> 00:52:57.810
I asked the following questions.

00:52:57.810 --> 00:52:58.900
First of all, I asked,

00:52:58.900 --> 00:53:02.250
what do you think about
giving young kids amphetamine?

00:53:02.250 --> 00:53:07.250
And their answer was, on the
face of it, it seems crazy,

00:53:08.030 --> 00:53:12.080
but provided that the
lowest possible dose is used

00:53:12.080 --> 00:53:15.810
and that that dosage is
modulating as they grow older

00:53:15.810 --> 00:53:18.548
and develop those powers of attention,

00:53:18.548 --> 00:53:22.730
their observation was that
they've seen more kids benefit

00:53:22.730 --> 00:53:25.540
than not benefit from that.

00:53:25.540 --> 00:53:27.730
Now I'm certainly not saying
what people should do.

00:53:27.730 --> 00:53:29.160
You obviously have to go to a doctor

00:53:29.160 --> 00:53:31.380
because as I always say, I'm not a doctor,

00:53:31.380 --> 00:53:32.340
I don't prescribe anything,

00:53:32.340 --> 00:53:34.010
I'm a professor so I profess things

00:53:34.010 --> 00:53:35.950
and here I'm professing that
you talk to your doctor,

00:53:35.950 --> 00:53:39.150
if you're considering
giving Ritalin or Adderall

00:53:39.150 --> 00:53:41.470
or any type of stimulant
to your child, of course,

00:53:41.470 --> 00:53:44.040
what could be more important
than the health of your child.

00:53:44.040 --> 00:53:46.090
But it was a very
interesting answer because

00:53:46.090 --> 00:53:48.610
typically we hear yes,
medicator don't medicate.

00:53:48.610 --> 00:53:51.268
Rarely do we hear that the
medication should be adjusted

00:53:51.268 --> 00:53:54.650
across the lifespan and in
any particular kind of way.

00:53:54.650 --> 00:53:56.380
Now the fact that this person,

00:53:56.380 --> 00:53:58.966
this now friend of mine
and colleague of mine

00:53:58.966 --> 00:54:02.487
has so much expertise in
the way that the brain works

00:54:02.487 --> 00:54:06.690
and is considering putting
their child on such medication.

00:54:06.690 --> 00:54:09.910
I said, why wouldn't you wait

00:54:09.910 --> 00:54:11.500
until your kid reaches puberty?

00:54:11.500 --> 00:54:14.690
I mean, we know that in boys and in girls,

00:54:14.690 --> 00:54:16.110
there are increases in testosterone

00:54:16.110 --> 00:54:17.510
and estrogen during puberty,

00:54:17.510 --> 00:54:21.440
that dramatically change the
way that the body appears.

00:54:21.440 --> 00:54:23.050
But also that dramatically change

00:54:23.050 --> 00:54:26.700
the way that the brain functions
in particular we know this,

00:54:26.700 --> 00:54:30.580
that puberty triggers the
activation of so-called

00:54:30.580 --> 00:54:34.020
frontotemporal task related
executive functioning.

00:54:34.020 --> 00:54:37.270
That's just fancy science
speak for being able to focus,

00:54:37.270 --> 00:54:38.610
being able to direct your attention,

00:54:38.610 --> 00:54:41.500
being able to control your
impulses, look at a small child,

00:54:41.500 --> 00:54:44.300
or look at a puppy and then
look at an older child,

00:54:44.300 --> 00:54:46.490
or look at a dog, very different levels,

00:54:46.490 --> 00:54:47.920
patterns of spontaneous behavior.

00:54:47.920 --> 00:54:49.840
Young children move around a lot they're,

00:54:49.840 --> 00:54:50.673
I don't want to say shifty,

00:54:50.673 --> 00:54:52.570
cause that makes it sound like
they're up to something bad,

00:54:52.570 --> 00:54:53.510
which they might be,

00:54:53.510 --> 00:54:55.520
but they don't have to
be up to something bad,

00:54:55.520 --> 00:54:56.550
they fidget a lot.

00:54:56.550 --> 00:54:57.383
So to puppies,

00:54:57.383 --> 00:55:00.500
everything's a stimulus as
animals and humans get older,

00:55:00.500 --> 00:55:04.270
they learn how to control
their behavior and sit, still,

00:55:04.270 --> 00:55:07.570
listen and focus even
if they don't want to.

00:55:07.570 --> 00:55:12.380
So giving a drug that allows
a child to access that

00:55:12.380 --> 00:55:16.300
stillness early on it's
thought will allow them

00:55:16.300 --> 00:55:19.640
to maintain that ability as time goes on.

00:55:19.640 --> 00:55:21.570
But I decided to push
a little bit further,

00:55:21.570 --> 00:55:25.090
I said, well, why would you do it now

00:55:25.090 --> 00:55:28.460
as opposed to during
puberty or after puberty?

00:55:28.460 --> 00:55:30.580
And their answer was very specific

00:55:30.580 --> 00:55:33.530
and I think very important,
what they said was look,

00:55:33.530 --> 00:55:37.210
neuroplasticity is greatest in childhood

00:55:37.210 --> 00:55:40.350
and tapers off after about age 25,

00:55:40.350 --> 00:55:45.350
but neuroplasticity from
age three until age 12 or 13

00:55:45.540 --> 00:55:49.040
is exceedingly high and they're right,

00:55:49.040 --> 00:55:49.900
when you sit back

00:55:49.900 --> 00:55:52.090
and you look at the
literature on neuroplasticity,

00:55:52.090 --> 00:55:54.670
you'd say childhood plasticity
and young adult plasticity

00:55:54.670 --> 00:55:57.010
is much greater than adult plasticity,

00:55:57.010 --> 00:56:00.330
but that early childhood
plasticity is far and away

00:56:00.330 --> 00:56:03.460
the period in which you
can reshape the brain

00:56:03.460 --> 00:56:05.420
at an accelerated rate.

00:56:05.420 --> 00:56:08.860
So this lines up really well
with the clinical literature.

00:56:08.860 --> 00:56:09.693
Not surprisingly,

00:56:09.693 --> 00:56:13.510
there are clinician that
early treatment is key.

00:56:13.510 --> 00:56:16.560
If you have the opportunity to
work with a quality physician

00:56:16.560 --> 00:56:18.430
and treat these things early,

00:56:18.430 --> 00:56:21.130
these drugs can allow
these frontal circuits,

00:56:21.130 --> 00:56:24.900
these task-related circuits
to achieve their appropriate

00:56:24.900 --> 00:56:27.840
levels of functioning and for
kids to learn how to focus

00:56:27.840 --> 00:56:30.430
in a variety of different contexts.

00:56:30.430 --> 00:56:33.360
Now, is that the only thing
that they should be doing?

00:56:33.360 --> 00:56:34.350
Of course not.

00:56:34.350 --> 00:56:36.660
So the next question I asked was

00:56:36.660 --> 00:56:40.060
what should we make of all
this diet related stuff, right?

00:56:40.060 --> 00:56:44.300
I've heard before that the
so-called elimination diet

00:56:44.300 --> 00:56:48.860
or ingesting no sugars
or no dairy or no gluten,

00:56:48.860 --> 00:56:51.010
that all of these things
have been purported

00:56:51.010 --> 00:56:56.010
to improve symptoms of ADHD and
people and parents with ADHD

00:56:56.040 --> 00:57:00.230
go to fanatic lanes to try
and find the exact foods

00:57:00.230 --> 00:57:03.540
that are causing problems
and the exact foods

00:57:03.540 --> 00:57:05.660
that the kids can eat in order to try

00:57:05.660 --> 00:57:07.310
and get their brain wired up right,

00:57:07.310 --> 00:57:11.160
and correctly, and to avoid lifelong ADHD

00:57:12.313 --> 00:57:14.110
and their answer was really interesting.

00:57:14.110 --> 00:57:16.080
But before I tell you their answer,

00:57:16.080 --> 00:57:18.500
I want to tell you the
studies and the data

00:57:18.500 --> 00:57:21.760
related to this question
of whether or not food

00:57:21.760 --> 00:57:24.990
and the constellation
of foods that one avoids

00:57:24.990 --> 00:57:28.240
and will eat has anything to
do with our levels of attention

00:57:28.240 --> 00:57:29.073
and in particular,

00:57:29.073 --> 00:57:31.700
whether or not that can be
used as a leverage point

00:57:31.700 --> 00:57:33.470
to treat ADHD.

00:57:33.470 --> 00:57:36.320
So you can imagine the
challenges of exploring the role

00:57:36.320 --> 00:57:39.150
of diet and nutrition in any study,

00:57:39.150 --> 00:57:41.670
but especially in a study on ADHD, why?

00:57:41.670 --> 00:57:44.827
Well, because as I mentioned
before, children with ADHD,

00:57:44.827 --> 00:57:46.800
and it turns out adults with ADHD

00:57:46.800 --> 00:57:49.690
tend to pursue sugary
foods or any types of food

00:57:49.690 --> 00:57:51.560
that increase their levels of dopamine.

00:57:51.560 --> 00:57:53.090
They are naturally drawn to those foods,

00:57:53.090 --> 00:57:55.300
whether or not they realize it or not,

00:57:55.300 --> 00:57:57.160
presumably as a way to try and treat

00:57:57.160 --> 00:58:00.000
their lack of focus and impulsivity.

00:58:00.000 --> 00:58:02.500
So in this study that I'm
about to share with you,

00:58:03.350 --> 00:58:05.910
there was no drug treatment,
it was just a study,

00:58:05.910 --> 00:58:09.290
manipulating diet and
involved 100 children,

00:58:09.290 --> 00:58:12.430
50 in the so-called
elimination diet group,

00:58:12.430 --> 00:58:14.650
the special diet where
certain foods were eliminated

00:58:14.650 --> 00:58:16.690
and 50 in the so-called control group.

00:58:16.690 --> 00:58:21.420
However, being a well-designed
randomized controlled trial,

00:58:21.420 --> 00:58:23.780
this study also included a crossover,

00:58:23.780 --> 00:58:27.520
meaning where the kids would
serve as their own control

00:58:27.520 --> 00:58:30.050
or control group at a
certain portion of the study.

00:58:30.050 --> 00:58:30.883
So there'll be in one group

00:58:30.883 --> 00:58:32.170
where they eliminated certain foods

00:58:32.170 --> 00:58:33.890
and then after a period
of time in the study,

00:58:33.890 --> 00:58:35.260
they would swap to the other group.

00:58:35.260 --> 00:58:37.200
This is a powerful way to design a study

00:58:37.200 --> 00:58:38.470
for reasons that you can imagine,

00:58:38.470 --> 00:58:41.760
because you start to
eliminate changes and effects

00:58:41.760 --> 00:58:43.204
due to individual differences.

00:58:43.204 --> 00:58:46.830
In any case, 100 children
total 50 in each group

00:58:46.830 --> 00:58:48.280
at any one period in time

00:58:48.280 --> 00:58:51.766
and the effects that they
observed were extremely dramatic.

00:58:51.766 --> 00:58:55.030
In the world of statistics and
analysis of scientific data,

00:58:55.030 --> 00:58:57.210
we talk about P-values,
probability values.

00:58:57.210 --> 00:58:58.740
What's the likelihood that something

00:58:58.740 --> 00:59:00.100
could happen according to chance

00:59:00.100 --> 00:59:01.750
and typically the cutoff would be

00:59:01.750 --> 00:59:04.360
something like P less than 0.05,

00:59:04.360 --> 00:59:08.730
that's less than 0.05 chance essentially,

00:59:08.730 --> 00:59:11.810
of the effect being due to chance.

00:59:11.810 --> 00:59:13.090
However, in this study,

00:59:13.090 --> 00:59:17.520
every single one of the
effects is P less than 0.0001,

00:59:17.520 --> 00:59:19.920
very, very infant decimally small

00:59:19.920 --> 00:59:23.350
probability that the effect
observed could be due to chance.

00:59:23.350 --> 00:59:24.280
So what were these effects?

00:59:24.280 --> 00:59:26.990
These effects were
enhanced ability to focus,

00:59:26.990 --> 00:59:28.296
less impulsivity,

00:59:28.296 --> 00:59:32.790
even less tendency to move
when trying to sit still.

00:59:32.790 --> 00:59:34.270
So everything from mental focus

00:59:34.270 --> 00:59:36.440
to the ability to control
their bodies improved

00:59:36.440 --> 00:59:38.720
when they were in the
elimination diet group,

00:59:38.720 --> 00:59:39.690
what was eliminated?

00:59:39.690 --> 00:59:44.140
Well, the elimination diet
in this particular study

00:59:44.140 --> 00:59:47.560
was a so-called oligoantigenic diet.

00:59:47.560 --> 00:59:51.140
It was a diet in which each
kid took a test to determine

00:59:51.140 --> 00:59:53.940
which foods they had antibodies for,

00:59:53.940 --> 00:59:56.840
meaning that they were mildly allergic to.

00:59:56.840 --> 00:59:58.320
Now in this study, it was very important

00:59:58.320 --> 01:00:00.650
that the kids not be
extremely allergic to any food

01:00:00.650 --> 01:00:01.950
because as I mentioned before,

01:00:01.950 --> 01:00:05.370
they actually served as a
control at one point in the study

01:00:05.370 --> 01:00:06.970
where they were eating all sorts of foods,

01:00:06.970 --> 01:00:08.890
including foods that
had mild allergies to.

01:00:08.890 --> 01:00:13.890
So basically what the study
said was that eliminating foods

01:00:14.480 --> 01:00:16.350
to which children have allergies

01:00:16.350 --> 01:00:19.770
can dramatically improve
their symptoms of ADHD.

01:00:19.770 --> 01:00:21.050
And this study,

01:00:21.050 --> 01:00:22.920
not surprisingly because it was published

01:00:22.920 --> 01:00:25.460
in such a high quality
journal Lancet, et cetera,

01:00:25.460 --> 01:00:28.850
large number of subjects
set the world on fire.

01:00:28.850 --> 01:00:32.100
People were extremely
excited about these results

01:00:32.100 --> 01:00:34.466
because here in the absence
of any drug treatment,

01:00:34.466 --> 01:00:36.320
there was a significant improvement

01:00:36.320 --> 01:00:40.900
in ADHD symptoms observed
and then came the criticisms.

01:00:40.900 --> 01:00:45.440
So many papers were published
after this specifically

01:00:45.440 --> 01:00:48.050
dealing with re-analysis of these data

01:00:48.050 --> 01:00:51.210
and I want to be fair in saying that

01:00:51.210 --> 01:00:53.410
the data in the paper look good,

01:00:53.410 --> 01:00:55.110
but there are criticisms

01:00:55.110 --> 01:00:57.710
of the overall structural
design of the study.

01:00:57.710 --> 01:00:59.500
I don't want to go into
all the details exactly

01:00:59.500 --> 01:01:02.460
'cause it gets really nuanced
about some of the statistics

01:01:02.460 --> 01:01:05.750
and the way that one
examines these types of data,

01:01:05.750 --> 01:01:07.600
but there was skepticism

01:01:07.600 --> 01:01:09.440
and in science, skepticism is healthy,

01:01:09.440 --> 01:01:11.160
especially when making decisions about

01:01:11.160 --> 01:01:13.450
whether or not to treat or feed children

01:01:13.450 --> 01:01:16.150
one food or another, or give
them one drug or another.

01:01:17.290 --> 01:01:19.590
Now I want to return to
the story of my friend,

01:01:19.590 --> 01:01:23.240
who is a pediatric
neurologist and treats ADHD

01:01:23.240 --> 01:01:26.440
and has a child who is on the precipice of

01:01:26.440 --> 01:01:29.450
perhaps starting to take drugs
for the treatment of ADHD.

01:01:29.450 --> 01:01:33.780
I asked the simple question,
do you see an effect of diet?

01:01:33.780 --> 01:01:37.700
Meaning when parents control
the diet of their children,

01:01:37.700 --> 01:01:41.310
does it make a positive or
negative or no difference in

01:01:41.310 --> 01:01:44.135
terms of the way that
the kids respond to ADHD,

01:01:44.135 --> 01:01:47.330
drugs like Ritalin and
Adderall or whether or not

01:01:47.330 --> 01:01:49.990
it can help them avoid treating
with those drugs entirely?

01:01:49.990 --> 01:01:53.060
And her response was very
straightforward, she said,

01:01:53.060 --> 01:01:54.940
elimination of simple sugars

01:01:54.940 --> 01:01:56.990
has a dramatic and positive effect.

01:01:56.990 --> 01:01:59.370
She's observed that over
and over and over again

01:01:59.370 --> 01:02:03.360
in many dozens, if not
hundreds of patients, okay?

01:02:03.360 --> 01:02:04.850
Now that's not a peer reviewed study,

01:02:04.850 --> 01:02:07.150
that's a statement that I'm
conveying to you anecdotally,

01:02:07.150 --> 01:02:09.163
but it's a highly, highly informed one.

01:02:10.160 --> 01:02:12.780
I said, what about
these elimination diets?

01:02:12.780 --> 01:02:15.550
She said, and I found other
sources to support this,

01:02:15.550 --> 01:02:18.540
that these oligoantigenic
diets are controversial.

01:02:18.540 --> 01:02:21.130
There are many people who really believe

01:02:21.130 --> 01:02:23.760
in identifying all the things
that you're allergic to

01:02:23.760 --> 01:02:25.390
and making sure that you

01:02:25.390 --> 01:02:27.570
and especially your
kids avoid those foods.

01:02:27.570 --> 01:02:30.630
However, there's another camp
that's starting to emerge

01:02:30.630 --> 01:02:33.670
in the peer reviewed
scientific literature,

01:02:33.670 --> 01:02:37.590
showing that when kids are
not exposed to certain foods

01:02:37.590 --> 01:02:39.849
in particular nuts and
things of that sort,

01:02:39.849 --> 01:02:42.700
they develop allergies to those foods

01:02:42.700 --> 01:02:44.290
and then when exposed to them later,

01:02:44.290 --> 01:02:45.400
they cause real problems.

01:02:45.400 --> 01:02:48.960
So there's a whole galaxy of
discussion and controversy

01:02:48.960 --> 01:02:51.130
and outright fighting about allergies

01:02:51.130 --> 01:02:53.230
and kids and whether or
not the oligoantigenic diet

01:02:53.230 --> 01:02:54.130
is the appropriate one.

01:02:54.130 --> 01:02:58.430
However, out of the four
neurologists and psychiatrists

01:02:58.430 --> 01:03:01.660
that I spoke to about ADHD
in preparation for this,

01:03:01.660 --> 01:03:04.670
every single one said children with ADHD,

01:03:04.670 --> 01:03:05.750
as much as possible,

01:03:05.750 --> 01:03:08.970
should be encouraged to avoid high sugar

01:03:08.970 --> 01:03:11.380
and simple sugar foods of most kinds

01:03:11.380 --> 01:03:14.720
and if they can find particular foods

01:03:14.720 --> 01:03:16.410
that exacerbate their symptoms,

01:03:16.410 --> 01:03:20.410
obviously eliminating
those foods is beneficial

01:03:20.410 --> 01:03:23.610
and the foods that
exacerbate their symptoms

01:03:23.610 --> 01:03:25.527
change over time.

01:03:25.527 --> 01:03:28.750
So I don't like giving
a complicated answer,

01:03:28.750 --> 01:03:31.340
but I also don't like
giving an incomplete answer.

01:03:31.340 --> 01:03:34.740
What this tells me is that children,

01:03:34.740 --> 01:03:37.930
especially young children who have ADHD

01:03:37.930 --> 01:03:41.500
should probably not eat much sugar

01:03:41.500 --> 01:03:43.250
in particular simple sugars.

01:03:43.250 --> 01:03:44.710
In addition to that,

01:03:44.710 --> 01:03:47.760
exploring whether or not
they have existing allergies

01:03:47.760 --> 01:03:52.210
to foods, they already
consume might be a good idea.

01:03:52.210 --> 01:03:53.870
At least that's what this paper,

01:03:53.870 --> 01:03:56.580
the Pelsser et. al Lancet
paper seems to speak to

01:03:56.580 --> 01:03:59.920
and I should mention that that
paper was published in 2011.

01:03:59.920 --> 01:04:03.620
Since then there have been many
dozens of studies exploring

01:04:03.620 --> 01:04:06.510
the same thing, as well as
meta analysis of all those data

01:04:06.510 --> 01:04:09.360
and it does appear that diet can have

01:04:09.360 --> 01:04:13.250
a highly significant role in eliminating

01:04:13.250 --> 01:04:15.360
or at least reducing the symptoms of ADHD

01:04:15.360 --> 01:04:17.750
so much so that some of the children

01:04:17.750 --> 01:04:19.760
are able to not take medication at all,

01:04:19.760 --> 01:04:23.000
or eventually wean
themselves off medication

01:04:23.000 --> 01:04:25.720
as young adults and as adults.

01:04:25.720 --> 01:04:28.520
One interesting question
is whether or not adults

01:04:28.520 --> 01:04:31.480
should modify their diet in order to

01:04:31.480 --> 01:04:32.720
increase their levels of focus,

01:04:32.720 --> 01:04:35.550
if they're already having
normal levels of focus,

01:04:35.550 --> 01:04:37.980
but we'd like more or would like to reduce

01:04:37.980 --> 01:04:42.550
existing adult ADHD,
that's an interesting,

01:04:42.550 --> 01:04:44.770
and even more controversial topic,

01:04:44.770 --> 01:04:47.260
it brings us right into the
realm of what are called

01:04:47.260 --> 01:04:48.640
omega-3 fatty acids.

01:04:48.640 --> 01:04:50.730
I've talked many times
on this podcast about

01:04:50.730 --> 01:04:54.530
the known benefits of omega-3
fatty acids in particular,

01:04:54.530 --> 01:04:58.710
getting a one gram 1000 milligrams or more

01:04:58.710 --> 01:05:01.550
even as much as 2000
milligrams each day of

01:05:01.550 --> 01:05:06.070
the so-called EPA component
of omega-3 fatty acids

01:05:06.070 --> 01:05:08.630
known to have antidepressant effects,

01:05:08.630 --> 01:05:09.660
mood elevating effects,

01:05:09.660 --> 01:05:13.120
known to have important effects

01:05:13.120 --> 01:05:15.600
protecting the cardiovascular system.

01:05:15.600 --> 01:05:18.860
I think it's now clear that
the immune system also benefits

01:05:18.860 --> 01:05:23.860
that omega-3 fatty acids that
include a gram or more of EPA

01:05:24.140 --> 01:05:25.910
that are very beneficial typically

01:05:25.910 --> 01:05:27.110
that's done through fish oil,

01:05:27.110 --> 01:05:29.120
liquid fish oil is going to
be the most cost efficient,

01:05:29.120 --> 01:05:30.470
but they're capsule forms

01:05:30.470 --> 01:05:33.100
for those of you that don't like fish oil,

01:05:33.100 --> 01:05:34.330
you can ingest this through other means

01:05:34.330 --> 01:05:36.960
you can get it from certain
algaes or krill, et cetera.

01:05:36.960 --> 01:05:40.700
You have to make it compatible
with your particular diet,

01:05:40.700 --> 01:05:41.533
whether or not you're vegan

01:05:41.533 --> 01:05:43.320
or vegetarian or omnivore, et cetera.

01:05:44.500 --> 01:05:45.600
Omega-3s have shown,

01:05:45.600 --> 01:05:48.490
been shown to have all these
positive health benefits.

01:05:48.490 --> 01:05:52.270
Do they have positive effects
on focus and attention?

01:05:52.270 --> 01:05:55.050
And the answer is you can find studies

01:05:55.050 --> 01:05:59.350
that support that statement and
the effects are significant,

01:05:59.350 --> 01:06:01.283
but the effects are modest.

01:06:02.390 --> 01:06:06.350
You can also find studies
that show no effect,

01:06:06.350 --> 01:06:11.107
however much like with
omega-3s and antidepressants,

01:06:11.107 --> 01:06:16.107
whereby ingestion of omega-3
fatty acids of a gram or

01:06:17.250 --> 01:06:20.170
more of EPA per day allows
people with major depression

01:06:20.170 --> 01:06:21.960
to get away with taking lower doses

01:06:21.960 --> 01:06:23.790
of antidepressant medication.

01:06:23.790 --> 01:06:28.650
It does seem that ingestion of
omega-3 fatty acids in adults

01:06:30.220 --> 01:06:33.920
that include EPA is of
1000 milligrams or more

01:06:33.920 --> 01:06:36.050
can allow adults with ADHD

01:06:36.050 --> 01:06:38.600
or mild attention deficit issues

01:06:38.600 --> 01:06:43.600
to function well on
lower doses of medication

01:06:43.880 --> 01:06:47.390
and in rare cases to
eliminate medication entirely.

01:06:47.390 --> 01:06:49.400
So what this says is once again,

01:06:49.400 --> 01:06:51.630
that the omega-3 fatty
acids are beneficial,

01:06:51.630 --> 01:06:54.810
will they cure or eliminate ADHD?

01:06:54.810 --> 01:06:57.070
I think it's safe to say, no,

01:06:57.070 --> 01:06:58.420
they are playing a supportive

01:06:58.420 --> 01:07:00.730
or what we call a modulatory role.

01:07:00.730 --> 01:07:02.250
Just like good sleep,

01:07:02.250 --> 01:07:04.360
plays a supportive and modulatory role

01:07:04.360 --> 01:07:06.310
for essentially everything,
your immune system,

01:07:06.310 --> 01:07:08.500
your ability to think your
ability to regulate your emotion,

01:07:08.500 --> 01:07:10.830
it's modulating that process.

01:07:10.830 --> 01:07:13.010
This component of modulation

01:07:13.010 --> 01:07:14.880
is extremely important to highlight

01:07:14.880 --> 01:07:17.079
and I think I want to spend
a moment on it because

01:07:17.079 --> 01:07:20.560
this is especially important
in the context of ADHD

01:07:20.560 --> 01:07:22.920
and all the information that's out there.

01:07:22.920 --> 01:07:26.190
There are biological
processes that are mediated

01:07:26.190 --> 01:07:28.940
by particular compounds like dopamine.

01:07:28.940 --> 01:07:31.510
So for instance, the
ability to feel motivated,

01:07:31.510 --> 01:07:35.890
to attend to focus is mediated
by the circuits in the brain

01:07:35.890 --> 01:07:38.440
that release dopamine.

01:07:38.440 --> 01:07:42.730
However, attention is also
modulating by how rested you are.

01:07:42.730 --> 01:07:45.800
If you want to eliminate your
ability to think well at all,

01:07:45.800 --> 01:07:48.690
just stay up for two nights
and don't sleep at all right?

01:07:48.690 --> 01:07:49.740
If you do that,

01:07:49.740 --> 01:07:52.350
you will have modulating
the circuits in your brain

01:07:52.350 --> 01:07:55.320
that respond to various things

01:07:55.320 --> 01:07:57.020
and you will be highly distractible.

01:07:57.020 --> 01:07:58.170
You'll be highly emotional.

01:07:58.170 --> 01:07:59.630
You will feel like garbage,

01:07:59.630 --> 01:08:02.260
but that doesn't mean that sleep mediates,

01:08:02.260 --> 01:08:03.440
focus and attention.

01:08:03.440 --> 01:08:06.090
It modulates it indirectly.

01:08:06.090 --> 01:08:08.480
Likewise, I think these
omega-3 fatty acids

01:08:09.450 --> 01:08:12.370
in particular the EPA is which
are so beneficial for mood

01:08:12.370 --> 01:08:14.730
and apparently also for attention,

01:08:14.730 --> 01:08:18.490
they directly mediate attention and mood,

01:08:18.490 --> 01:08:20.640
what they do is they
modulate those circuits,

01:08:20.640 --> 01:08:23.160
they make dopamine more available.

01:08:23.160 --> 01:08:25.240
They make whatever dopamine is available,

01:08:25.240 --> 01:08:28.520
more likely to bind to
the various receptors

01:08:28.520 --> 01:08:30.680
that are present on neurons and so forth

01:08:30.680 --> 01:08:33.630
and I think this is very
important because likewise diet

01:08:33.630 --> 01:08:35.300
in any discussion about nutrition

01:08:35.300 --> 01:08:38.490
has to include this
framework of is the diet,

01:08:38.490 --> 01:08:39.600
the elimination diet,

01:08:39.600 --> 01:08:42.580
or whether or not it's some
other diet or esoteric diet,

01:08:42.580 --> 01:08:46.160
ketogenic diet, is it modulating
or mediating a process?

01:08:46.160 --> 01:08:48.810
And most likely in the context of ADHD,

01:08:48.810 --> 01:08:51.000
it's modulating that process.

01:08:51.000 --> 01:08:54.370
So if the ADHD is mild or
if it's caught early enough,

01:08:54.370 --> 01:08:57.720
or if it's in conjunction
with pharmacology

01:08:57.720 --> 01:08:59.310
with a prescription treatment,

01:08:59.310 --> 01:09:01.910
well, then it might help
guide the child or adult

01:09:01.910 --> 01:09:03.990
to a better place of being able to focus.

01:09:03.990 --> 01:09:07.170
But it's not going to be the
switch that flips everything.

01:09:07.170 --> 01:09:10.810
Now that does not mean that
consuming the wrong foods,

01:09:10.810 --> 01:09:13.160
sugary foods or foods that
you happen to be allergic to

01:09:13.160 --> 01:09:16.100
is a good idea it will
still be detrimental.

01:09:16.100 --> 01:09:18.010
So I hope that conceptual framework helps

01:09:18.010 --> 01:09:19.100
because if you go online,

01:09:19.100 --> 01:09:20.420
if you're somebody with ADHD

01:09:20.420 --> 01:09:24.500
or not your going to be
bombarded with the ADHD diet,

01:09:24.500 --> 01:09:27.810
the oligoantigenic diet,
the elimination this,

01:09:27.810 --> 01:09:29.260
this supplement that EPA

01:09:29.260 --> 01:09:31.565
and I think it's very important
to understand whether or not

01:09:31.565 --> 01:09:34.590
you're talking about
something mediating a process

01:09:34.590 --> 01:09:36.310
or modulating a process.

01:09:36.310 --> 01:09:38.880
Now drugs like Ritalin,
drugs like Adderall,

01:09:38.880 --> 01:09:40.260
they are tapping into the circuitries

01:09:40.260 --> 01:09:45.260
and the neurochemistries that
mediate attention and focus.

01:09:45.360 --> 01:09:48.430
They are not the only
alternatives or the only choices

01:09:48.430 --> 01:09:50.380
rather for treatment of these circuits

01:09:50.380 --> 01:09:52.240
and enhancement of the circuits for focus.

01:09:52.240 --> 01:09:54.010
I'm going to talk about other alternatives

01:09:54.010 --> 01:09:56.020
and some behavioral alternatives

01:09:56.020 --> 01:09:57.460
that are not very well known,

01:09:57.460 --> 01:10:00.960
but are very, very
effective in a few minutes.

01:10:00.960 --> 01:10:03.500
But I really want to make
this clear distinction

01:10:03.500 --> 01:10:05.640
between modulation and mediation,

01:10:05.640 --> 01:10:09.170
because it's vital for anyone
that's trying to modulate

01:10:09.170 --> 01:10:11.630
or mediate anything
within their own brain.

01:10:11.630 --> 01:10:14.400
If any of you are interested
in this oligoantigenic diet,

01:10:14.400 --> 01:10:16.267
as it relates to ADHD,

01:10:16.267 --> 01:10:19.720
and you want to explore
a more recent study

01:10:19.720 --> 01:10:22.780
besides that classic 2011 Lancet study,

01:10:22.780 --> 01:10:23.870
that's rather controversial.

01:10:23.870 --> 01:10:25.970
There's a paper that was
published in frontiers

01:10:25.970 --> 01:10:29.090
in psychiatry just last year, 2020.

01:10:29.090 --> 01:10:30.470
The title of the paper is,

01:10:30.470 --> 01:10:33.450
"Oligoantigenic diet
improves children's ADHD

01:10:33.450 --> 01:10:37.760
rating scale scores reliably
in added video rating."

01:10:37.760 --> 01:10:39.590
The added video rating is
just that they're using

01:10:39.590 --> 01:10:43.300
an additional measure
of focus and attention.

01:10:43.300 --> 01:10:46.220
Again, that's Frontiers
in psychiatry, 2020,

01:10:46.220 --> 01:10:48.290
I'll put a link to it in the caption,

01:10:48.290 --> 01:10:51.110
and that's a more recent
study for you to peruse.

01:10:51.110 --> 01:10:53.140
So we've talked about the
neural circuits of focus

01:10:53.140 --> 01:10:55.240
and the chemistry of focus,

01:10:55.240 --> 01:10:59.440
but we haven't talked yet
about what would make us better

