01:13:03.860 --> 01:13:06.240
and it's visual search for an object

01:13:06.240 --> 01:13:07.340
that has distinct features,

01:13:07.340 --> 01:13:10.970
but is embedded in this
ocean of other things that

01:13:10.970 --> 01:13:12.750
could easily be confused as Waldo.

01:13:12.750 --> 01:13:13.583
So you tend to look, look,

01:13:13.583 --> 01:13:14.890
look, look, look, look, look, look, look,

01:13:14.890 --> 01:13:16.600
and then you find Waldo.

01:13:16.600 --> 01:13:18.260
Kids can do this they enjoy doing this.

01:13:18.260 --> 01:13:19.730
Adults may or may not enjoy it,

01:13:19.730 --> 01:13:21.160
but they can do it too.

01:13:21.160 --> 01:13:24.220
They find Waldo, when you find Waldo

01:13:24.220 --> 01:13:26.170
or when you search for a target

01:13:26.170 --> 01:13:29.350
in some other visual
search task at that moment,

01:13:29.350 --> 01:13:31.970
your nervous system
celebrates a little bit

01:13:31.970 --> 01:13:34.760
and it celebrates through
the release of neurochemicals

01:13:34.760 --> 01:13:38.300
that make you feel good,
you found it and you pause.

01:13:38.300 --> 01:13:41.810
Now, the pause is interesting
because when you pause,

01:13:41.810 --> 01:13:45.160
what we know from many experiments is that

01:13:45.160 --> 01:13:48.810
in that moment of pause
and mild celebration,

01:13:48.810 --> 01:13:53.810
however, mild you are not
able to see another Waldo

01:13:54.320 --> 01:13:56.170
sitting right next to it.

01:13:56.170 --> 01:13:59.410
So what this means is in
attending to something

01:13:59.410 --> 01:14:03.990
in searching and in
identifying a visual target

01:14:03.990 --> 01:14:07.220
your attention blinked
it shut off for a second

01:14:07.220 --> 01:14:10.970
and there's a more formal
and more laboratory type

01:14:10.970 --> 01:14:12.293
way that we look at this.

01:14:13.260 --> 01:14:16.640
The more typical way to
do this is to give someone

01:14:16.640 --> 01:14:19.530
a string of letters or a string of numbers

01:14:19.530 --> 01:14:23.700
and beforehand you tell them
be on the lookout for the

01:14:23.700 --> 01:14:27.350
letters R and Z, okay?

01:14:27.350 --> 01:14:30.110
You're just going to watch
this string of numbers go by

01:14:30.110 --> 01:14:31.880
and there will be a letter R in there,

01:14:31.880 --> 01:14:33.800
and there will be a letter Z in there

01:14:33.800 --> 01:14:35.810
and try and spot them both

01:14:36.760 --> 01:14:38.740
and what you find is when you present

01:14:38.740 --> 01:14:42.270
that string of numbers,
and then they see the R,

01:14:42.270 --> 01:14:45.917
they see the R they
register it consciously

01:14:45.917 --> 01:14:48.930
and they tend to miss the Z,

01:14:48.930 --> 01:14:51.440
just like in the Waldo type example.

01:14:51.440 --> 01:14:53.610
Now, of course the numbers
are going by pretty quickly,

01:14:53.610 --> 01:14:55.133
but they can spot the R.

01:14:56.220 --> 01:14:57.620
They could also spot the Z,

01:14:57.620 --> 01:15:00.730
if you told them
beforehand, just spot the Z

01:15:00.730 --> 01:15:02.780
and the numbers are moving
through at the same rate

01:15:02.780 --> 01:15:03.613
in both conditions.

01:15:03.613 --> 01:15:05.950
So what that means is that in every case,

01:15:05.950 --> 01:15:10.260
you are capable of seeing the R or the Z

01:15:10.260 --> 01:15:13.990
it's when you try and see
both that seeing the first one

01:15:13.990 --> 01:15:16.450
prevents you from seeing the second one,

01:15:16.450 --> 01:15:19.210
it's what we call an attentional blink.

01:15:19.210 --> 01:15:21.010
We do this all the time

01:15:21.010 --> 01:15:25.460
and people with ADHD
tend to have many more

01:15:25.460 --> 01:15:27.560
attentional blinks than people that don't

01:15:27.560 --> 01:15:29.810
and this is true for
children and for adults.

01:15:30.770 --> 01:15:32.090
This is an important point.

01:15:32.090 --> 01:15:34.090
So important that I want
to emphasize it twice

01:15:34.090 --> 01:15:36.570
in case you attentionally blinked.

01:15:36.570 --> 01:15:39.090
If you see something
that you're looking for,

01:15:39.090 --> 01:15:40.890
or you're very interested in something,

01:15:40.890 --> 01:15:43.510
you are definitely
missing other information

01:15:45.130 --> 01:15:47.960
in part because you're
over focusing on something

01:15:47.960 --> 01:15:50.320
and this leads to a very
interesting hypothesis

01:15:50.320 --> 01:15:53.440
about what might go wrong in ADHD,

01:15:53.440 --> 01:15:56.550
where we've always thought
that they cannot focus

01:15:56.550 --> 01:15:58.360
and yet we know they can focus on things

01:15:58.360 --> 01:16:00.450
they care very much about,

01:16:00.450 --> 01:16:03.060
well, maybe just maybe

01:16:03.060 --> 01:16:06.180
they are experiencing
more attentional blinks

01:16:06.180 --> 01:16:09.040
than people who do not have ADHD

01:16:09.040 --> 01:16:12.470
and indeed, there are data
now to support the possibility

01:16:12.470 --> 01:16:14.240
that that's actually what's happening

01:16:14.240 --> 01:16:16.930
and that should be exciting
to anyone that has ADHD.

01:16:16.930 --> 01:16:18.990
It should also be exciting
to anyone that cares about

01:16:18.990 --> 01:16:22.130
increasing their focus and
their ability to attend.

01:16:22.130 --> 01:16:23.780
What this is saying is
that these circuits,

01:16:23.780 --> 01:16:26.410
that underlie focus in
our ability to attend

01:16:26.410 --> 01:16:28.583
and our ability to eliminate distraction,

01:16:30.050 --> 01:16:32.110
they aren't just failing to focus.

01:16:32.110 --> 01:16:35.470
That's just a semantic way
of describing the outcome.

01:16:35.470 --> 01:16:37.640
They are over focusing on certain things

01:16:37.640 --> 01:16:39.610
and thereby missing other things.

01:16:39.610 --> 01:16:42.650
And so our distractability
or the distractability

01:16:42.650 --> 01:16:46.280
of somebody with ADHD could exist because

01:16:46.280 --> 01:16:49.430
they are over focusing on certain elements

01:16:49.430 --> 01:16:51.220
and there are there for missing

01:16:51.220 --> 01:16:53.940
other elements that they
should be attending to.

01:16:53.940 --> 01:16:57.540
So what they really need is this property

01:16:57.540 --> 01:16:59.070
that we call open monitoring.

01:16:59.070 --> 01:17:00.720
Now open monitoring is something

01:17:00.720 --> 01:17:02.840
that's described in the
book that I just referred to

01:17:02.840 --> 01:17:05.420
and that typically is
associated with people

01:17:05.420 --> 01:17:07.580
who have done a lot of meditation,

01:17:07.580 --> 01:17:09.250
so called Vipassana meditation,

01:17:09.250 --> 01:17:12.350
or have spent a lot of
time learning how to

01:17:12.350 --> 01:17:15.310
do what's called open gaze visual analysis

01:17:15.310 --> 01:17:16.330
and open gaze thinking.

01:17:16.330 --> 01:17:17.780
But there's a simpler version of this

01:17:17.780 --> 01:17:19.760
that allows us to bypass all that.

01:17:19.760 --> 01:17:20.623
First of all,

01:17:22.930 --> 01:17:26.770
your visual system has
two modes of processing.

01:17:26.770 --> 01:17:28.920
It can be highly focused,
a soda straw view.

01:17:28.920 --> 01:17:31.390
So looking for the R in
this string of numbers

01:17:31.390 --> 01:17:33.050
in the example that I just gave,

01:17:33.050 --> 01:17:35.006
or if you're very excited about something

01:17:35.006 --> 01:17:36.460
you're in that soda
straw view of the world,

01:17:36.460 --> 01:17:38.010
and you're missing other things, okay,

01:17:38.010 --> 01:17:40.350
that's high levels of attention.

01:17:40.350 --> 01:17:43.390
However, there's also a
property of your visual system

01:17:43.390 --> 01:17:45.070
that allows you to dilate your gaze,

01:17:45.070 --> 01:17:47.340
to be in so-called panoramic vision.

01:17:47.340 --> 01:17:49.410
Panoramic vision is something
you can do right now,

01:17:49.410 --> 01:17:51.940
no matter where you are,
and I can do it right now,

01:17:51.940 --> 01:17:53.250
you won't know that I'm doing it,

01:17:53.250 --> 01:17:56.420
but even though I'm still
looking directly at you,

01:17:56.420 --> 01:17:59.060
I'm consciously dilating my
gaze so that I can see the

01:17:59.060 --> 01:18:01.180
ceiling, the floor and
the walls all around me.

01:18:01.180 --> 01:18:03.710
That panoramic vision
is actually mediated by

01:18:03.710 --> 01:18:06.900
a separate stream or
set of neural circuits

01:18:06.900 --> 01:18:08.490
going from the eye into the brain

01:18:08.490 --> 01:18:10.970
and it's a stream or set of circuits

01:18:10.970 --> 01:18:13.220
that isn't just wide angle view.

01:18:13.220 --> 01:18:16.280
It also is better at
processing things in time.

01:18:16.280 --> 01:18:18.200
Its frame rate is higher.

01:18:18.200 --> 01:18:20.120
So you've seen slow motion video,

01:18:20.120 --> 01:18:21.780
and you've seen standard video,

01:18:21.780 --> 01:18:26.650
slow motion video gives
you that slow motion look,

01:18:26.650 --> 01:18:28.070
because it's a higher frame rate.

01:18:28.070 --> 01:18:30.893
You're thin slicing time, okay?

01:18:32.300 --> 01:18:35.440
You can use panoramic
vision to access the state

01:18:35.440 --> 01:18:36.720
that we call open monitoring.

01:18:36.720 --> 01:18:38.380
When people do that,

01:18:38.380 --> 01:18:42.500
they are able to attend to and recognize

01:18:42.500 --> 01:18:46.130
multiple targets within
this string of numbers.

01:18:46.130 --> 01:18:48.230
They can see the R and they can see the Z

01:18:48.230 --> 01:18:50.180
and they can see additional things.

01:18:50.180 --> 01:18:52.690
So this is something
that can be trained up

01:18:52.690 --> 01:18:54.040
and people can practice whether or not

01:18:54.040 --> 01:18:56.170
they have ADHD or not.

01:18:56.170 --> 01:18:57.590
What involves is learning

01:18:57.590 --> 01:18:59.030
how to dilate your gaze consciously,

01:18:59.030 --> 01:19:01.470
that's actually quite
easy for most people,

01:19:01.470 --> 01:19:03.440
whether or not you wear corrective lenses

01:19:03.440 --> 01:19:04.440
or contacts or not

01:19:04.440 --> 01:19:06.290
you can consciously go into open gaze

01:19:06.290 --> 01:19:09.288
and then you can contract
your field of view as well.

01:19:09.288 --> 01:19:11.380
There have also been studies done

01:19:11.380 --> 01:19:15.980
where people were taught to
think in a particular way

01:19:15.980 --> 01:19:17.820
for a very short period of time,

01:19:17.820 --> 01:19:21.520
and that forever changed
their ability to limit

01:19:21.520 --> 01:19:24.330
or reduce the number of
these attentional blinks.

01:19:24.330 --> 01:19:26.050
There are now published
accounts in the literature

01:19:26.050 --> 01:19:29.850
of a simple practice done
for about 15 minutes,

01:19:29.850 --> 01:19:33.020
where subjects were asked to
just sit quietly eyes closed

01:19:33.020 --> 01:19:35.100
and do what is sort of akin to meditation,

01:19:35.100 --> 01:19:36.380
but to not direct their mind

01:19:36.380 --> 01:19:38.380
into any particular state or place,

01:19:38.380 --> 01:19:40.600
but simply to think about their breathing

01:19:40.600 --> 01:19:42.700
and to focus on their
so-called interoception,

01:19:42.700 --> 01:19:44.280
focus on how their body feels,

01:19:44.280 --> 01:19:46.200
their mind drifted to bring it back, okay?

01:19:46.200 --> 01:19:50.240
So it's basically meditation
for about 15 minutes.

01:19:50.240 --> 01:19:53.660
That might not seem like a
significant or unusual practice

01:19:53.660 --> 01:19:55.950
or that it would have any impact at all.

01:19:55.950 --> 01:20:00.950
But remarkably, just doing
that once for 17 minutes,

01:20:01.860 --> 01:20:05.190
significantly reduced the
number of attentional blinks

01:20:05.190 --> 01:20:06.610
that people would carry out.

01:20:06.610 --> 01:20:08.560
In other words, their focus got better

01:20:08.560 --> 01:20:12.072
in a near permanent way without
any additional training.

01:20:12.072 --> 01:20:15.440
There's something about that
practice of reducing the amount

01:20:15.440 --> 01:20:17.200
of visual information coming in

01:20:17.200 --> 01:20:19.610
and learning to pay attention
to one's internal state,

01:20:19.610 --> 01:20:23.130
what we call interoception
that allow them an awareness,

01:20:23.130 --> 01:20:26.090
such that when they needed
to look for visual targets,

01:20:26.090 --> 01:20:29.050
when they need to focus on
multiple things in sequence,

01:20:29.050 --> 01:20:30.560
they didn't experience

01:20:30.560 --> 01:20:32.560
the same number of attentional blinks

01:20:32.560 --> 01:20:36.150
and I should mention not
incidentally as people age

01:20:36.150 --> 01:20:38.250
and their working memory gets worse

01:20:38.250 --> 01:20:40.900
and their ability to focus gets worse,

01:20:40.900 --> 01:20:42.470
the number of attentional blinks

01:20:42.470 --> 01:20:44.220
that they carry out goes up,

01:20:44.220 --> 01:20:46.510
and there are now studies
exploring whether or not

01:20:46.510 --> 01:20:50.420
the simple meditation like
practice of 15 to 20 minutes

01:20:50.420 --> 01:20:53.340
or so of sitting and just quietly resting

01:20:53.340 --> 01:20:54.730
and paying attention to one's breathing

01:20:54.730 --> 01:20:57.320
and internal state can
also offset some of that

01:20:57.320 --> 01:21:01.410
age-related what is
called cognitive decline.

01:21:01.410 --> 01:21:03.850
So what these data tell me is that

01:21:03.850 --> 01:21:05.925
regardless of whether
or not you're a child

01:21:05.925 --> 01:21:07.150
or you're an adult,

01:21:07.150 --> 01:21:09.930
whether or not you have ADHD or not,

01:21:09.930 --> 01:21:11.180
whether or not you're experiencing

01:21:11.180 --> 01:21:12.730
age-related cognitive decline,

01:21:12.730 --> 01:21:14.260
or you would simply like to avoid

01:21:14.260 --> 01:21:15.893
age-related cognitive decline,

01:21:16.920 --> 01:21:20.670
a simple practice of taking 17 minutes

01:21:20.670 --> 01:21:23.780
sitting and paying attention
to your internal state,

01:21:23.780 --> 01:21:27.020
just interocepting,
registering your breathing,

01:21:27.020 --> 01:21:29.180
registering the contact of your skin

01:21:29.180 --> 01:21:31.260
with whatever surface you're on,

01:21:31.260 --> 01:21:35.600
can forever rewire your brain
to be able to attend better

01:21:35.600 --> 01:21:37.420
and possibly even offset

01:21:37.420 --> 01:21:40.143
some of that age related
attentional drift.

01:21:41.460 --> 01:21:44.930
Now, I don't expect anyone to
start meditating regularly.

01:21:44.930 --> 01:21:47.530
I don't expect anyone to do
anything they don't want to do,

01:21:47.530 --> 01:21:49.700
but I think most of us could handle

01:21:49.700 --> 01:21:53.540
one meditation's session
of 17 minutes or so

01:21:53.540 --> 01:21:56.290
and so if ever there was a
tool that stood to rewire

01:21:56.290 --> 01:21:59.060
our attentional circuitry
in a powerful way.

01:21:59.060 --> 01:22:00.750
This seems to be it

01:22:00.750 --> 01:22:05.570
and in addition, the ability
to engage in panoramic vision,

01:22:05.570 --> 01:22:06.640
to dilate our gaze,

01:22:06.640 --> 01:22:10.030
the so-called open monitoring
that allows the brain

01:22:10.030 --> 01:22:10.863
to function in a way

01:22:10.863 --> 01:22:13.240
that it can detect more
information faster,

01:22:13.240 --> 01:22:14.700
that's a powerful tool as well

01:22:14.700 --> 01:22:17.200
and the beauty of that tool is
that it works the first time

01:22:17.200 --> 01:22:19.050
and it works every time.

01:22:19.050 --> 01:22:23.387
Now, how exactly it works
is a little bit unclear.

01:22:23.387 --> 01:22:25.930
Is it for instance,

01:22:25.930 --> 01:22:29.120
orchestrating this synchrony or asynchrony

01:22:29.120 --> 01:22:30.610
between the default mode network

01:22:30.610 --> 01:22:32.750
and the task related
networks we don't know.

01:22:32.750 --> 01:22:35.370
Those studies have not
yet been carried out.

01:22:35.370 --> 01:22:37.650
Nonetheless, the effects are significant,

01:22:37.650 --> 01:22:40.930
they are long lasting
and they appear to exist

01:22:40.930 --> 01:22:43.820
after just one session of this quiet

01:22:43.820 --> 01:22:45.760
17 minute interoception,

01:22:45.760 --> 01:22:46.990
which to me makes it seem like

01:22:46.990 --> 01:22:49.830
a very worthwhile thing
to do for everybody.

01:22:49.830 --> 01:22:51.970
So we just talked about
attentional blinks,

01:22:51.970 --> 01:22:54.360
which are essentially blinks of thinking

01:22:54.360 --> 01:22:56.520
it's your mind shutting off for a moment

01:22:56.520 --> 01:22:58.690
and missing information.

01:22:58.690 --> 01:23:00.800
Now let's talk about actual blinks,

01:23:00.800 --> 01:23:03.090
the sort that you do with your eyelids.

01:23:03.090 --> 01:23:05.550
Now, this might come
across as somewhat obvious,

01:23:05.550 --> 01:23:10.050
but you can do fast, what
are called spontaneous blinks

01:23:10.050 --> 01:23:12.840
and they're always coordinated
between the two eyes

01:23:12.840 --> 01:23:14.100
or you can do long blinks

01:23:14.100 --> 01:23:15.590
like when you go to sleep at night,

01:23:15.590 --> 01:23:19.520
you do one very long blink,
and I'm not being facetious.

01:23:19.520 --> 01:23:20.510
When you go to sleep at night,

01:23:20.510 --> 01:23:23.437
you are shutting your eyelids

01:23:23.437 --> 01:23:27.530
and you are limiting the
amount of information coming in

01:23:27.530 --> 01:23:30.490
and your perception of
time starts to drift

01:23:30.490 --> 01:23:31.690
as you go into sleep.

01:23:31.690 --> 01:23:35.860
Your perception of time
changes from very fast,

01:23:35.860 --> 01:23:40.180
at one moment to very slow
meaning the frame rate

01:23:40.180 --> 01:23:44.810
at which you are analyzing
information dreaming, et cetera,

01:23:44.810 --> 01:23:46.750
is variable when you were in sleep,

01:23:46.750 --> 01:23:48.200
sometimes it's very fast.

01:23:48.200 --> 01:23:49.860
Meaning you experienced
things in slow motion.

01:23:49.860 --> 01:23:51.140
Sometimes it's very fast.

01:23:51.140 --> 01:23:55.990
In waking to your experience of time

01:23:55.990 --> 01:23:58.600
can sometimes be very fast
sometimes be very slow.

01:23:58.600 --> 01:24:01.803
Typically the more alert you
are, the higher the frame rate,

01:24:01.803 --> 01:24:05.150
your thin slicing your experience.

01:24:05.150 --> 01:24:06.410
You've probably had this happen.

01:24:06.410 --> 01:24:07.480
If you're ever very stressed

01:24:07.480 --> 01:24:09.900
and you're waiting for
something or somebody,

01:24:09.900 --> 01:24:12.850
it seems like it takes forever because

01:24:12.850 --> 01:24:14.070
your frame rate is higher

01:24:14.070 --> 01:24:16.460
you're analyzing time more finely.

01:24:16.460 --> 01:24:21.090
Conversely, if you are very
relaxed or even sleepy,

01:24:21.090 --> 01:24:22.210
you wake up and you have to think of

01:24:22.210 --> 01:24:23.043
all the things you have to do.

01:24:23.043 --> 01:24:25.720
It will seem like the world
is going by very, very fast

01:24:25.720 --> 01:24:28.040
and that you are moving very slow.

01:24:28.040 --> 01:24:30.360
Time is going at the same rate,

01:24:30.360 --> 01:24:33.620
but your perception of
time is what's changed.

01:24:33.620 --> 01:24:35.050
Believe it or not.

01:24:35.050 --> 01:24:39.270
Your perception of time is
also changed on a rapid basis.

01:24:39.270 --> 01:24:43.223
Moment to moment basis
by how often you blink.

01:24:44.280 --> 01:24:46.820
This is a well-established literature

01:24:46.820 --> 01:24:51.050
in the world of neuroscience
that unlike the literature

01:24:51.050 --> 01:24:53.750
and claims about blinking and sociopathy,

01:24:53.750 --> 01:24:55.690
which have no basis,

01:24:55.690 --> 01:24:59.050
the science of blinking as
it relates to time perception

01:24:59.050 --> 01:25:01.270
has some very good data to support it.

01:25:01.270 --> 01:25:03.980
I want to just emphasize
one study in particular,

01:25:03.980 --> 01:25:06.447
which is quite appropriately titled,

01:25:06.447 --> 01:25:09.100
"Time dilates after spontaneous blinking."

01:25:09.100 --> 01:25:11.520
This is a paper that was
published in current biology.

01:25:11.520 --> 01:25:15.108
The first author is
Terhune, T-E-R-H-U-N-E.

01:25:15.108 --> 01:25:16.623
It's a wonderful paper.

01:25:17.540 --> 01:25:22.540
They examine the relationship
between fluctuations in timing

01:25:22.840 --> 01:25:26.210
and blinking and to
make a long story short

01:25:26.210 --> 01:25:29.960
what they found is that
right after blinks,

01:25:29.960 --> 01:25:33.570
we reset our perception of time, okay?

01:25:33.570 --> 01:25:36.130
So blinks in that sense
are a little bit like

01:25:36.130 --> 01:25:38.150
the curtain coming down on a scene

01:25:38.150 --> 01:25:40.120
between scenes in a play

01:25:40.120 --> 01:25:43.210
or takes in a movie, and
they clap the clap thing,

01:25:43.210 --> 01:25:46.820
they started take in our,
what do they say, action

01:25:46.820 --> 01:25:49.660
and then at the end they do the
thing and they click it down

01:25:49.660 --> 01:25:52.550
and they say, it's a take that's one take

01:25:52.550 --> 01:25:55.063
when you blink it's a take, okay?

01:25:56.650 --> 01:25:58.260
Now what's interesting

01:25:58.260 --> 01:26:01.150
and will immediately make
sense to you as to why

01:26:01.150 --> 01:26:05.680
this is important is
that the rate of blinking

01:26:05.680 --> 01:26:08.350
is controlled by dopamine.

01:26:08.350 --> 01:26:10.250
So what this means is that dopamine

01:26:10.250 --> 01:26:11.530
is controlling attention.

01:26:11.530 --> 01:26:14.280
Blinks relate to attention and focus,

01:26:14.280 --> 01:26:17.810
and therefore the dopamine
and blinking system is one way

01:26:17.810 --> 01:26:21.870
that you constantly modulate and update

01:26:21.870 --> 01:26:23.830
your perception of time

01:26:23.830 --> 01:26:27.070
and fortunately, it's also
one that you can control.

01:26:27.070 --> 01:26:29.980
So the basic takeaway of
this study was that blinking

01:26:29.980 --> 01:26:31.210
controls time perception,

01:26:31.210 --> 01:26:33.840
but also that levels of dopamine

01:26:33.840 --> 01:26:38.320
can alter your sense of
time and stay with me here,

01:26:38.320 --> 01:26:42.930
and that blinking and dopamine
are inextricably linked.

01:26:42.930 --> 01:26:46.060
They are working together
to control your attention.

01:26:46.060 --> 01:26:48.480
When dopamine levels go up,

01:26:48.480 --> 01:26:52.780
people tend to overestimate
how long something lasted, why?

01:26:53.620 --> 01:26:56.280
Because they are
processing time more finely

01:26:56.280 --> 01:26:58.193
it's slow motion mode.

01:26:59.240 --> 01:27:01.070
When dopamine levels are lower,

01:27:01.070 --> 01:27:04.450
they tend to underestimate time intervals.

01:27:04.450 --> 01:27:07.230
Let's remember back to the
very beginning of the episode,

01:27:07.230 --> 01:27:09.383
what's going on in people with ADHD,

01:27:10.420 --> 01:27:12.620
they are not good at managing their time,

01:27:12.620 --> 01:27:15.130
they tend to run late,
or they are disorganized.

01:27:15.130 --> 01:27:17.780
They are not just disorganized in space,

01:27:17.780 --> 01:27:20.348
meaning in that physical
space, around them,

01:27:20.348 --> 01:27:23.590
they're disorganized in time.

01:27:23.590 --> 01:27:26.770
Their dopamine is low,
we know that as well

01:27:26.770 --> 01:27:29.630
and so they are
underestimating time intervals

01:27:29.630 --> 01:27:32.140
and so it makes perfect sense
that they would be late.

01:27:32.140 --> 01:27:34.500
It makes perfect sense that
they would lose track of time

01:27:34.500 --> 01:27:36.660
or the ability to focus.

01:27:36.660 --> 01:27:39.710
This is really exciting
because what it means is that

01:27:39.710 --> 01:27:42.340
children with ADHD, adults, with ADHD

01:27:42.340 --> 01:27:44.160
or people with normal levels of focus

01:27:44.160 --> 01:27:46.930
that want to improve
their ability to focus

01:27:46.930 --> 01:27:50.230
can do so through a training that involves

01:27:50.230 --> 01:27:53.150
learning how often to blink and when,

01:27:53.150 --> 01:27:56.860
and how to keep their visual
focus on a given target

01:27:56.860 --> 01:27:59.930
and it turns out this study
has actually been done.

01:27:59.930 --> 01:28:02.260
There's a study again,
I'll link to the study,

01:28:02.260 --> 01:28:04.140
entitled "Improvement of attention

01:28:04.140 --> 01:28:06.040
in elementary school students

01:28:06.040 --> 01:28:08.740
through fixation focused
training activity."

01:28:08.740 --> 01:28:10.220
I won't go through all the details,

01:28:10.220 --> 01:28:13.460
but what they found was a short period of

01:28:14.300 --> 01:28:16.800
focusing on a visual target,

01:28:16.800 --> 01:28:20.040
allowed the school
children to greatly enhance

01:28:20.040 --> 01:28:23.650
their ability to focus on
other types of information

01:28:23.650 --> 01:28:26.110
and a significant component
of the effect was due

01:28:26.110 --> 01:28:28.390
to the way that they were
controlling the shutters

01:28:28.390 --> 01:28:31.730
on their eyes, their eyelids,
and controlling their blinks.

01:28:31.730 --> 01:28:34.240
So what they did in this
study is they had these kids

01:28:34.240 --> 01:28:35.760
focus their visual attention

01:28:35.760 --> 01:28:38.040
on some object that was relatively close,

01:28:38.040 --> 01:28:40.670
like their hand for a minute or so,

01:28:40.670 --> 01:28:42.890
which actually takes some
effort if you try and do that,

01:28:42.890 --> 01:28:44.758
they were allowed to blink.

01:28:44.758 --> 01:28:47.700
However, it's known from other work

01:28:47.700 --> 01:28:51.179
that if people can consciously
override the desire to blink,

01:28:51.179 --> 01:28:54.010
at least to the point where
they feel like they have to,

01:28:54.010 --> 01:28:55.490
or else their eyes were dry out,

01:28:55.490 --> 01:28:58.570
that actually can increase
attention even further

01:28:58.570 --> 01:29:00.980
and they had conditions where
they would look at a point

01:29:00.980 --> 01:29:04.314
further across the room and
even further across the room.

01:29:04.314 --> 01:29:07.390
It only took a few minutes
each day to do this

01:29:07.390 --> 01:29:09.730
30 seconds in one
condition, or maybe a minute

01:29:09.730 --> 01:29:11.210
and then at another station

01:29:11.210 --> 01:29:12.247
of looking a little bit further out

01:29:12.247 --> 01:29:14.170
and a little bit further out, however,

01:29:14.170 --> 01:29:16.430
there was an important
feature of this study

01:29:16.430 --> 01:29:18.600
that is definitely worth mentioning,

01:29:18.600 --> 01:29:20.550
which is before they did this

01:29:20.550 --> 01:29:23.870
visual focus, task or training,

01:29:23.870 --> 01:29:27.410
they did a series of physical
movements with the kids

01:29:27.410 --> 01:29:30.530
so that the kids could sort
of eliminate or move out

01:29:30.530 --> 01:29:32.620
some of their desire to move

01:29:32.620 --> 01:29:36.390
and would thereby enhance
their ability to sit still.

01:29:36.390 --> 01:29:38.780
Now it's long been known
that kids need a recess,

01:29:38.780 --> 01:29:41.420
they need time to run around
and play and roll around,

01:29:41.420 --> 01:29:42.480
do whatever it is that they do

01:29:42.480 --> 01:29:44.850
in order to be able to sit still at all.

01:29:44.850 --> 01:29:46.470
Adults probably need this too, frankly,

01:29:46.470 --> 01:29:49.750
but kids need it more because
the circuits in the brain

01:29:49.750 --> 01:29:53.870
that control reflexive
movements and as we say,

01:29:53.870 --> 01:29:57.100
kind of rhythmic undulating
behavior and things like that,

01:29:57.100 --> 01:29:58.740
that's an active suppression

01:29:58.740 --> 01:30:00.810
and kids have less of
that circuitry built up

01:30:00.810 --> 01:30:03.970
until they hit about age 15 or 16.

01:30:03.970 --> 01:30:06.180
So they had the kids move around a bit

01:30:06.180 --> 01:30:08.540
and then do this focus training.

01:30:08.540 --> 01:30:10.610
That brings me to another treatment

01:30:10.610 --> 01:30:14.420
that's actively used nowadays
in schools for kids with ADHD,

01:30:14.420 --> 01:30:18.450
but also is starting
to be used by many kids

01:30:18.450 --> 01:30:22.500
and by parents in order to
keep their kids focusing

01:30:22.500 --> 01:30:27.500
and not going crazy in the car
or not acting out in general

01:30:27.500 --> 01:30:31.140
and that's the prevalence of
these so-called fidgeter toys

01:30:31.140 --> 01:30:32.880
or things that kids can do actively

01:30:32.880 --> 01:30:34.610
and repetitively in order to move out

01:30:34.610 --> 01:30:37.970
some of their underlying
reverberatory activity

01:30:37.970 --> 01:30:39.320
in their nervous system.

01:30:39.320 --> 01:30:43.010
So what you will find is
that some kids with ADHD

01:30:43.010 --> 01:30:45.680
are now given a rubber band on their desk,

01:30:45.680 --> 01:30:47.480
literally a rubber band
that's attached to their desk

01:30:47.480 --> 01:30:49.200
and they're able to pull on it,

01:30:49.200 --> 01:30:50.630
even snap it against the desk,

01:30:50.630 --> 01:30:51.690
if I had done that when I was a kid,

01:30:51.690 --> 01:30:53.420
I think my teachers were
throw me out of class,

01:30:53.420 --> 01:30:54.910
but I think it's great
that they're allowing them

01:30:54.910 --> 01:30:57.530
to do this now as a way of moving

01:30:57.530 --> 01:31:00.680
some of their physical energy out

01:31:00.680 --> 01:31:03.160
or engage their physical energy, rather,

01:31:03.160 --> 01:31:04.800
as opposed to trying to sit

01:31:04.800 --> 01:31:06.930
statue still all the time and attend

01:31:06.930 --> 01:31:10.130
and it turns out that does
enhance these children's ability

01:31:10.130 --> 01:31:12.820
to focus mentally when they
have some physical activity

01:31:12.820 --> 01:31:16.980
to attend to and it turns out
it also can work for adults.

01:31:16.980 --> 01:31:19.160
I'll share with you I related anecdote

01:31:19.160 --> 01:31:21.342
because it illustrates
the underlying mechanism.

01:31:21.342 --> 01:31:25.370
I've had the great privilege
of being able to do a number of

01:31:25.370 --> 01:31:28.520
surgeries, brain surgeries
during my career.

01:31:28.520 --> 01:31:30.213
So one thing you find when
you do brain surgeries,

01:31:30.213 --> 01:31:32.122
is that the brain's pretty small

01:31:32.122 --> 01:31:33.988
regardless of the species
that you're working on

01:31:33.988 --> 01:31:35.360
and you're in there
and you're trying to do

01:31:35.360 --> 01:31:38.140
something very specific
and the more you try

01:31:38.140 --> 01:31:40.460
and hold your hands really steady,

01:31:40.460 --> 01:31:42.500
the more they want to shake, all right?

01:31:42.500 --> 01:31:44.650
So it's not natural for any of our limbs

01:31:44.650 --> 01:31:46.800
to sit perfectly still,

01:31:46.800 --> 01:31:48.180
depending on how much coffee you had,

01:31:48.180 --> 01:31:49.720
how well rested you are

01:31:49.720 --> 01:31:52.100
and your sort of baseline
level of autonomic arousal.

01:31:52.100 --> 01:31:54.290
Some of you may find that
you can hold out your hand,

01:31:54.290 --> 01:31:58.400
absolutely rock solid, others
will shake a little bit more.

01:31:58.400 --> 01:31:59.870
It doesn't mean you're if you're shaking,

01:31:59.870 --> 01:32:02.503
doesn't mean you're calm if you're still.

01:32:03.460 --> 01:32:04.730
What it relates to

01:32:04.730 --> 01:32:06.640
is the amount of what we
call premotor activity,

01:32:06.640 --> 01:32:08.370
the number of commands to move

01:32:08.370 --> 01:32:09.720
that are being sent through the system

01:32:09.720 --> 01:32:12.010
and that's what I mean
by reverberatory activity

01:32:12.010 --> 01:32:16.010
and it does seem that kids
with ADHD and adults with ADHD

01:32:16.010 --> 01:32:18.470
have a lot of reverberatory activity

01:32:18.470 --> 01:32:19.327
in their nervous system

01:32:19.327 --> 01:32:21.150
and so that's that constant desire to move

01:32:21.150 --> 01:32:22.840
it's hard for them to sit still

01:32:22.840 --> 01:32:24.920
and therefore it's hard
for them to attend,

01:32:24.920 --> 01:32:26.270
to harness their attention.

01:32:27.599 --> 01:32:29.110
When you do a surgery

01:32:29.110 --> 01:32:32.045
and you find that your hands are shaking,

01:32:32.045 --> 01:32:33.880
what you learn from your mentors,

01:32:33.880 --> 01:32:36.130
which I did and what works extremely well,

01:32:36.130 --> 01:32:37.800
whether or not you're
doing a surgery or not,

01:32:37.800 --> 01:32:39.550
is that you simply tap your foot

01:32:39.550 --> 01:32:40.960
or you bounce your knee a little bit,

01:32:40.960 --> 01:32:44.240
which you might think would
make your hand shake even more,

01:32:44.240 --> 01:32:45.960
but provided that it's subtle.

01:32:45.960 --> 01:32:49.220
What it does is it actually
shuttle some of the activity

01:32:49.220 --> 01:32:51.980
from those premotor circuits
to elsewhere in the body

01:32:51.980 --> 01:32:55.130
and then you're able to sit
much more still with your hand,

01:32:55.130 --> 01:32:57.720
you're able to perform the
surgery with much more precision.

01:32:57.720 --> 01:33:00.460
You are able to write with
much better handwriting

01:33:00.460 --> 01:33:03.600
and for those of you who
engage in public speaking,

01:33:03.600 --> 01:33:04.840
if you ever too nervous,

01:33:04.840 --> 01:33:07.020
that's why pacing while
you public speak helps

01:33:07.020 --> 01:33:07.853
if you're nervous,

01:33:07.853 --> 01:33:10.150
that's why bouncing your
knee behind the podium

01:33:10.150 --> 01:33:10.983
works as well.

01:33:10.983 --> 01:33:13.340
That's why nodding your head
and gesticulating can help.

01:33:13.340 --> 01:33:15.557
It's not a matter of,

01:33:15.557 --> 01:33:17.100
"Moving energy out of the body."

01:33:17.100 --> 01:33:18.400
That doesn't actually happen,

01:33:18.400 --> 01:33:20.970
what it is you're engaging
those premotor circuits

01:33:20.970 --> 01:33:22.360
that are sending through commands.

01:33:22.360 --> 01:33:23.400
It's like trying to stuff,

01:33:23.400 --> 01:33:25.050
a bunch of stuff through a funnel,

01:33:25.050 --> 01:33:26.670
and it creates this tension,

01:33:26.670 --> 01:33:31.010
so you're giving it an outlet
for the neural circuitry

01:33:31.010 --> 01:33:32.370
to be able to move something

01:33:32.370 --> 01:33:34.640
so that you can keep other
components of your body

01:33:34.640 --> 01:33:37.510
and your mental attention engaged

01:33:37.510 --> 01:33:41.000
and locked onto something
what we call focus.

01:33:41.000 --> 01:33:43.260
One thing related to this
whole business of blinking

01:33:43.260 --> 01:33:45.520
and focus and training yourself to focus

01:33:45.520 --> 01:33:50.520
and not blinking, et cetera,
is that most all of the drugs,

01:33:51.080 --> 01:33:53.710
Ritalin, Adderall, and recreational drugs

01:33:53.710 --> 01:33:55.150
that increase dopamine,

01:33:55.150 --> 01:33:58.343
even coffee and tea and
other forms of caffeine,

01:33:59.510 --> 01:34:01.760
they tend to make us blink less

01:34:01.760 --> 01:34:04.560
and when we get tired,
we tend to blink more.

01:34:04.560 --> 01:34:07.270
Now this is sort of a duh, right?

01:34:07.270 --> 01:34:10.590
But being wide-eyed
with excitement or fear

01:34:10.590 --> 01:34:15.370
or with your eyes, barely
being able to keep them open,

01:34:15.370 --> 01:34:17.590
now it should make perfect
sense that these shutters

01:34:17.590 --> 01:34:18.500
on the front of your eyes,

01:34:18.500 --> 01:34:20.340
they aren't just there for winking

01:34:20.340 --> 01:34:22.980
and they aren't just there
for cosmetic purposes.

01:34:22.980 --> 01:34:26.320
They are there to regulate
the amount of information

01:34:26.320 --> 01:34:27.710
going into your nervous system

01:34:27.710 --> 01:34:31.140
and they're there to regulate how long

01:34:31.140 --> 01:34:34.000
you are bringing information
into your nervous system

01:34:34.000 --> 01:34:37.750
and in what bins, how widely or finely

01:34:37.750 --> 01:34:40.960
you are binning time is
set by how often you blink

01:34:40.960 --> 01:34:44.440
and how widely or specifically

01:34:44.440 --> 01:34:46.780
you are grabbing attention
from the visual world is set

01:34:46.780 --> 01:34:48.920
by whether or not you're
viewing things very specifically

01:34:48.920 --> 01:34:51.810
like a cross area through a
soda straw view like this,

01:34:51.810 --> 01:34:54.050
or whether or not you
were in this panoramic

01:34:54.050 --> 01:34:57.200
sort of whole environment mode,

01:34:57.200 --> 01:35:00.540
this kind of fisheye lens
or wide angle lens mode

01:35:00.540 --> 01:35:03.253
and in fairness to the
pharmacology and the circuitry,

01:35:04.120 --> 01:35:07.780
while dopamine and heightened
levels of alertness

01:35:07.780 --> 01:35:12.780
and excitement tend to make
us blink less and attend more.

01:35:12.840 --> 01:35:14.580
There's actually a study that's looked at

01:35:14.580 --> 01:35:16.890
the other neurochemical systems

01:35:16.890 --> 01:35:19.410
and drugs and how those relate to blinking

01:35:19.410 --> 01:35:22.190
and so this will all be obvious
by the title of the paper

01:35:22.190 --> 01:35:23.100
I'm about to share with you.

01:35:23.100 --> 01:35:25.217
This is a paper entitled,

01:35:25.217 --> 01:35:27.960
"Decreased spontaneous eyeblink rates

01:35:27.960 --> 01:35:29.970
in chronic cannabis users,

01:35:29.970 --> 01:35:34.150
evidence for stride or cannabinoid,
dopamine interactions."

01:35:34.150 --> 01:35:36.130
Okay, I'm not going to go
into all the details here,

01:35:36.130 --> 01:35:40.050
but one thing that is
somewhat surprising is that

01:35:40.050 --> 01:35:44.683
many people with ADHD
use or abuse cannabis,

01:35:45.540 --> 01:35:47.110
you might think, well,
why would they do that?

01:35:47.110 --> 01:35:50.550
Because I thought that
a increase in dopamine

01:35:50.550 --> 01:35:51.560
is actually what's going to lead

01:35:51.560 --> 01:35:52.730
to heightened levels of attention

01:35:52.730 --> 01:35:55.210
and that's what these
people in children crave.

01:35:55.210 --> 01:35:57.790
Well, it turns out that cannabis also

01:35:57.790 --> 01:36:00.770
increases dopamine
transmission in the brain,

01:36:00.770 --> 01:36:02.870
but because of the other chemicals,

01:36:02.870 --> 01:36:04.510
it increases namely serotonin

01:36:04.510 --> 01:36:07.530
and some components of the
cannabinoid and opioid system,

01:36:07.530 --> 01:36:12.530
it creates that kind of
alert, but mellow feel

01:36:13.130 --> 01:36:15.530
and again, here I'm not
a proponent of this,

01:36:15.530 --> 01:36:18.020
I personally am not a
THC or cannabis user.

01:36:18.020 --> 01:36:19.190
It's just not my thing

01:36:20.120 --> 01:36:21.810
and obviously it's illegal some places

01:36:21.810 --> 01:36:24.040
and so you have to
determine that for yourself

01:36:24.040 --> 01:36:28.380
it does have medical purposes
in some places it is legal,

01:36:28.380 --> 01:36:32.240
but THC increases dopamine
and increases neurochemicals

01:36:32.240 --> 01:36:34.140
that can also create a state of calm.

01:36:34.140 --> 01:36:35.970
So it's that sort of middle ground

01:36:35.970 --> 01:36:38.500
and this paper has a
beautiful demonstration

01:36:38.500 --> 01:36:42.530
whereby not just while
people are using cannabis,

01:36:42.530 --> 01:36:44.930
but depending on how
long they've been using

01:36:44.930 --> 01:36:46.880
cannabis across their lifespan,

01:36:46.880 --> 01:36:49.160
the rates of eye blinking change.

01:36:49.160 --> 01:36:51.900
So if you look at the number of years

01:36:51.900 --> 01:36:54.860
that people have been using
cannabis on a regular basis,

01:36:54.860 --> 01:36:58.660
either daily or up to excuse
me, weekly, or up to daily,

01:36:58.660 --> 01:37:00.680
what you find is that for people

01:37:00.680 --> 01:37:02.760
that have not been using cannabis at all,

01:37:02.760 --> 01:37:05.530
or have only been using
it for about two years,

01:37:05.530 --> 01:37:08.260
their rates of eye blinks are much higher

01:37:08.260 --> 01:37:10.640
than people who've been using
it chronically for 10 years.

01:37:10.640 --> 01:37:11.800
In other words, people

01:37:11.800 --> 01:37:13.420
who may be using cannabis for 10 years,

01:37:13.420 --> 01:37:15.440
don't blink very often at all.

01:37:15.440 --> 01:37:19.530
Now cannabis has well known
effects in depleting memory,

01:37:19.530 --> 01:37:22.670
but it does seem to engage the focus

01:37:22.670 --> 01:37:25.630
and blinking system in a
way that increases focus.

01:37:25.630 --> 01:37:27.310
So basically what I'm saying is

01:37:27.310 --> 01:37:29.250
marijuana seems to
increase people's focus,

01:37:29.250 --> 01:37:32.100
but then they can't remember
what they were focusing on.

01:37:32.100 --> 01:37:35.450
Something I'd like to discuss
just briefly is the so-called

01:37:35.450 --> 01:37:39.520
interoceptive awareness that's
present in people with ADHD,

01:37:39.520 --> 01:37:40.970
both children and adults.

01:37:40.970 --> 01:37:43.690
Interoceptive awareness is one sense

01:37:43.690 --> 01:37:46.460
of one's own internal state heartbeat,

01:37:46.460 --> 01:37:50.590
breathing contact of skin with
a given surface, et cetera.

01:37:50.590 --> 01:37:52.820
For a long time, there
was this hypothesis,

01:37:52.820 --> 01:37:54.970
this idea that people with ADHD,

01:37:54.970 --> 01:37:57.610
were just not in touch with how they felt

01:37:57.610 --> 01:37:59.410
that somehow they weren't registering

01:37:59.410 --> 01:38:01.440
all the stuff that was
going on inside them

01:38:01.440 --> 01:38:02.990
changes in heart rate and so forth

01:38:02.990 --> 01:38:04.900
and so they were behaving in a way

01:38:04.900 --> 01:38:07.883
that was dysregulated
or appear dysregulated,

01:38:08.790 --> 01:38:11.400
and that if they could
just learn to attend

01:38:11.400 --> 01:38:13.240
to their internal state better,

01:38:13.240 --> 01:38:16.320
that somehow they would
function better in the world.

01:38:16.320 --> 01:38:19.340
Now, before we described a process,

01:38:19.340 --> 01:38:23.110
literally a 17 minute
interoceptive exercise

01:38:23.110 --> 01:38:25.860
that does seem to lead to improvements

01:38:25.860 --> 01:38:29.940
in one's ability to focus
for a longer period of time.

01:38:29.940 --> 01:38:34.200
However, it's very unlikely
that that was due to

01:38:34.200 --> 01:38:37.370
increasing interoceptive awareness per se.

01:38:37.370 --> 01:38:41.420
It probably wasn't because
people gain a much heightened

01:38:41.420 --> 01:38:44.250
or improved ability to understand

01:38:44.250 --> 01:38:46.160
what's going on internally.

01:38:46.160 --> 01:38:47.950
In fact, you can imagine
how that might actually

01:38:47.950 --> 01:38:49.960
prevent one's ability to
pay attention to things

01:38:49.960 --> 01:38:51.490
in the outside world.

01:38:51.490 --> 01:38:53.670
So while there is benefit
to just sitting there

01:38:53.670 --> 01:38:55.380
and being in stillness, as they say,

01:38:55.380 --> 01:38:57.910
or focusing on one's
breathing and internal state

01:38:57.910 --> 01:39:00.380
for sake of then accessing information

01:39:00.380 --> 01:39:01.930
in the external world,

01:39:01.930 --> 01:39:06.520
a really nice study called
interoceptive awareness

01:39:06.520 --> 01:39:08.620
and attention deficit
hyperactivity disorder

01:39:08.620 --> 01:39:11.140
explored whether or not
interoceptive awareness

01:39:11.140 --> 01:39:15.832
was different in people with
ADHD or did not have ADHD

01:39:15.832 --> 01:39:20.200
and the findings were essentially
that there's no difference

01:39:20.200 --> 01:39:22.460
that people with ADHD,
children, and adults,

01:39:22.460 --> 01:39:25.350
they are aware of what's
going on inside them

01:39:25.350 --> 01:39:27.550
just as much as anyone else's

01:39:27.550 --> 01:39:29.870
and the typical measure
of interoceptive awareness

01:39:29.870 --> 01:39:33.140
is one's ability to count
their own heartbeats.

01:39:33.140 --> 01:39:36.060
This is actually challenging
for some individuals

01:39:36.060 --> 01:39:37.890
and very easy for other individuals,

01:39:37.890 --> 01:39:39.660
regardless of their attentional capacity.

01:39:39.660 --> 01:39:41.870
Some people just can
really feel their heartbeat

01:39:41.870 --> 01:39:45.020
without taking their
pulse other people cannot

01:39:45.020 --> 01:39:47.410
and these studies are pretty
straightforward to do.

01:39:47.410 --> 01:39:50.820
You ask people to sit there
and to count their heartbeats,

01:39:50.820 --> 01:39:52.700
and then you are
monitoring their heartbeats

01:39:52.700 --> 01:39:55.140
and you get to gauge
how accurate they are.

01:39:55.140 --> 01:39:58.980
So it's important to understand
that people with ADHD

01:39:58.980 --> 01:40:01.560
are in touch with how they feel.

01:40:01.560 --> 01:40:03.700
It's really a question of whether or not

01:40:03.700 --> 01:40:06.760
they can take the demands
that are placed upon them

01:40:06.760 --> 01:40:09.430
and enter a cognitive
state of mental state

01:40:09.430 --> 01:40:11.220
that allows them to access the information

01:40:11.220 --> 01:40:12.053
they need to access

01:40:12.053 --> 01:40:13.300
in other words, whether
or not they can focus,

01:40:13.300 --> 01:40:15.860
but it is absolutely wrong to think that

01:40:15.860 --> 01:40:18.600
the child that's getting
up 11 times during a short

01:40:19.498 --> 01:40:21.660
six minute interaction at the table,

01:40:21.660 --> 01:40:24.460
or whether or not a child who

01:40:24.460 --> 01:40:26.270
somehow has to venture off every moment

01:40:26.270 --> 01:40:27.640
or a coworker of yours

01:40:27.640 --> 01:40:29.430
who's an adult who's constantly fidgeting

01:40:29.430 --> 01:40:31.500
or moving things around that
somehow they are unaware

01:40:31.500 --> 01:40:32.410
that they are oblivious,

01:40:32.410 --> 01:40:34.260
they're not oblivious to how they feel.

01:40:34.260 --> 01:40:36.520
Chances are they're very
challenged in the situations

01:40:36.520 --> 01:40:37.353
that they're in

01:40:37.353 --> 01:40:38.860
and they're doing
everything they can to try

01:40:38.860 --> 01:40:40.410
and regulate their attention.

01:40:40.410 --> 01:40:42.428
So I think it's an
important study to highlight

01:40:42.428 --> 01:40:44.760
because it really
underscores the fact that

01:40:44.760 --> 01:40:46.170
something else is going on

01:40:46.170 --> 01:40:48.320
and that something else
has everything to do

01:40:48.320 --> 01:40:49.600
with this ability to coordinate

01:40:49.600 --> 01:40:51.220
these tasks directed networks,

01:40:51.220 --> 01:40:53.930
and to coordinate that in the proper way

01:40:53.930 --> 01:40:55.700
with that default mode network

01:40:55.700 --> 01:40:58.120
and that is a process as you now know,

01:40:58.120 --> 01:41:02.510
that's regulated exquisitely
by certain neurochemicals

01:41:02.510 --> 01:41:04.740
and in particular the
neurochemicals, dopamine,

01:41:04.740 --> 01:41:07.130
norepinephrine and serotonin,

01:41:07.130 --> 01:41:09.040
and a fourth one I'd like
to throw into the mix,

01:41:09.040 --> 01:41:10.380
which is acetylcholine,

01:41:10.380 --> 01:41:13.000
which is very vital for cognitive focus.

01:41:13.000 --> 01:41:15.410
So now I want to switch
back to talking about

01:41:15.410 --> 01:41:17.570
some of the drugs that are typically used

01:41:17.570 --> 01:41:19.800
to access those systems,
prescription drugs

01:41:19.800 --> 01:41:22.070
and I want to talk about
some of the new and emerging

01:41:22.070 --> 01:41:23.930
non-prescription approaches

01:41:23.930 --> 01:41:25.990
to increasing the levels of dopamine,

01:41:25.990 --> 01:41:28.130
acetylcholine and serotonin in the brain

01:41:28.130 --> 01:41:30.240
using various supplement type compounds,

01:41:30.240 --> 01:41:32.750
because several of them are showing

01:41:32.750 --> 01:41:34.770
really remarkable efficacy

01:41:34.770 --> 01:41:36.740
in excellent peer reviewed studies.

01:41:36.740 --> 01:41:39.770
So before moving to some of
the newer atypical compounds

01:41:39.770 --> 01:41:41.569
and things sold over the counter,

01:41:41.569 --> 01:41:46.300
I'd like to just briefly
return to the classic drugs

01:41:46.300 --> 01:41:48.363
that are used to treat ADHD.

01:41:49.600 --> 01:41:51.590
These are the ones I mentioned earlier,

01:41:51.590 --> 01:41:54.640
methylphenidate also called Ritalin,

01:41:54.640 --> 01:41:59.640
Modafinil or armodafinil is
another one and Adderall,

01:42:00.460 --> 01:42:02.190
again, all of these work by

01:42:02.190 --> 01:42:04.663
increasing levels of
dopamine and norepinephrine.

01:42:05.530 --> 01:42:08.534
Typically they're taken
orally in pill form,

01:42:08.534 --> 01:42:11.650
or sometimes in capsule form

01:42:11.650 --> 01:42:14.300
the dosages that are appropriate vary,

01:42:14.300 --> 01:42:17.340
according to severity of the condition

01:42:17.340 --> 01:42:20.890
for a given person and
the age of the person.

01:42:20.890 --> 01:42:24.240
This is a complicated
landscape for each individual.

01:42:24.240 --> 01:42:25.760
They have to figure out the pharmacology

01:42:25.760 --> 01:42:26.990
that's best for them.

01:42:26.990 --> 01:42:30.340
Some individuals are even layering long

01:42:30.340 --> 01:42:35.160
or time to release Ritalin
with Adderall in smaller doses,

01:42:35.160 --> 01:42:37.810
it can get quite complex or it
can be quite straightforward

01:42:37.810 --> 01:42:40.220
if you are really
interested in these drugs

01:42:40.220 --> 01:42:41.260
and how they work

01:42:41.260 --> 01:42:46.260
and you'd like to get a glance
at a table of all the results

01:42:46.500 --> 01:42:49.860
from all the studies of
which there are now hundreds,

01:42:49.860 --> 01:42:54.060
there's an excellent review
about these drugs and their use

01:42:54.060 --> 01:42:57.270
and their comparison to
similarly structured drugs

01:42:57.270 --> 01:43:01.530
in particular MDMA and
cocaine and amphetamine,

01:43:01.530 --> 01:43:03.030
meaning Street Amphetamine

01:43:03.030 --> 01:43:05.170
to really illustrate the similarities

01:43:05.170 --> 01:43:08.560
of action and some of
the problems associated

01:43:08.560 --> 01:43:10.270
with long-term use.

01:43:10.270 --> 01:43:11.870
I don't expect you to
read this article in full

01:43:11.870 --> 01:43:14.360
I'm here so that you don't
have to go read these articles,

01:43:14.360 --> 01:43:17.100
but in case you want a ton of information,

01:43:17.100 --> 01:43:20.740
the paper is Esposito et al
Frontiers and bio-sciences,

01:43:20.740 --> 01:43:22.810
it's an excellent, excellent

01:43:22.810 --> 01:43:24.680
review of the entire literature.

01:43:24.680 --> 01:43:26.740
It is quite long.

01:43:26.740 --> 01:43:29.860
I can put a link to that
study in our caption,

01:43:29.860 --> 01:43:33.110
and it essentially
describes all the studies

01:43:33.110 --> 01:43:35.970
that have been done, peer
reviewed and published,

01:43:35.970 --> 01:43:39.140
and it refers to these
drugs in an interesting way.

01:43:39.140 --> 01:43:42.040
It doesn't just refer these
drugs as for treatment of ADHD.

01:43:42.040 --> 01:43:45.070
It actually refers to them
using language that ordinarily

01:43:45.070 --> 01:43:48.160
I'm not very fond of,
but I'll agree to here,

01:43:48.160 --> 01:43:51.363
which is so-called smart
drugs or nootropics.

01:43:52.740 --> 01:43:56.880
It also covers caffeine, which
again as I mentioned earlier,

01:43:56.880 --> 01:43:59.370
increases dopamine norepinephrine

01:43:59.370 --> 01:44:01.890
and to some extent serotonin,

01:44:01.890 --> 01:44:05.100
but what I like about this
review so much is that

01:44:05.100 --> 01:44:07.040
in putting, these drugs of abuse,

01:44:07.040 --> 01:44:09.610
methamphetamine, and cocaine,
right alongside these drugs,

01:44:09.610 --> 01:44:12.370
like Ritalin and Adderall
and also caffeine,

01:44:12.370 --> 01:44:15.130
we start to realize that
the distinction between

01:44:15.130 --> 01:44:15.963
drugs of abuse

01:44:15.963 --> 01:44:18.020
and the distinction
between drugs of treatment

01:44:18.020 --> 01:44:21.750
is actually a very fine and
sometimes even a blurry line

01:44:21.750 --> 01:44:25.440
and in thinking about whether
or not one wants to use

01:44:25.440 --> 01:44:27.700
these prescription, I want
to emphasize prescription,

01:44:27.700 --> 01:44:28.533
not drugs of abuse,

01:44:28.533 --> 01:44:29.510
but prescription drugs

01:44:29.510 --> 01:44:32.223
for treatment of one's
own attentional capacity.

01:44:33.230 --> 01:44:35.290
I think it is important to understand

01:44:35.290 --> 01:44:37.140
the extent to which they all carry

01:44:37.140 --> 01:44:38.620
more or less the same side effects.

01:44:38.620 --> 01:44:41.750
The one exception being
caffeine caffeine side effects

01:44:41.750 --> 01:44:44.700
can be anxiety if you ingest
too much of it, insomnia,

01:44:44.700 --> 01:44:46.340
if you drink it too late in the day,

01:44:46.340 --> 01:44:49.440
but typically it will not
cause the major side effects

01:44:49.440 --> 01:44:50.920
of the other drugs,

01:44:50.920 --> 01:44:54.463
such as high propensity
for addiction and abuse.

01:44:55.595 --> 01:44:58.550
Amphetamines of any
kind as well as cocaine

01:44:58.550 --> 01:45:00.680
can cause sexual side effects

01:45:00.680 --> 01:45:02.604
because they're vasoconstrictors.

01:45:02.604 --> 01:45:06.530
So, men have trouble achieving erection,

01:45:06.530 --> 01:45:11.530
there can often be the intense
desire or libido for sex,

01:45:11.970 --> 01:45:14.370
but an inability to actually perform.

01:45:14.370 --> 01:45:16.990
So that's an issue with
any kind of stimulant.

01:45:16.990 --> 01:45:19.290
So these drugs are not
without their consequences.

01:45:19.290 --> 01:45:24.030
In addition, and here I'd lump
caffeine back into the mix.

01:45:24.030 --> 01:45:27.770
In addition, they almost all
carry cardiac effects, right?

01:45:27.770 --> 01:45:28.880
They increase heart rate,

01:45:28.880 --> 01:45:32.830
but they also have effects on
constriction of blood vessels

01:45:32.830 --> 01:45:34.950
and arteries and veins
and so forth in ways

01:45:34.950 --> 01:45:37.570
that can create cardiovascular problems.

01:45:37.570 --> 01:45:40.540
Now, caffeine is a bit
of a complicated one.

01:45:40.540 --> 01:45:42.650
I talked about this on a podcast long ago,

01:45:42.650 --> 01:45:44.940
but I'll just remind you that it turns out

01:45:44.940 --> 01:45:47.180
that if you are caffeine
adapted, in other words,

01:45:47.180 --> 01:45:49.300
if you are used to drinking caffeine

01:45:49.300 --> 01:45:51.280
then the ingestion of caffeine,

01:45:51.280 --> 01:45:54.330
most often will cause vasodilation
who actually allow more

01:45:54.330 --> 01:45:55.570
blood flow through.

01:45:55.570 --> 01:45:57.730
However, if you are not caffeine adapted,

01:45:57.730 --> 01:45:59.619
it will cause vasoconstriction

01:45:59.619 --> 01:46:02.160
due to an increased stress response.

01:46:02.160 --> 01:46:04.220
So if you're familiar with caffeine,

01:46:04.220 --> 01:46:06.250
caffeine can actually
have a little bit more

01:46:06.250 --> 01:46:08.090
of a relaxation response

01:46:08.090 --> 01:46:08.923
although if you drink enough of it,

01:46:08.923 --> 01:46:11.000
it will make you amped up.

01:46:11.000 --> 01:46:15.050
These other drugs, almost
always lead to vasoconstriction,

01:46:15.050 --> 01:46:18.220
increased heart rate dilation
of the pupils, less blinking,

01:46:18.220 --> 01:46:19.890
heightened levels of attention,

01:46:19.890 --> 01:46:22.050
which looks very much like stress

01:46:22.050 --> 01:46:23.990
and at its extremes looks very much

01:46:23.990 --> 01:46:25.230
like the effects of street drugs,

01:46:25.230 --> 01:46:27.290
like cocaine and amphetamine.

01:46:27.290 --> 01:46:28.390
Because of the large amounts of

01:46:28.390 --> 01:46:30.620
dopamine that released in the brain.

01:46:30.620 --> 01:46:33.350
People tend to crave
that state over and over

01:46:33.350 --> 01:46:36.260
and yet with each subsequent use

01:46:36.260 --> 01:46:38.010
are able to get less and less

01:46:38.010 --> 01:46:39.410
of that euphoric feeling

01:46:39.410 --> 01:46:41.330
or that really, really focused feeling.

01:46:41.330 --> 01:46:43.560
So one thing that's being
explored quite extensively now

01:46:43.560 --> 01:46:47.760
in the treatment of
ADHD are drug schedules.

01:46:47.760 --> 01:46:51.720
Whether or not people should
take Adderall every day

01:46:51.720 --> 01:46:52.800
or every other day,

01:46:52.800 --> 01:46:53.830
whether or not they should take it

01:46:53.830 --> 01:46:55.160
only every once in a while,

01:46:55.160 --> 01:46:57.760
whether or not young children
can take it just a few times

01:46:57.760 --> 01:47:00.440
and engage in behavioral
training of the sort

01:47:00.440 --> 01:47:02.990
that I talked about before,
where they're doing,

01:47:02.990 --> 01:47:05.990
maybe it's a 17 minute
meditation type exercise,

01:47:05.990 --> 01:47:08.130
but more likely it would be the movement

01:47:08.130 --> 01:47:10.430
followed by the visual focusing,

01:47:10.430 --> 01:47:13.040
cause that's only done for
20 or 30 or 60 seconds.

01:47:13.040 --> 01:47:13.873
Why would you do that?

01:47:13.873 --> 01:47:16.490
Well in a chemically enhanced state,

01:47:16.490 --> 01:47:17.850
your brain is more plastic.

01:47:17.850 --> 01:47:21.713
The circuits are able to
modify and learn better.

01:47:22.574 --> 01:47:25.840
That's the optimal time to engage in focus

01:47:25.840 --> 01:47:27.370
in a very deliberate way.

01:47:27.370 --> 01:47:29.330
So just taking a drug and expecting

01:47:29.330 --> 01:47:31.190
focus to just work at any point

01:47:31.190 --> 01:47:35.090
and being able to turn
focus on and off at will,

01:47:35.090 --> 01:47:38.010
that's an unrealistic expectation, right?

01:47:38.010 --> 01:47:43.010
More likely the best use of
things like Adderall, Modafinil,

01:47:44.020 --> 01:47:47.330
armodafinil and Ritalin is going to be

01:47:47.330 --> 01:47:51.500
to combine those treatments
with behavioral exercises

01:47:51.500 --> 01:47:53.360
that actively engage the very circuits

01:47:53.360 --> 01:47:55.370
that you're trying to train up and enhance

01:47:55.370 --> 01:47:58.010
and then perhaps I want
to highlight perhaps

01:47:58.010 --> 01:47:59.400
tapering off those drugs

01:47:59.400 --> 01:48:01.570
so that then one can use those circuits

01:48:01.570 --> 01:48:04.470
without any need for
chemical intervention.

01:48:04.470 --> 01:48:07.150
So despite any controversy
that might be out there,

01:48:07.150 --> 01:48:09.070
I think it's fair to say that

01:48:09.070 --> 01:48:11.310
the consumption of omega-3 fatty acids

01:48:12.260 --> 01:48:14.220
can positively modulate

01:48:14.220 --> 01:48:16.650
the systems for attention and focus.

01:48:16.650 --> 01:48:20.530
So then the question becomes how much EPA,

01:48:20.530 --> 01:48:23.290
how much DHA does that differ for,

01:48:23.290 --> 01:48:25.810
what's helpful for depression, et cetera

01:48:25.810 --> 01:48:27.900
and actually it does differ

01:48:27.900 --> 01:48:29.320
in reviewing the studies for this

01:48:29.320 --> 01:48:32.960
it appears that a threshold
level of 300 milligrams of DHA

01:48:34.290 --> 01:48:37.200
turns out to be an
important inflection point.

01:48:37.200 --> 01:48:41.098
So typically fish oils or
other sources of omega-3s

01:48:41.098 --> 01:48:43.950
will have DHA and EPA

01:48:43.950 --> 01:48:45.860
and typically it's the EPA

01:48:45.860 --> 01:48:48.170
that's harder to get at sufficient levels,

01:48:48.170 --> 01:48:50.150
meaning you have to take
quite a lot of fish oil

01:48:50.150 --> 01:48:52.380
in order to get above that 1000 milligram

01:48:52.380 --> 01:48:55.730
or 2000 milligram
threshold to improve mood

01:48:55.730 --> 01:48:56.680
and other functions.

01:48:56.680 --> 01:48:59.280
But for sake of attention,

01:48:59.280 --> 01:49:02.400
there are 10 studies that
have explored this in detail

01:49:02.400 --> 01:49:05.440
and while the EPA component is important,

01:49:05.440 --> 01:49:08.930
the most convincing studies
point to the fact that getting

01:49:08.930 --> 01:49:12.493
above 300 milligrams per day
of DHA is really where you

01:49:12.493 --> 01:49:14.290
start to see the attentional effects.

01:49:14.290 --> 01:49:16.500
Now, fortunately, if you're
getting sufficient EPA

01:49:16.500 --> 01:49:19.403
for sake of mood and other
biological functions,

01:49:20.430 --> 01:49:22.610
almost without question,

01:49:22.610 --> 01:49:25.240
you're getting 300
milligrams or more of DHA.

01:49:25.240 --> 01:49:27.840
So that usually checks that box just fine.

01:49:27.840 --> 01:49:30.080
What's interesting is that
there's another compound

01:49:30.080 --> 01:49:35.080
phosphatidylserine that has
been explored for its capacity

01:49:35.120 --> 01:49:37.680
to improve the symptoms of ADHD.

01:49:37.680 --> 01:49:39.740
Again, I don't think
