02:01:54.320 --> 02:01:56.550
you definitely need to
consult your doctor,

02:01:56.550 --> 02:01:58.660
especially if you have ADHD,

02:01:58.660 --> 02:02:02.230
but new pepped has been shown when taken,

02:02:02.230 --> 02:02:06.010
at 10 milligrams, twice
daily can be more effective

02:02:06.010 --> 02:02:07.830
than some of the other Racetams.

02:02:07.830 --> 02:02:11.010
What is Noopept? Noopept taps
into the cholinergic system,

02:02:11.010 --> 02:02:14.760
the acetylcholine system in
ways, very similar to alpha-GPC,

02:02:14.760 --> 02:02:18.350
but seems to have a slightly
higher affinity for some of the

02:02:18.350 --> 02:02:22.000
receptors involved and can
lead to those heightened states

02:02:22.000 --> 02:02:23.100
of cognitive capacity

02:02:23.100 --> 02:02:26.069
and there are these
studies one in particular,

02:02:26.069 --> 02:02:28.040
comparative studies of new pepped,

02:02:28.040 --> 02:02:29.410
Racetams in the treatment of patients

02:02:29.410 --> 02:02:31.315
with mild cognitive disorders

02:02:31.315 --> 02:02:34.340
and brain diseases of
vascular and traumatic origin.

02:02:34.340 --> 02:02:35.190
That's a mouthful.

02:02:35.190 --> 02:02:37.550
What this study basically points to

02:02:37.550 --> 02:02:40.820
is the fact that people who
are experiencing some degree

02:02:40.820 --> 02:02:44.150
of inability to focus
due to prior concussion

02:02:44.150 --> 02:02:47.840
or some vascular event, a
stroke or a schemey of any kind,

02:02:47.840 --> 02:02:49.100
because neurons need blood,

02:02:49.100 --> 02:02:50.950
when the blood supply
is cut off to neurons,

02:02:50.950 --> 02:02:52.800
or when there's a bleed in the brain.

02:02:52.800 --> 02:02:54.810
Subsequent to that, often

02:02:54.810 --> 02:02:56.760
there are challenges in maintaining focus.

02:02:56.760 --> 02:02:59.120
This is very common for
people who have done sports,

02:02:59.120 --> 02:03:00.650
where there's a lot of
running into each other

02:03:00.650 --> 02:03:04.360
with your head like rugby
football, hockey, and so forth,

02:03:04.360 --> 02:03:06.150
but also people who have
experienced head blows

02:03:06.150 --> 02:03:08.460
or often overlooked is the fact that

02:03:08.460 --> 02:03:11.410
most traumatic head injury
is not actually from sports,

02:03:11.410 --> 02:03:14.130
even football it's from
things like construction work

02:03:14.130 --> 02:03:16.640
from high-impact work of that kind.

02:03:16.640 --> 02:03:18.560
So there does seem to be some efficacy

02:03:18.560 --> 02:03:21.763
of new Pepped and Racetams.
and things like it.

02:03:22.620 --> 02:03:25.530
It's an emerging area and
as I mentioned in the U.S.

02:03:25.530 --> 02:03:27.370
these things are sold over the counter.

02:03:27.370 --> 02:03:29.660
Again, you have to figure
out if it's right for you,

02:03:29.660 --> 02:03:32.900
but they are beginning
to show some promise,

02:03:32.900 --> 02:03:35.670
and I'm intrigued by
them because of the way

02:03:35.670 --> 02:03:37.700
that they tap into the cholinergic system,

02:03:37.700 --> 02:03:40.397
which is both directly involved in focus,

02:03:40.397 --> 02:03:42.430
and the ability to focus,

02:03:42.430 --> 02:03:45.790
but is also important for things related

02:03:45.790 --> 02:03:47.670
to age-related cognitive decline.

02:03:47.670 --> 02:03:51.320
So a decline in cholinergic
transmission or acetylcholine

02:03:51.320 --> 02:03:54.320
as we call it in the
brain is one of the things

02:03:54.320 --> 02:03:55.297
associated with cognitive decline

02:03:55.297 --> 02:03:58.400
and it does seem that increasing
cholinergic transmission

02:03:58.400 --> 02:04:00.420
can offset some of that cognitive decline

02:04:00.420 --> 02:04:03.280
and perhaps even more so in conditions

02:04:03.280 --> 02:04:06.310
such as vascular damage or
concussion to the brain.

02:04:06.310 --> 02:04:09.480
If you're interested in
atypical treatments for ADHD

02:04:10.860 --> 02:04:13.320
compounds or improve
focus and related themes,

02:04:13.320 --> 02:04:14.960
and you like reading about this stuff,

02:04:14.960 --> 02:04:16.520
there's an excellent review article

02:04:16.520 --> 02:04:18.220
that I can refer you to it's

02:04:18.220 --> 02:04:22.600
by Ahn et al, AHN it was published in 2016

02:04:22.600 --> 02:04:24.500
so it's a little bit behind the times,

02:04:25.647 --> 02:04:27.710
although it's surprisingly
comprehensive given that,

02:04:27.710 --> 02:04:32.550
which lines up all the various
drugs that I've discussed,

02:04:32.550 --> 02:04:34.590
Racetams., and Adderall and Ritalin,

02:04:34.590 --> 02:04:38.120
and various forms of dopaminergic agents

02:04:38.120 --> 02:04:40.640
and cholinergic agents
spells out whether or not

02:04:40.640 --> 02:04:43.360
they are sold over the
counter by prescription,

02:04:43.360 --> 02:04:45.230
and really lines them
up in all their effects,

02:04:45.230 --> 02:04:48.160
their drawbacks, et cetera.

02:04:48.160 --> 02:04:49.400
I'll refer you to that study.

02:04:49.400 --> 02:04:52.414
It's available in its full
length form online for free

02:04:52.414 --> 02:04:56.640
it's Hen et al the journal
is neuro plasticity,

02:04:56.640 --> 02:04:58.950
neural plasticity, 2016

02:04:58.950 --> 02:05:01.430
should be very easy to find
if you put those keywords in,

02:05:01.430 --> 02:05:02.680
and while it is a review,

02:05:02.680 --> 02:05:04.410
it is a very comprehensive review

02:05:04.410 --> 02:05:06.120
and if you're really into this stuff,

02:05:06.120 --> 02:05:08.650
and you also want to
learn a thing or two about

02:05:08.650 --> 02:05:11.480
how these things interact
with neurofeedback, et cetera,

02:05:11.480 --> 02:05:13.470
there's some information in there as well.

02:05:13.470 --> 02:05:15.570
I know I've already covered
a lot of information,

02:05:15.570 --> 02:05:18.520
but there is one more
category of technology

02:05:18.520 --> 02:05:22.560
for the treatment of ADHD
and for enhancement of focus

02:05:22.560 --> 02:05:26.030
in anyone that I would like to emphasize

02:05:26.030 --> 02:05:28.920
and that's transcranial
magnetic stimulation.

02:05:28.920 --> 02:05:31.980
Transcranial magnetic
stimulation also called TMS

02:05:31.980 --> 02:05:34.620
is achieving increasing
popularity nowadays

02:05:34.620 --> 02:05:38.410
for the treatment of all
sorts of neurologic conditions

02:05:38.410 --> 02:05:40.200
and psychiatric conditions.

02:05:40.200 --> 02:05:41.850
It is a non-invasive tool,

02:05:41.850 --> 02:05:45.520
it involves taking a coil
it's a device with a coil

02:05:45.520 --> 02:05:48.970
that's placed over particular
locations in the brain,

02:05:48.970 --> 02:05:53.220
and then sends magnetic
stimulation into the brain

02:05:53.220 --> 02:05:54.570
and it can actually pass through the skull

02:05:54.570 --> 02:05:56.550
without having to drill through the skull

02:05:56.550 --> 02:05:59.190
and nowadays can be used to both

02:05:59.190 --> 02:06:00.870
lower the amount of activity

02:06:00.870 --> 02:06:02.550
or increase the amount of activity

02:06:02.550 --> 02:06:04.740
in specific brain areas.

02:06:04.740 --> 02:06:09.740
It's spatial, precision is not remarkable.

02:06:09.840 --> 02:06:11.200
That doesn't mean it's not of use,

02:06:11.200 --> 02:06:16.200
but it is not a super
fine green tool, okay?

02:06:16.240 --> 02:06:19.460
It's not a canon, but
it's also not a needle.

02:06:19.460 --> 02:06:21.200
It is somewhere in between.

02:06:21.200 --> 02:06:23.850
It can direct the activity
of particular brain regions

02:06:23.850 --> 02:06:26.450
at particular depths and as I mentioned,

02:06:26.450 --> 02:06:28.450
it can increase or decrease that activity.

02:06:28.450 --> 02:06:29.490
So for instance,

02:06:29.490 --> 02:06:31.160
I've had a TMS coil placed on my head,

02:06:31.160 --> 02:06:33.930
not for therapeutic purposes, even it was,

02:06:33.930 --> 02:06:36.640
I wouldn't tell you, but rather just for,

02:06:36.640 --> 02:06:37.990
well, I'm a neuroscientist

02:06:37.990 --> 02:06:40.240
and I worked in a lab with
one for entertainment,

02:06:40.240 --> 02:06:42.790
exploratory purposes, please
don't do this at home.

02:06:44.120 --> 02:06:46.750
It was placed over my motor cortex,

02:06:46.750 --> 02:06:49.260
which generates voluntary action

02:06:49.260 --> 02:06:52.230
and it was a coil that at that time

02:06:52.230 --> 02:06:54.110
could only inhibit neurons

02:06:54.110 --> 02:06:56.670
and so what I was doing
as I was moving objects

02:06:56.670 --> 02:06:58.470
around on a table, just like I am now,

02:06:58.470 --> 02:07:00.330
it was actually a pencil, not a pen

02:07:00.330 --> 02:07:01.980
and I was tapping the pencil

02:07:01.980 --> 02:07:05.400
and then the TMS coil was turned
on and for the life of me,

02:07:05.400 --> 02:07:08.570
I could not move that pencil, okay?

02:07:08.570 --> 02:07:11.510
Because it was inhibiting
my upper motor neurons

02:07:11.510 --> 02:07:12.970
in the portion of my cortex

02:07:12.970 --> 02:07:15.590
that controls voluntary activity.

02:07:15.590 --> 02:07:16.960
As soon as the coil was turned off,

02:07:16.960 --> 02:07:19.940
I could return to
tapping the pencil again,

02:07:19.940 --> 02:07:23.180
nowadays it's possible
to stimulate motor cortex

02:07:23.180 --> 02:07:26.180
or any area of the brain
with some degree of precision

02:07:26.180 --> 02:07:29.550
that could create the impulse to move

02:07:29.550 --> 02:07:31.690
without actually making
the decision to move.

02:07:31.690 --> 02:07:34.810
So you can literally engage
certain neural circuits

02:07:34.810 --> 02:07:36.860
and therefore behaviors
and certain thought

02:07:36.860 --> 02:07:38.000
and emotional patterns

02:07:38.000 --> 02:07:40.436
by way of transcranial
magnetic stimulation.

02:07:40.436 --> 02:07:43.850
This has far reaching
and vast implications,

02:07:43.850 --> 02:07:46.030
as you can probably imagine

02:07:47.010 --> 02:07:50.750
in discussing ADHD with a
colleague that uses TMS,

02:07:50.750 --> 02:07:55.400
what they are doing is they
are taking the TMS coil

02:07:55.400 --> 02:07:59.270
to children and adults that have ADHD,

02:07:59.270 --> 02:08:01.950
and they're using it to
stimulate the portions

02:08:01.950 --> 02:08:04.750
of the prefrontal cortex
that we talked about earlier

02:08:04.750 --> 02:08:08.620
that engage task directed focused states.

02:08:08.620 --> 02:08:09.960
So rather than using a drug

02:08:09.960 --> 02:08:11.247
that generally increases dopamine,

02:08:11.247 --> 02:08:13.120
and some of the other chemicals involved

02:08:13.120 --> 02:08:17.310
there you using directed TMS
stimulation of the circuits

02:08:17.310 --> 02:08:20.490
and fortunately, I was
quite relieved to hear this,

02:08:20.490 --> 02:08:24.060
they are combining that with
a focused learning task.

02:08:24.060 --> 02:08:25.940
So they're literally
teaching the brain to learn

02:08:25.940 --> 02:08:28.810
in a noninvasive way, no drug at all

02:08:28.810 --> 02:08:31.590
and right now there are
experiments clinical trials

02:08:31.590 --> 02:08:34.110
going on, comparing TMS of this sort

02:08:34.110 --> 02:08:37.570
to the drug treatments of the
sort that we described earlier

02:08:37.570 --> 02:08:38.690
that engaged these circuits

02:08:38.690 --> 02:08:40.160
through pharmacologic mechanisms.

02:08:40.160 --> 02:08:42.719
So very exciting times for TMS,

02:08:42.719 --> 02:08:47.719
very exciting times for
pharmacology related to ADHD

02:08:48.060 --> 02:08:49.750
and for enhancing focus in general

02:08:49.750 --> 02:08:51.580
and when I say very exciting times,

02:08:51.580 --> 02:08:53.460
I mean, no drug is perfect,

02:08:53.460 --> 02:08:57.250
but the constellation of
drugs that's out there

02:08:57.250 --> 02:08:58.920
is getting much larger,

02:08:58.920 --> 02:09:01.320
but because they tap
into different aspects

02:09:01.320 --> 02:09:02.153
of their circuitry,

02:09:02.153 --> 02:09:04.060
I do think that we are well on our way

02:09:04.060 --> 02:09:06.870
to identifying the ideal
combinations of drug treatments,

02:09:06.870 --> 02:09:08.010
technological treatments,

02:09:08.010 --> 02:09:11.360
and behavioral paradigms
for increasing focus in both

02:09:11.360 --> 02:09:14.130
children and adults with ADHD.

02:09:14.130 --> 02:09:16.650
And as a final final point,

02:09:16.650 --> 02:09:18.980
I also want to mention
something about technologies

02:09:18.980 --> 02:09:22.140
that are making it harder
for all of us to focus,

02:09:22.140 --> 02:09:23.240
regardless of whether or not

02:09:23.240 --> 02:09:25.360
we have pre-existing ADHD or not.

02:09:25.360 --> 02:09:27.823
You can probably guess
where this is going.

02:09:28.800 --> 02:09:31.180
Everybody nowadays seems
to have a smartphone.

02:09:31.180 --> 02:09:33.250
I'm sure there are a few
individuals out there

02:09:33.250 --> 02:09:35.540
that don't have a smartphone.

02:09:35.540 --> 02:09:37.160
Nonetheless, most people have them.

02:09:37.160 --> 02:09:40.090
Most kids want one, as
soon as they can get them

02:09:40.090 --> 02:09:45.090
and they are small, they
grab our attention entirely.

02:09:45.910 --> 02:09:48.560
But within that small box of attention,

02:09:48.560 --> 02:09:51.860
there are millions of attentional windows

02:09:51.860 --> 02:09:53.160
scrolling by, right?

02:09:53.160 --> 02:09:55.170
So just because it's one
device that we look at

02:09:55.170 --> 02:09:56.800
does not mean that we are focused,

02:09:56.800 --> 02:09:58.630
we are focused on our phone,

02:09:58.630 --> 02:10:00.000
but because of the way,

02:10:00.000 --> 02:10:03.400
in which context switches
up so fast within the phone,

02:10:03.400 --> 02:10:06.430
it's thought that the
brain is struggling now

02:10:06.430 --> 02:10:09.540
to leave that rapid
turnover of context, right?

02:10:09.540 --> 02:10:12.190
Many, many shows, many,
many Instagram pages,

02:10:12.190 --> 02:10:14.230
many, many Twitter feeds
many, many websites.

02:10:14.230 --> 02:10:16.500
Basically the whole world,

02:10:16.500 --> 02:10:18.500
at least in virtual format is available

02:10:18.500 --> 02:10:20.160
within that small box.

02:10:20.160 --> 02:10:21.590
Unlike any other technology

02:10:21.590 --> 02:10:23.120
humans have ever dealt with before,

02:10:23.120 --> 02:10:25.370
even though there are trillions

02:10:25.370 --> 02:10:27.150
infinite number of bits of information

02:10:27.150 --> 02:10:29.280
in the actual physical world,

02:10:29.280 --> 02:10:30.530
your attentional window,

02:10:30.530 --> 02:10:32.740
that aperture of constriction

02:10:32.740 --> 02:10:34.910
and dilating that visual window

02:10:34.910 --> 02:10:36.620
is the way in which you cope with all that

02:10:36.620 --> 02:10:39.140
overwhelming information typically.

02:10:39.140 --> 02:10:40.640
Well within the phone,

02:10:40.640 --> 02:10:44.010
your visual aperture
is set to a given width

02:10:44.010 --> 02:10:45.040
it's about this big,

02:10:45.040 --> 02:10:46.740
typically the phone seem
to be getting bigger,

02:10:46.740 --> 02:10:48.970
but nonetheless, it's about that big

02:10:48.970 --> 02:10:51.130
and within there,

02:10:51.130 --> 02:10:54.600
your attentional window is
grabbing it near infinite

02:10:54.600 --> 02:10:57.300
number of bits of
information, colors, movies.

02:10:57.300 --> 02:10:59.120
If a picture is worth 1000 words,

02:10:59.120 --> 02:11:01.450
a movie is worth a billion pictures,

02:11:01.450 --> 02:11:03.540
the brain loves visual motion

02:11:03.540 --> 02:11:06.083
and so the question is,

02:11:07.040 --> 02:11:09.380
does that sort of interaction
on a regular basis

02:11:09.380 --> 02:11:12.010
lead to deficits in the types of attention

02:11:12.010 --> 02:11:13.610
that we need in order to perform well

02:11:13.610 --> 02:11:15.690
in work, in school,
relationships, et cetera

02:11:15.690 --> 02:11:19.200
and the short answer is
yes, it does appear so

02:11:19.200 --> 02:11:22.170
we are inducing a sort of ADHD

02:11:22.170 --> 02:11:25.120
and while the studies on this
are ongoing because prominent

02:11:25.120 --> 02:11:27.930
use of smartphones really
took off right around 2010

02:11:27.930 --> 02:11:32.930
and we're only in 2021
longstanding studies take time,

02:11:33.560 --> 02:11:36.910
which is essentially to say the
same thing as long standing.

02:11:36.910 --> 02:11:39.100
There are some studies
and one in particular

02:11:39.100 --> 02:11:39.933
that I'd like to highlight

02:11:39.933 --> 02:11:42.900
one was actually carried
out pretty early in 2014.

02:11:42.900 --> 02:11:46.080
This is a study that
explored smartphone use

02:11:46.080 --> 02:11:47.970
at the time they called
it mobile phone use,

02:11:47.970 --> 02:11:50.670
but smartphone use and inattention,

02:11:50.670 --> 02:11:54.820
difficulties in attending
in 7,102 adolescents

02:11:56.940 --> 02:11:58.020
that's a huge study,

02:11:58.020 --> 02:12:00.410
a population based cross-sectional study

02:12:01.300 --> 02:12:06.300
and you will be probably
surprised and somewhat dismayed

02:12:06.560 --> 02:12:10.070
to hear that in order
to avoid this decrease

02:12:10.070 --> 02:12:11.583
in attentional capacity,

02:12:12.420 --> 02:12:16.440
adolescents needed to use their smartphone

02:12:16.440 --> 02:12:19.290
for less than 60 minutes per day,

02:12:19.290 --> 02:12:23.010
in order to stay focused and
centered on their other tasks.

02:12:23.010 --> 02:12:24.530
Otherwise they started to really run

02:12:24.530 --> 02:12:26.410
into significant issues.

02:12:26.410 --> 02:12:28.610
So 60 minutes is not much,

02:12:28.610 --> 02:12:30.997
I've a feeling that most young people

02:12:30.997 --> 02:12:33.690
are using their phone more
than 60 minutes per day,

02:12:33.690 --> 02:12:35.170
I know I am.

02:12:35.170 --> 02:12:36.020
I think for adults,

02:12:36.020 --> 02:12:40.660
the number's probably higher
meaning if you're an adult,

02:12:40.660 --> 02:12:43.770
I'm going to just extrapolate
from what I read in this study.

02:12:43.770 --> 02:12:47.110
It seems that probably two
hours a day on the phone

02:12:47.110 --> 02:12:49.760
would be the upper limit beyond which

02:12:49.760 --> 02:12:51.440
you would probably experience

02:12:51.440 --> 02:12:54.063
pretty severe attentional deficits.

02:12:54.960 --> 02:12:57.910
I'm a big fan of Cal Newport
who wrote the book "Deep work."

02:12:57.910 --> 02:12:59.267
He's also written an excellent book,

02:12:59.267 --> 02:13:00.390
"A world without Email."

02:13:00.390 --> 02:13:02.460
I've never met him, but I'm
a huge admirer of his work

02:13:02.460 --> 02:13:05.160
and I will paraphrase
something that he said

02:13:05.160 --> 02:13:07.420
far more eloquently than I ever could,

02:13:07.420 --> 02:13:12.200
which is that the brain does
not do well with constant

02:13:12.200 --> 02:13:15.610
context switching, meaning it can do it,

02:13:15.610 --> 02:13:18.620
but it diminishes our
capacity to do meaningful work

02:13:18.620 --> 02:13:20.270
of any other kind.

02:13:20.270 --> 02:13:24.150
And so Cal, as I understand is very

02:13:24.150 --> 02:13:25.550
he's our computer science professor

02:13:25.550 --> 02:13:26.800
at Georgetown, by the way,

02:13:26.800 --> 02:13:29.890
is very structured and very disciplined

02:13:29.890 --> 02:13:32.313
in his avoidance of cell phone use.

02:13:33.270 --> 02:13:34.850
I think we're all striving to do that.

02:13:34.850 --> 02:13:36.100
I'm not here to tell you what to do,

02:13:36.100 --> 02:13:39.520
but I think whether or
not you have ADHD or not,

02:13:39.520 --> 02:13:42.930
if you're an adolescent
limiting your smartphone use

02:13:42.930 --> 02:13:45.360
to 60 minutes per day or less

02:13:45.360 --> 02:13:49.920
and if you are an adult to
two hours per day or less

02:13:49.920 --> 02:13:54.140
is going to be among the
very best ways to maintain,

02:13:54.140 --> 02:13:56.640
just to maintain your ability to focus

02:13:56.640 --> 02:14:01.360
at whatever level you can
now and as I always say,

02:14:01.360 --> 02:14:03.040
most of the things that we get recognized

02:14:03.040 --> 02:14:05.900
for in life success in
life, in every endeavor,

02:14:05.900 --> 02:14:08.905
whether or not it's school
relationships, sport,

02:14:08.905 --> 02:14:12.810
creative works of any kind
